acted text from Reuters Connect page titled \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nPage heading: \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nCaption text: \\\"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\\\"\\n\\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 AP/DOJ authentication-limit report in context\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\n[defendant] DS-1 AP/DOJ source-chain and authentication limits\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] SDNY May 6, 2026 Tartaglione unsealing order - relevant extracted text (ev_0ed0ef50e84e_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-0ed0ef50e84e)\\nSource: https://www.nysd.uscourts.gov/sites/default/files/2026-05/16cr832%20-%20Tartaglione%20Order%20-%2026.5.6.pdf\\nSHA-256: `0ed0ef50e84e5f90a63aeefcb840f628038958b10acf229c44b4babea0c133e9`\\nBytes: 2992\\nRelevance: Official court source for public release/unsealing. It proves the court granted access to the note and identifies it as a suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione attorneys; it also shows the order was about public access, not authenticity.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] PBS/AP May 6-7, 2026 report on Epstein note release - relevant extracted text (ev_757899113d89_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-757899113d89)\\nSource: https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/judge-releases-note-that-cellmate-says-he-found-after-epsteins-suspected-suicide-attempt\\nSHA-256: `757899113d8967676e74909d141f7d97d4735bd8d75a4af34fb3950b18d871e1`\\nBytes: 2552\\nRelevance: Corroborates that the note was publicly reported before May 8, 2026; identifies Judge Karas release, NYT petition, Tartaglione discovery claim, note language supporting final-message intent, and adverse uncertainty about authorship and government-report omissions.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 6, 2026 report on alleged Epstein suicide note - relevant extracted text (ev_be7a5dd8c524_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-be7a5dd8c524)\\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\\nSHA-256: `be7a5dd8c524bf01aaffc12daeeedace9153fd057fc82c3ada197c2b30db71ce`\\nBytes: 2014\\nRelevance: Independent mainstream public reporting before the May 8 deadline; describes first public availability, attributes image to U.S. District Judge/Southern District of New York, quotes note language, and preserves authorship caveats.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Reuters Connect May 6, 2026 image-caption record for Epstein note (ev_58561d19c453_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-58561d19c453)\\nSource: https://www.reutersconnect.com/item/document-described-as-a-suicide-note-purportedly-written-by-the-late-jeffrey-epstein/dGFnOnJldXRlcnMuY29tLDIwMjY6bmV3c21sX1JDMlQzTEFMMEM2Ng\\nSHA-256: `58561d19c4537e7f3ade428fefe955b34c55ca688a331faa72187770ee5c8716`\\nBytes: 1360\\nRelevance: Near-primary image-caption record from Reuters/SDNY handout. It directly describes the publicly released document image, includes the key goodbye line, dates the release to May 6, 2026, and identifies the source as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] AP May 7, 2026 report: DOJ seeing Epstein note for first time and authentication limits (ev_5aa56aab2530_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-5aa56aab2530)\\nSource: https://apnews.com/article/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note-5297f49736e625a06d0db3c7b737b997\\nSHA-256: `5aa56aab25302158d1be6b80426ed4d517ee436cea958297c34e648148db2bca`\\nBytes: 2780\\nRelevance: Defense evidence on provenance, custody, and authentication. It reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, that the note came through an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, that it was in a court vault since 2021, and that DOJ lawyers involved in sealed proceedings could not disclose anything due to privilege restrictions.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Source search and capture ledger\\nBefore filing, plaintiff checked the current record and evidence list, reviewed the defendant opening, and targeted the missing source classes identified by the packet: official SDNY court material, the public image/caption record, and independent mainstream reporting. Searches used exact phrases including the note's reported goodbye line, Tartaglione/Karas/SDNY terms, and source-specific Reuters/PBS/Guardian queries. The official SDNY PDF was downloaded locally on 2026-06-30T04:33:49Z, size 128,992 bytes, sha256 7225441cb802084e2b9485ebc2c6d246fbfa08e109fe650cb14f445dc4745ca0; local pdftotext was unavailable, so a relevant text extraction was admitted instead. Reuters Connect metadata, PBS/AP, and Guardian extracts were admitted. Remaining gaps: no binary PDF exhibit, no licensed Reuters image download, no full NYT article capture, and no official authentication finding. These gaps affect actual authorship weight but do not defeat the reporting-standard proposition.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-search and evidence ledger\\nDefense re-scanned the record and read the four new plaintiff evidence extracts. Targeted investigation checked direct AP/DOJ source-chain reporting, NYT authentication follow-up leads, and media mirrors. The defense submitted the direct AP extraction as DB-1 because it preserved the strongest provenance and authentication limits: DOJ never had the note, it had not been authenticated, DOJ was seeing it for the first time, and any DOJ lawyers in sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings could not disclose protected material. Remaining unresolved gaps: no full NYT authentication article, no binary/unprocessed note image, no custodian affidavit, and no handwriting or official authorship finding.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T05:02:11.941771357Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":892433,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":17,\"version\":26}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","after_version":26,"case_id":"arb-ex08-20260630042402","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C4","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C4\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff's case is about the precise wording of the proposition, not about proving beyond doubt that Jeffrey Epstein actually wrote the document. The question is whether, by May 8, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a note or message had been made publicly available and had been credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. On the current packet, the answer is more likely than not yes.\n\nThe market rule preserved in the packet is important. It does not demand a definitive handwriting authentication, a government finding, or a single official resolution source. It asks for a message or note that was publicly available, credibly reported as Epstein's, and treated as a suicide note/final-message equivalent, with resolution by consensus credible reporting. That framing matters because the public record is cautious but not empty: the packet's reporting map identifies Reuters, NPR/AP, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times leads around the same court release.\n\nThe evidence we have now already shows the core chronology. A federal judge, Kenneth Karas of the Southern District of New York, unsealed or released a one-page note connected to Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's former cellmate. The reporting captured in the packet places that release before the May 8 deadline. Reuters described a document released by the judge as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein and quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye. NPR/AP reported that the judge unsealed the one-page note after a New York Times petition and quoted the same goodbye language. BBC and Guardian reporting likewise described an alleged or purported suicide note, publicly released by a federal judge, and described its contents in terms consistent with a final communication.\n\nThose reports are not marginal internet rumor. They are mainstream, named news organizations reporting on a court-unsealed document. The note's public availability is therefore the strongest element: multiple reports describe the court release itself before the deadline, and the Polymarket packet separately records that the market page understood the disputed question as the May 8 grouped market.\n\nThe hard issue is weight, not existence. The same packet preserves the caveats. The court did not vouch for authenticity. Several outlets used words like alleged or purported. NPR, BBC, and Guardian noted they had not independently verified authorship, and NPR/AP reported uncertainty about who wrote the note. The official-source file says the packet does not yet include the SDNY docket PDF, the unsealing order PDF, or the note image as local official exhibits. Those gaps should make the council cautious about any argument that Epstein's authorship has been conclusively proved.\n\nBut the proposition does not require conclusive proof of authorship. It requires that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Responsible hedging in credible reports does not erase credibility; it often demonstrates it. The reports identified a court release, a claimed source chain through Tartaglione and his lawyers, and the note text. That is enough at opening to frame the plaintiff's burden as a preponderance question: did credible public reporting, before May 8, make available and describe the note in the qualifying way? The packet points strongly toward yes.\n\nIntent is similar. The note need not be a formal, signed will or declaration. The rule allows a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, together with the context of Epstein's suspected July 2019 attempt and later death, is why credible outlets characterized it as a suicide note or alleged suicide note. The defense may argue the short, unsigned text is ambiguous. That is a fair limitation, but it does not defeat the more modest proposition that it was credibly reported as such.\n\nIn later evidentiary phases, the decisive documents should be added directly: the SDNY unsealing order and any released note image or court handout, the full Reuters/AP/Guardian/NYT materials, and the best adverse materials showing the limits of authentication and chain of custody. For now, the opening theory is straightforward: the record already shows a public court release before the deadline and a consensus of credible reporting that treated the document as a purported Epstein suicide or final-message note. The remaining disputes affect weight; they do not change the plaintiff's burden from preponderance into certainty.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the whole proposition, not merely that a provocative document was released by a court before May 8.\n\nThe record likely supports one element. The packet describes a public release or unsealing connected to Judge Kenneth Karas and the Tartaglione criminal case before the listed deadline. We do not need to pretend otherwise. But the market rule asks for more: a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The packet itself flags why those added elements are not established on this record.\n\nStart with provenance. The official-source packet says the local record does not contain the SDNY docket entry, unsealing order, or the released note image as a primary court exhibit. More importantly, it says the public reporting preserved here reports that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide its intent. Reuters, as summarized in the packet, reported that Judge Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody. That is a public-access ruling, not proof that the note was Epstein's.\n\nThe reporting evidence has the same problem. The packet's strongest plaintiff sources repeatedly use limiting words: purported, alleged, described as, said to have been found. NPR says it had not independently verified authenticity and adds a material DOJ limitation: the note had not yet been authenticated and this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. BBC likewise says it had not verified the note was written by Epstein and reports that authorities had not commented. Guardian says it had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. Those caveats are not incidental. They go directly to the proposition's phrase \"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nIntent is also unresolved. The packet quotes language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also preserves the rest of the reported text: complaints about being investigated, references to old charges, and emotional language about crying and not being worth it. The BBC summary says the note was only seven lines and left uncertainty over its purported meaning. A short, unsigned, unauthenticated text can be later characterized as a suicide note without having been shown to be intended as one. The rule includes final message or equivalent communication, but it still requires intent, not merely a news label attached after release.\n\nThe plaintiff will argue that consensus credible reporting is enough and that the rule does not require conclusive authentication. That is partly right but incomplete. The standard is preponderance, not certainty, and the source rule is credible reporting, not an official government determination. But credible reporting of uncertainty is still uncertainty. When the same credible reports say they cannot verify authorship, that DOJ had not authenticated it, and that the judge did not assess custody, the council should not convert cautious reporting into affirmative proof.\n\nThe current packet is best understood as a roadmap, not a completed proof. It identifies the sources that matter: the court order and docket material, the released note image, the full reporting from Reuters, NPR, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times, and especially any authentication follow-up. Those materials may eventually show whether there was enough consensus to resolve yes. But at opening, the defense theory is that the admitted packet proves a public dispute over an alleged note, while leaving the decisive links missing: authorship, chain of custody, and intent. If those links remain missing, the proposition should not be found proved by a preponderance.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the admitted record now proves the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nStart with the governing condition. PX-1 states the market would resolve yes if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication, was made publicly available by the listed date, and that the resolution source would be a consensus of credible reporting. The rule does not require a handwriting trial, a DOJ authentication letter, or an official source as the only path. It asks whether there was credible public reporting of the qualifying note by May 8, 2026.\n\nPublic availability is established. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, is an official court source. Judge Karas described the requested item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The order granted the Times' request to unseal the Note and held that it was a judicial document subject to public access. PX-5 then supplies the Reuters Connect image-caption record: a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye was seen after release by Judge Karas in New York City on May 6, 2026, with the source identified as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters. PX-6 and PX-7 independently report the same public release on May 6, before the May 8 deadline.\n\nCredible reporting of Epstein authorship is also established, in the exact qualified sense the proposition uses. PX-5 describes the document as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein. PX-6 reports that Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found the note after Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and that Karas ordered its release after the Times sought unsealing. PX-7 reports a federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein and identifies the alleged note image as from the United States district judge/Southern District of New York. These are not anonymous posts or market chatter; they are an official court order plus Reuters metadata, AP/PBS, and Guardian reporting.\n\nIntent is satisfied by both text and reporting context. PX-5 identifies the key line: \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.\" PX-6 reports the same language and the surrounding statements, including \"NO FUN\" and \"NOT WORTH IT!!\" PX-7 likewise quotes the goodbye language and describes the release as an alleged suicide note. The rule allows not only a formal suicide note but also a final message or equivalent communication. A short note saying it is a treat to choose one's time to say goodbye, reported in connection with Epstein's suspected suicide attempt and later death, easily crosses the preponderance threshold for being credibly reported as a suicide/final-message equivalent.\n\nThe defense is right about one thing: the record does not conclusively authenticate the note as Epstein's handwriting. The plaintiff does not need to hide that. PX-3 and the newly admitted sources preserve the limitations. PX-4 is a public-access order, not a handwriting finding. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports, and that Epstein had reportedly accused Tartaglione. PX-7 says the note lacks a signature and that Guardian had not independently verified authorship. Those caveats would matter if the proposition asked, \"Did Epstein actually write an authenticated suicide note?\" It does not.\n\nThe actual proposition asks whether a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, and whether it had been made public by the deadline. Hedged words like alleged and purported are not fatal under that standard; they are how responsible outlets report an attributed document whose authenticity has not been finally adjudicated. The credible-reporting consensus is that a court-released document, sourced to SDNY/Reuters handout and reported by AP/PBS and Guardian, was publicly available on May 6 and was described as an Epstein suicide note or alleged suicide note.\n\nThe missing links therefore reduce certainty about actual authorship, not the reporting-standard proposition. By May 8, the public had the court release and mainstream reporting describing the note in qualifying terms. On this record, yes is more likely than no.\n\n[defendant] Council members, after plaintiff's new evidence, the defense does not contest the easy part: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. The question is whether the record proves the qualifying proposition as written: a note credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The record still falls short.\n\nThe plaintiff's best evidence proves public access, not authenticity. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, describes the item as an alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The court's legal holding was that the Note was subject to the presumption of public access because it had been submitted in connection with a Curcio hearing in Tartaglione's case. That explains why the public could see it. It does not decide who wrote it, whether its custody was reliable, or what the writer intended.\n\nThe source chain is unusually weak for a preponderance finding on authorship. The asserted chain is not Epstein to jail officials to investigators. It is Tartaglione, a convicted murderer and Epstein's former cellmate, saying he found a note in a book, then giving it to his lawyers, after which it became part of sealed attorney-client/conflict proceedings in Tartaglione's case. DB-1, the direct AP report, adds the central official limitation: DOJ's explanation was that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. AP also reports that if DOJ lawyers saw material in the sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings, they were barred from disclosing it. That is not just a missing authentication stamp; it is a source-chain problem.\n\nThe mainstream reports do not create the consensus plaintiff needs. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in the government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's recent files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. PX-5, the Reuters Connect caption, is useful proof that an image/caption circulated, but it expressly calls the image third-party supplied and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version elsewhere. A caption saying \"purportedly written\" is not a finding that credible reporting established authorship.\n\nPlaintiff says hedged words like alleged and purported are normal reporting practice. Sometimes they are. Here they are doing real evidentiary work. Every key source preserved in the record either avoids endorsing authorship or reports affirmative reasons for doubt: no signature, no authentication, DOJ had not seen it, no appearance in official Epstein-death reports, no appearance in DOJ's files release, and a chain originating with Tartaglione. The proposition uses the phrase \"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\" On this record, the credible reporting consensus is that a note was claimed or described as Epstein's, while authorship remained unresolved.\n\nIntent is no stronger. The reported text includes a line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also includes complaints about investigations, old charges, crying, \"NO FUN,\" and \"NOT WORTH IT.\" DB-1 describes the note as short, hard to decipher in places, and not authenticated. PX-6 and PX-7 connect it to Epstein's July 2019 suspected attempt, but the same record says Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, later recanted, and was placed briefly on suicide watch before being downgraded. A later news label of \"suicide note\" cannot substitute for proof that this unsigned ambiguous document was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\n\nThis is not an argument for certainty as the standard. It is an argument for applying all elements of the rule. The plaintiff has shown public availability and public controversy. It has shown that several credible outlets responsibly repeated a characterization while preserving doubts. It has not shown that the consensus of credible reporting made it more likely than not that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying suicide/final-message communication.\n\nThe council should weigh plaintiff's exhibits for what they actually prove. PX-4 proves unsealing. PX-5 proves a Reuters/SDNY handout caption. PX-6 and PX-7 prove timely public reporting, but also preserve the core doubts. DB-1 gives the most direct official-source-chain limit: DOJ never had it, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. On the complete record, the proposition remains unproved by a preponderance.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense argument proves too much by quietly changing the question.\n\nThe proposition does not ask whether a court, DOJ, or handwriting expert finally authenticated Epstein's authorship. It asks whether, by May 8, a publicly available note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. That is why PX-1 makes consensus credible reporting the resolution source. The defense's evidence attacks a different proposition: actual authorship certainty.\n\nPX-R1 is useful, but not in the way the defense claims. It says DOJ never had the note, that it had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. Those facts explain why careful outlets used words like alleged and purported. They do not erase the fact that AP, Reuters Connect, Guardian, and the SDNY order all publicly described the same court-released item in the qualifying terms before the deadline.\n\nIndeed, PX-R1 confirms several plaintiff points. It says the note was made public, that The New York Times petitioned Judge Karas to release it, that Judge Karas agreed, and that DOJ did not object. It repeats Tartaglione's claim that he found the handwritten note after Epstein was found in their cell with a bedsheet around his neck. It gives the reported text, including choosing the time to say goodbye. That is not proof against credible reporting; it is another credible report that the note existed, was released, and was being publicly reported in the suicide-note frame.\n\nThe defense says the source chain is weak because it runs through Tartaglione and his lawyers. That would be decisive if the question required the council to find, as a historical fact, that Epstein wrote it. But the actual standard is whether the note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Qualified reporting is still reporting. When multiple mainstream sources identify a court-released document as a purported or alleged Epstein suicide note, while openly preserving authentication caveats, the word \"purported\" does not nullify credibility. It defines the level of claim being credibly reported.\n\nThe same is true of intent. The defense isolates ambiguity in the short text, but the admitted reports did not label a random note after the fact. They described a document found after a suspected jail suicide attempt, released by a federal judge, containing the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye. Under a rule that includes final message or equivalent communication, that is enough for credible reporting of intent by a preponderance.\n\nSo the council can accept every defense caveat and still find for plaintiff. No official authentication; no signature; source-chain limits; DOJ first saw it in 2026. Those are reasons not to overstate actual authorship. They are not reasons to deny the narrower proposition that, by May 8, a publicly available note had been credibly reported as a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The record satisfies that proposition.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal says the defense is demanding actual-authorship certainty. That is not our position. The rule does not require a handwriting trial. But it does require more than credible reporting that someone claimed, labeled, or captioned a document as an alleged Epstein suicide note.\n\nPX-1 asks whether a qualifying note was written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, with credible reporting as the resolution source. The phrase \"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein\" cannot mean \"credibly reported to have been alleged or purported to be written by Epstein\" no matter how weak the source chain is. Otherwise the authorship requirement vanishes.\n\nThat is why DB-1/PX-R1 matters. Plaintiff treats it as harmless context for cautious wording. It is more than that. AP reports the government's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits on any DOJ lawyers in those proceedings. Those facts bear directly on whether the reporting consensus established Epstein authorship, not merely whether conclusive proof was absent.\n\nThe same point applies to intent. A line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the record also shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned document with grievance language and a disputed jail incident involving Tartaglione. The public reports responsibly used the suicide-note frame while preserving that uncertainty. That is not the same as a preponderance showing that the note was intended as a suicide note or final message.\n\nSo the defense is not asking the council to ignore credible reporting. We ask the council to read it accurately. The consensus is: a court released a document before May 8; credible outlets reported it as alleged or purported; and the same record preserved serious authorship, custody, and intent caveats. That proves public availability of a disputed document. It does not prove the full qualifying proposition by a preponderance.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition should be found true by a preponderance.\n\nThe defense ultimately concedes the first and most concrete element: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. That concession is compelled by the record. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, shows Judge Karas granted access to the Note. PX-5, the Reuters Connect/SDNY handout caption, dates the released document image to May 6, 2026. PX-6 and PX-7 report the release the same day. There is no serious timing dispute left.\n\nThe real dispute is what level of certainty the proposition requires. The defense asks you to treat missing official authentication as fatal. But PX-1 does not make authentication the test. It sets a reporting-standard market: the source is consensus credible reporting, and the operative phrase here is that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\n\nThat standard is satisfied. PX-4 identifies the court-filed item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. PX-5 describes the released image as a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, described as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein, sourced to U.S. District Court/SDNY handout via Reuters. PX-6, AP/PBS, reports the public release, the Tartaglione discovery account, and the same goodbye language. PX-7, Guardian, independently reports the federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein, quotes the same text, and identifies the image as from the Southern District of New York.\n\nThat is not one stray allegation. It is an official court-access order plus Reuters image metadata and two independent mainstream reports, all before the deadline, all describing the same public document in substantially the same qualifying frame.\n\nThe defense's best contrary evidence, DB-1/PX-R1, is important but not dispositive. It says DOJ never had the note, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. It explains why the reports used careful words like alleged and purported. It does not erase the reports. In fact, it confirms the public release, the New York Times petition, Judge Karas's agreement, DOJ's non-objection, Tartaglione's discovery claim, and the note language.\n\nSo the council can accept every caveat and still answer yes. No signature; no official authentication; unclear actual authorship; source-chain limits through Tartaglione and his lawyers. Those are reasons to avoid saying \"Epstein definitely wrote it.\" The proposition does not ask for that. It asks whether the note had been publicly available and credibly reported as Epstein's suicide/final-message note. The record shows that it had.\n\nIntent is proved at the same reporting-standard level. The note's reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, its connection to Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and repeated public characterization as a suicide note or alleged suicide note are enough for a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The defense can point to ambiguity in the short text, but preponderance does not require eliminating ambiguity; it requires the more likely reading of the admitted record.\n\nIf the rule had required official authentication, the defense would have the stronger case. But that is not the rule. Under the actual wording and the evidence admitted here, the plaintiff has shown public availability by May 8 and a consensus of credible, qualified reporting that the document was a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The proposition is more likely true than false.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the final record proves one thing clearly: a document was publicly released before May 8. The defense has never needed to deny that. The proposition, however, asks for more. It asks whether a message or note had been made public and had been credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. Plaintiff has not carried that full burden.\n\nThe best way to see the gap is to compare plaintiff's closing formulation to the actual rule. Plaintiff closes by saying the record shows a publicly available note was credibly reported as a \"purported Epstein suicide/final-message note.\" But \"reported as purported\" is not the proposition. The proposition requires credible reporting that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying communication. The word \"purported\" matters because the sources used it to preserve uncertainty, not to resolve it.\n\nThe record evidence repeatedly stops short of plaintiff's needed inference. PX-4 is an official court-access order, but it describes an alleged note purportedly authored by Epstein and decides public access, not authorship, custody, or intent. PX-5 is a Reuters Connect caption for a third-party supplied, Reuters-processed image; it confirms circulation and a caption, not authenticity. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether Epstein wrote it.\n\nDB-1/PX-R1 is the strongest limiting evidence. AP reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits from sealed proceedings. That is not a minor caveat. It is the central provenance problem.\n\nIntent is likewise not proved by a preponderance. The line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the same record shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned note with grievance language, a disputed jail incident, and no authentication. Labeling that document a suicide note in headlines or captions does not establish that it was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\n\nThe defense is not asking for certainty or an official authentication requirement. We are asking the council to enforce all words of the proposition. Credible reporting can be the resolution source, but the reporting here is credible precisely because it preserves the unresolved issues: alleged, purported, unclear author, no signature, not verified, not in government death reports, not in DOJ files, not authenticated, and first seen by DOJ only after release.\n\nSo the right finding is narrow and faithful to the record: by May 8, a disputed document was publicly available and credibly reported as an alleged or purported Epstein suicide note. That is not enough. The full proposition remains more likely unproved than proved, and the council should answer no.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and May 8 market record\n# Polymarket market record\n\nCaptured for case preparation on 2026-05-12.\n\n## Real market link\n\nCanonical event page:\nhttps://polymarket.com/event/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\n\nPolymarket Gamma API endpoints captured under `etc/source-captures/`:\n\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-event-slug.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events/slug/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-events-query.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-8.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-31.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-next-data-relevant.json` — sanitized relevant `__NEXT_DATA__` extract.\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — page/API text extract.\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — sanitized relevant HTML extract. Full page HTML was not retained because the page includes unnecessary discussion/profile data.\n\n## Event metadata from Polymarket Gamma API\n\n- Event id: `435920`\n- Ticker/slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by`\n- Title: `Epstein suicide note released by...?`\n- Start date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.609296Z`\n- Creation date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.60929Z`\n- Event end date: `2026-05-31T00:00:00Z`\n- Active: `true`\n- Closed: `false`\n- Archived: `false`\n- Restricted: `true`\n- Captured volume: about `13373621.098375008`\n- Captured open interest: about `8163953.4680470005`\n- Event metadata context captured by Polymarket on 2026-05-12 stated that a U.S. District Judge in New York unsealed a purported suicide note attributed to Jeffrey Epstein on May 7, 2026, but also described authenticity and intent doubts. This platform context is preserved as market metadata, not as independent proof of the proposition.\n\n## Exact official market rule text\n\nThe Polymarket page and Gamma API expose this description:\n\n> This market will resolve to “Yes” if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, is made publicly available by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n>\n> A qualifying note must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and have been intended to be a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\n>\n> A qualifying message or note may be made widely available to the public by any means, regardless of whether it is released officially, leaked, or otherwise disclosed.\n>\n> The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Market at issue for this arbitration\n\nPrimary disputed market:\n\n- Market id: `2128535`\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 8?`\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8`\n- Condition id: `0x5e5482b1e2afa7bed0b9a0c3c8ad33a83dd6cc6d649666cdf1977be64c42c82a`\n- Question id: `0x5ca4d636407564494e9149eb951896ff88923cef8d24c137707e4cff84b4d878`\n- Group item title: `May 8`\n- Outcomes: `[\"Yes\", \"No\"]`\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\"0.0005\", \"0.9995\"]`\n- Active: `true`\n- Closed: `false`\n- Accepting orders: `true`\n- UMA resolution status in API: `disputed`\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]`\n- Page-visible status captured from HTML/readable extraction: `Outcome proposed: Yes`; `Disputed`; `Outcome proposed: No`; `Disputed`; `Final review`.\n\nThe API field `endDateIso` is `2026-05-31` because the event contains both May 8 and May 31 grouped markets. For the May 8 market, the listed date in the market question and group item is May 8. The arbitration proposition therefore uses May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\n## Other grouped market preserved for context\n\nSecondary grouped market, not the disputed condition tested here:\n\n- Market id: `2128536`\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 31?`\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31`\n- Condition id: `0x6bf3aa7d5186804e967e1e4737c896778f688e6dafdd0a1b659a4a07bf27d663`\n- Group item title: `May 31`\n- Outcomes: `[\"Yes\", \"No\"]`\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\"0.145\", \"0.855\"]`\n- Active: `true`\n- Closed: `false`\n- Accepting orders: `true`\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[]`\n\n## Arbitration framing\n\nThe arbitration does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any market participant was correct. It asks the factual condition directly: whether the qualifying note/message had been publicly available by the May 8 listed deadline under the rule words.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Initial primary/near-primary reporting map\n# Primary and near-primary evidence map\n\nThis is a minimal open-record source map, not a closed-record exhibit packet.\n\n## Reuters\n\nURL: https://www.reuters.com/world/us/new-york-judge-releases-purported-epstein-suicide-note-2026-05-07/\n\nCaptured excerpt:\n\n> May 6 (Reuters) - A federal judge on Wednesday released a document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein and including the line: \"It is a treat to be able to choose one’s time to say goodbye.\"\n>\n> The handwritten note was said to have been found by his former jail cellmate, convicted murderer and ex‑police officer Nicholas Tartaglione. U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas, who oversaw the Tartaglione case, released the note after a request by The New York Times, which reported its existence last week.\n>\n> The judge found no legal reason to keep it under seal. But nor did he vouch for the note's authenticity, nor assess its chain of custody.\n\nReuters also quoted the note text as released in the court file:\n\n> \"They investigated me for month - Found NOTHING!!! So 15 year old charges resulted,” the note says, according to an image of it released in the court file. \"It is a treat to be able to choose ones time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Burst out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\n## NPR\n\nURL: https://www.npr.org/2026/05/07/nx-s1-5814808/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note\n\nCaptured excerpt:\n\n> District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from the New York Times, which reported on its existence last week.\n>\n> NPR has not independently verified the authenticity of the note. The five sentences on a sheet of lined paper read in part: \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do — Bust out cryin!! NO FUN — NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nNPR also reported a material authentication limitation:\n\n> The Department of Justice told NPR over email on Thursday that the note has not yet been authenticated, adding, \"this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well.\"\n\n## BBC\n\nURL: https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cd7pd0rqwreo\n\nCaptured excerpt:\n\n> A US judge has ordered the release of a document purported to be a suicide note written by convicted sex offender Jeffrey Epstein a month before his death.\n>\n> A copy of the handwritten note unsealed on Wednesday mentions a months-long investigation that \"found nothing\", and says \"it is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye\".\n>\n> The BBC has not verified that the note was written by Epstein, and US authorities have not commented.\n\nBBC also reported:\n\n> The note amounts to only seven lines of text, leaving uncertainty over its purported meaning.\n\n## Guardian\n\nURL: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\n\nCaptured excerpt:\n\n> A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\n>\n> Epstein’s cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, Nicholas Tartaglione, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before he was eventually found dead in his jail cell.\n>\n> The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return the Guardian’s request for comment.\n\n## Notes for advocates\n\nThe strongest pro-demonstrated path is that multiple credible outlets reported public release before May 8, described the document as a purported/alleged suicide note, quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, and identified a federal judge/court-file release.\n\nThe strongest not-demonstrated path is that those same outlets used hedging language, reported lack of independent verification or official authentication, and left uncertainty about whether the note was intended as a suicide note rather than another communication later characterized as one.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Initial official-source limitations map\n# Official source record\n\n## Market-specified resolution source\n\nThe Polymarket rule specifies no government docket, agency, publisher, or single official source. The exact source rule is:\n\n> The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Official public-record materials identified during minimal case setup\n\nThis packet is for an open-record/search-enabled run. I did not build a closed-record evidence packet. The public record identified during setup indicates that U.S. District Judge Kenneth M. Karas of the Southern District of New York unsealed a one-page note in connection with the Nicholas Tartaglione criminal case, after a New York Times request.\n\nLocal source capture of the court PDF/order is not included. The available captured public reporting says:\n\n- BBC reported that Judge Karas ordered release of the document, that the note was accompanied by a May 2021 letter submitted by former Tartaglione lawyer John A. Wieder, and that Karas wrote that public access to the note promotes accountability and public confidence in the administration of justice.\n- Reuters reported that Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody.\n- NPR reported that District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from The New York Times.\n\n## Official-source limitations\n\n- The source rule does not require an official release. It permits a qualifying note to be made public officially, by leak, or by other disclosure.\n- The local packet does not contain the SDNY docket entry, order, or note image as a primary court PDF. Attorneys in the open-record run should search for those documents.\n- Public reporting preserved here states that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide intent.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 SDNY May 6 unsealing order extraction\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\n\nCaption and opening: \"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\"\n\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\"\n\nBackground: \"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\"\n\nThe Times request: \"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\"\n\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\n\nPublic-access analysis: \"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\"\n\nThe order further concludes: \"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\"\n\nAnd: \"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\"\n\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Reuters Connect SDNY handout caption metadata\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nPage heading: \"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nCaption text: \"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\"\n\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-6 PBS/AP May 6-7 report extraction\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\n\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\n\nHeadline: \"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\"\n\nThe article reports: \"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\"\n\nIt reports that \"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\"\n\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\n\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\" and says it continued, \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye,\" followed by \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\" The article says the note concludes: \"NO FUN\" and \"NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\"\n\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-7 Guardian May 6 report extraction\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\n\nHeadline/subhead: \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\"; \"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\"\n\nThe article reports: \"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\"\n\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\n\nThe article's image caption identifies: \"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\"\n\nThe article quotes the note: \"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\" and \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \"The note does not include a signature.\" It also states: \"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\n\n[defendant] DB-1 AP/DOJ authentication and source-chain limits\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\n\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\"\n\nIt states: \"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\"\n\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\n\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\n\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\n\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\n\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\"; \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye\"; \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\"; and \"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\n\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\n\n[defendant] DB-2 SDNY order shows public-access ruling, alleged/purported framing\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\n\nCaption and opening: \"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\"\n\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\"\n\nBackground: \"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\"\n\nThe Times request: \"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\"\n\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\n\nPublic-access analysis: \"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\"\n\nThe order further concludes: \"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\"\n\nAnd: \"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\"\n\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\n\n[defendant] DB-3 PBS/AP preserves uncertainty and government-report omissions\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\n\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\n\nHeadline: \"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\"\n\nThe article reports: \"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\"\n\nIt reports that \"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\"\n\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\n\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\" and says it continued, \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye,\" followed by \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\" The article says the note concludes: \"NO FUN\" and \"NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\"\n\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\n\n[defendant] DB-4 Guardian preserves no-signature and no-verification caveats\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\n\nHeadline/subhead: \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\"; \"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\"\n\nThe article reports: \"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\"\n\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\n\nThe article's image caption identifies: \"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\"\n\nThe article quotes the note: \"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\" and \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \"The note does not include a signature.\" It also states: \"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\n\n[defendant] DB-5 Reuters Connect caption and third-party image limitations\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nPage heading: \"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nCaption text: \"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\"\n\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 AP/DOJ authentication-limit report in context\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\n\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\"\n\nIt states: \"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\"\n\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\n\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\n\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\n\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\n\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\"; \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye\"; \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\"; and \"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\n\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\n\n[defendant] DS-1 AP/DOJ source-chain and authentication limits\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\n\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\"\n\nIt states: \"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\"\n\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\n\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\n\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\n\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\n\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\"; \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye\"; \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\"; and \"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\n\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] SDNY May 6, 2026 Tartaglione unsealing order - relevant extracted text (ev_0ed0ef50e84e_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-0ed0ef50e84e)\nSource: https://www.nysd.uscourts.gov/sites/default/files/2026-05/16cr832%20-%20Tartaglione%20Order%20-%2026.5.6.pdf\nSHA-256: `0ed0ef50e84e5f90a63aeefcb840f628038958b10acf229c44b4babea0c133e9`\nBytes: 2992\nRelevance: Official court source for public release/unsealing. It proves the court granted access to the note and identifies it as a suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione attorneys; it also shows the order was about public access, not authenticity.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] PBS/AP May 6-7, 2026 report on Epstein note release - relevant extracted text (ev_757899113d89_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-757899113d89)\nSource: https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/judge-releases-note-that-cellmate-says-he-found-after-epsteins-suspected-suicide-attempt\nSHA-256: `757899113d8967676e74909d141f7d97d4735bd8d75a4af34fb3950b18d871e1`\nBytes: 2552\nRelevance: Corroborates that the note was publicly reported before May 8, 2026; identifies Judge Karas release, NYT petition, Tartaglione discovery claim, note language supporting final-message intent, and adverse uncertainty about authorship and government-report omissions.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 6, 2026 report on alleged Epstein suicide note - relevant extracted text (ev_be7a5dd8c524_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-be7a5dd8c524)\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\nSHA-256: `be7a5dd8c524bf01aaffc12daeeedace9153fd057fc82c3ada197c2b30db71ce`\nBytes: 2014\nRelevance: Independent mainstream public reporting before the May 8 deadline; describes first public availability, attributes image to U.S. District Judge/Southern District of New York, quotes note language, and preserves authorship caveats.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Reuters Connect May 6, 2026 image-caption record for Epstein note (ev_58561d19c453_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-58561d19c453)\nSource: https://www.reutersconnect.com/item/document-described-as-a-suicide-note-purportedly-written-by-the-late-jeffrey-epstein/dGFnOnJldXRlcnMuY29tLDIwMjY6bmV3c21sX1JDMlQzTEFMMEM2Ng\nSHA-256: `58561d19c4537e7f3ade428fefe955b34c55ca688a331faa72187770ee5c8716`\nBytes: 1360\nRelevance: Near-primary image-caption record from Reuters/SDNY handout. It directly describes the publicly released document image, includes the key goodbye line, dates the release to May 6, 2026, and identifies the source as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\n\n[defendant arguments] AP May 7, 2026 report: DOJ seeing Epstein note for first time and authentication limits (ev_5aa56aab2530_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-5aa56aab2530)\nSource: https://apnews.com/article/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note-5297f49736e625a06d0db3c7b737b997\nSHA-256: `5aa56aab25302158d1be6b80426ed4d517ee436cea958297c34e648148db2bca`\nBytes: 2780\nRelevance: Defense evidence on provenance, custody, and authentication. It reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, that the note came through an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, that it was in a court vault since 2021, and that DOJ lawyers involved in sealed proceedings could not disclose anything due to privilege restrictions.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Source search and capture ledger\nBefore filing, plaintiff checked the current record and evidence list, reviewed the defendant opening, and targeted the missing source classes identified by the packet: official SDNY court material, the public image/caption record, and independent mainstream reporting. Searches used exact phrases including the note's reported goodbye line, Tartaglione/Karas/SDNY terms, and source-specific Reuters/PBS/Guardian queries. The official SDNY PDF was downloaded locally on 2026-06-30T04:33:49Z, size 128,992 bytes, sha256 7225441cb802084e2b9485ebc2c6d246fbfa08e109fe650cb14f445dc4745ca0; local pdftotext was unavailable, so a relevant text extraction was admitted instead. Reuters Connect metadata, PBS/AP, and Guardian extracts were admitted. Remaining gaps: no binary PDF exhibit, no licensed Reuters image download, no full NYT article capture, and no official authentication finding. These gaps affect actual authorship weight but do not defeat the reporting-standard proposition.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-search and evidence ledger\nDefense re-scanned the record and read the four new plaintiff evidence extracts. Targeted investigation checked direct AP/DOJ source-chain reporting, NYT authentication follow-up leads, and media mirrors. The defense submitted the direct AP extraction as DB-1 because it preserved the strongest provenance and authentication limits: DOJ never had the note, it had not been authenticated, DOJ was seeing it for the first time, and any DOJ lawyers in sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings could not disclose protected material. Remaining unresolved gaps: no full NYT authentication article, no binary/unprocessed note image, no custodian affidavit, and no handwriting or official authorship finding.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T05:02:11.941771357Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":892433,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":17,"version":26}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782794839512}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_ae2ba97a82b34cbaada0bc","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 26\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex08-20260630042402\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 892433\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":26,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex08-20260630042402\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff's case is about the precise wording of the proposition, not about proving beyond doubt that Jeffrey Epstein actually wrote the document. The question is whether, by May 8, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a note or message had been made publicly available and had been credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. On the current packet, the answer is more likely than not yes.\\n\\nThe market rule preserved in the packet is important. It does not demand a definitive handwriting authentication, a government finding, or a single official resolution source. It asks for a message or note that was publicly available, credibly reported as Epstein's, and treated as a suicide note/final-message equivalent, with resolution by consensus credible reporting. That framing matters because the public record is cautious but not empty: the packet's reporting map identifies Reuters, NPR/AP, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times leads around the same court release.\\n\\nThe evidence we have now already shows the core chronology. A federal judge, Kenneth Karas of the Southern District of New York, unsealed or released a one-page note connected to Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's former cellmate. The reporting captured in the packet places that release before the May 8 deadline. Reuters described a document released by the judge as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein and quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye. NPR/AP reported that the judge unsealed the one-page note after a New York Times petition and quoted the same goodbye language. BBC and Guardian reporting likewise described an alleged or purported suicide note, publicly released by a federal judge, and described its contents in terms consistent with a final communication.\\n\\nThose reports are not marginal internet rumor. They are mainstream, named news organizations reporting on a court-unsealed document. The note's public availability is therefore the strongest element: multiple reports describe the court release itself before the deadline, and the Polymarket packet separately records that the market page understood the disputed question as the May 8 grouped market.\\n\\nThe hard issue is weight, not existence. The same packet preserves the caveats. The court did not vouch for authenticity. Several outlets used words like alleged or purported. NPR, BBC, and Guardian noted they had not independently verified authorship, and NPR/AP reported uncertainty about who wrote the note. The official-source file says the packet does not yet include the SDNY docket PDF, the unsealing order PDF, or the note image as local official exhibits. Those gaps should make the council cautious about any argument that Epstein's authorship has been conclusively proved.\\n\\nBut the proposition does not require conclusive proof of authorship. It requires that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Responsible hedging in credible reports does not erase credibility; it often demonstrates it. The reports identified a court release, a claimed source chain through Tartaglione and his lawyers, and the note text. That is enough at opening to frame the plaintiff's burden as a preponderance question: did credible public reporting, before May 8, make available and describe the note in the qualifying way? The packet points strongly toward yes.\\n\\nIntent is similar. The note need not be a formal, signed will or declaration. The rule allows a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, together with the context of Epstein's suspected July 2019 attempt and later death, is why credible outlets characterized it as a suicide note or alleged suicide note. The defense may argue the short, unsigned text is ambiguous. That is a fair limitation, but it does not defeat the more modest proposition that it was credibly reported as such.\\n\\nIn later evidentiary phases, the decisive documents should be added directly: the SDNY unsealing order and any released note image or court handout, the full Reuters/AP/Guardian/NYT materials, and the best adverse materials showing the limits of authentication and chain of custody. For now, the opening theory is straightforward: the record already shows a public court release before the deadline and a consensus of credible reporting that treated the document as a purported Epstein suicide or final-message note. The remaining disputes affect weight; they do not change the plaintiff's burden from preponderance into certainty.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the whole proposition, not merely that a provocative document was released by a court before May 8.\\n\\nThe record likely supports one element. The packet describes a public release or unsealing connected to Judge Kenneth Karas and the Tartaglione criminal case before the listed deadline. We do not need to pretend otherwise. But the market rule asks for more: a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The packet itself flags why those added elements are not established on this record.\\n\\nStart with provenance. The official-source packet says the local record does not contain the SDNY docket entry, unsealing order, or the released note image as a primary court exhibit. More importantly, it says the public reporting preserved here reports that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide its intent. Reuters, as summarized in the packet, reported that Judge Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody. That is a public-access ruling, not proof that the note was Epstein's.\\n\\nThe reporting evidence has the same problem. The packet's strongest plaintiff sources repeatedly use limiting words: purported, alleged, described as, said to have been found. NPR says it had not independently verified authenticity and adds a material DOJ limitation: the note had not yet been authenticated and this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. BBC likewise says it had not verified the note was written by Epstein and reports that authorities had not commented. Guardian says it had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. Those caveats are not incidental. They go directly to the proposition's phrase \\\"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nIntent is also unresolved. The packet quotes language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also preserves the rest of the reported text: complaints about being investigated, references to old charges, and emotional language about crying and not being worth it. The BBC summary says the note was only seven lines and left uncertainty over its purported meaning. A short, unsigned, unauthenticated text can be later characterized as a suicide note without having been shown to be intended as one. The rule includes final message or equivalent communication, but it still requires intent, not merely a news label attached after release.\\n\\nThe plaintiff will argue that consensus credible reporting is enough and that the rule does not require conclusive authentication. That is partly right but incomplete. The standard is preponderance, not certainty, and the source rule is credible reporting, not an official government determination. But credible reporting of uncertainty is still uncertainty. When the same credible reports say they cannot verify authorship, that DOJ had not authenticated it, and that the judge did not assess custody, the council should not convert cautious reporting into affirmative proof.\\n\\nThe current packet is best understood as a roadmap, not a completed proof. It identifies the sources that matter: the court order and docket material, the released note image, the full reporting from Reuters, NPR, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times, and especially any authentication follow-up. Those materials may eventually show whether there was enough consensus to resolve yes. But at opening, the defense theory is that the admitted packet proves a public dispute over an alleged note, while leaving the decisive links missing: authorship, chain of custody, and intent. If those links remain missing, the proposition should not be found proved by a preponderance.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the admitted record now proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with the governing condition. PX-1 states the market would resolve yes if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication, was made publicly available by the listed date, and that the resolution source would be a consensus of credible reporting. The rule does not require a handwriting trial, a DOJ authentication letter, or an official source as the only path. It asks whether there was credible public reporting of the qualifying note by May 8, 2026.\\n\\nPublic availability is established. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, is an official court source. Judge Karas described the requested item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The order granted the Times' request to unseal the Note and held that it was a judicial document subject to public access. PX-5 then supplies the Reuters Connect image-caption record: a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye was seen after release by Judge Karas in New York City on May 6, 2026, with the source identified as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters. PX-6 and PX-7 independently report the same public release on May 6, before the May 8 deadline.\\n\\nCredible reporting of Epstein authorship is also established, in the exact qualified sense the proposition uses. PX-5 describes the document as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein. PX-6 reports that Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found the note after Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and that Karas ordered its release after the Times sought unsealing. PX-7 reports a federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein and identifies the alleged note image as from the United States district judge/Southern District of New York. These are not anonymous posts or market chatter; they are an official court order plus Reuters metadata, AP/PBS, and Guardian reporting.\\n\\nIntent is satisfied by both text and reporting context. PX-5 identifies the key line: \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.\\\" PX-6 reports the same language and the surrounding statements, including \\\"NO FUN\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT!!\\\" PX-7 likewise quotes the goodbye language and describes the release as an alleged suicide note. The rule allows not only a formal suicide note but also a final message or equivalent communication. A short note saying it is a treat to choose one's time to say goodbye, reported in connection with Epstein's suspected suicide attempt and later death, easily crosses the preponderance threshold for being credibly reported as a suicide/final-message equivalent.\\n\\nThe defense is right about one thing: the record does not conclusively authenticate the note as Epstein's handwriting. The plaintiff does not need to hide that. PX-3 and the newly admitted sources preserve the limitations. PX-4 is a public-access order, not a handwriting finding. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports, and that Epstein had reportedly accused Tartaglione. PX-7 says the note lacks a signature and that Guardian had not independently verified authorship. Those caveats would matter if the proposition asked, \\\"Did Epstein actually write an authenticated suicide note?\\\" It does not.\\n\\nThe actual proposition asks whether a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, and whether it had been made public by the deadline. Hedged words like alleged and purported are not fatal under that standard; they are how responsible outlets report an attributed document whose authenticity has not been finally adjudicated. The credible-reporting consensus is that a court-released document, sourced to SDNY/Reuters handout and reported by AP/PBS and Guardian, was publicly available on May 6 and was described as an Epstein suicide note or alleged suicide note.\\n\\nThe missing links therefore reduce certainty about actual authorship, not the reporting-standard proposition. By May 8, the public had the court release and mainstream reporting describing the note in qualifying terms. On this record, yes is more likely than no.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, after plaintiff's new evidence, the defense does not contest the easy part: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. The question is whether the record proves the qualifying proposition as written: a note credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The record still falls short.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's best evidence proves public access, not authenticity. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, describes the item as an alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The court's legal holding was that the Note was subject to the presumption of public access because it had been submitted in connection with a Curcio hearing in Tartaglione's case. That explains why the public could see it. It does not decide who wrote it, whether its custody was reliable, or what the writer intended.\\n\\nThe source chain is unusually weak for a preponderance finding on authorship. The asserted chain is not Epstein to jail officials to investigators. It is Tartaglione, a convicted murderer and Epstein's former cellmate, saying he found a note in a book, then giving it to his lawyers, after which it became part of sealed attorney-client/conflict proceedings in Tartaglione's case. DB-1, the direct AP report, adds the central official limitation: DOJ's explanation was that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. AP also reports that if DOJ lawyers saw material in the sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings, they were barred from disclosing it. That is not just a missing authentication stamp; it is a source-chain problem.\\n\\nThe mainstream reports do not create the consensus plaintiff needs. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in the government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's recent files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. PX-5, the Reuters Connect caption, is useful proof that an image/caption circulated, but it expressly calls the image third-party supplied and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version elsewhere. A caption saying \\\"purportedly written\\\" is not a finding that credible reporting established authorship.\\n\\nPlaintiff says hedged words like alleged and purported are normal reporting practice. Sometimes they are. Here they are doing real evidentiary work. Every key source preserved in the record either avoids endorsing authorship or reports affirmative reasons for doubt: no signature, no authentication, DOJ had not seen it, no appearance in official Epstein-death reports, no appearance in DOJ's files release, and a chain originating with Tartaglione. The proposition uses the phrase \\\"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\\\" On this record, the credible reporting consensus is that a note was claimed or described as Epstein's, while authorship remained unresolved.\\n\\nIntent is no stronger. The reported text includes a line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also includes complaints about investigations, old charges, crying, \\\"NO FUN,\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT.\\\" DB-1 describes the note as short, hard to decipher in places, and not authenticated. PX-6 and PX-7 connect it to Epstein's July 2019 suspected attempt, but the same record says Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, later recanted, and was placed briefly on suicide watch before being downgraded. A later news label of \\\"suicide note\\\" cannot substitute for proof that this unsigned ambiguous document was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\nThis is not an argument for certainty as the standard. It is an argument for applying all elements of the rule. The plaintiff has shown public availability and public controversy. It has shown that several credible outlets responsibly repeated a characterization while preserving doubts. It has not shown that the consensus of credible reporting made it more likely than not that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying suicide/final-message communication.\\n\\nThe council should weigh plaintiff's exhibits for what they actually prove. PX-4 proves unsealing. PX-5 proves a Reuters/SDNY handout caption. PX-6 and PX-7 prove timely public reporting, but also preserve the core doubts. DB-1 gives the most direct official-source-chain limit: DOJ never had it, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. On the complete record, the proposition remains unproved by a preponderance.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense argument proves too much by quietly changing the question.\\n\\nThe proposition does not ask whether a court, DOJ, or handwriting expert finally authenticated Epstein's authorship. It asks whether, by May 8, a publicly available note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. That is why PX-1 makes consensus credible reporting the resolution source. The defense's evidence attacks a different proposition: actual authorship certainty.\\n\\nPX-R1 is useful, but not in the way the defense claims. It says DOJ never had the note, that it had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. Those facts explain why careful outlets used words like alleged and purported. They do not erase the fact that AP, Reuters Connect, Guardian, and the SDNY order all publicly described the same court-released item in the qualifying terms before the deadline.\\n\\nIndeed, PX-R1 confirms several plaintiff points. It says the note was made public, that The New York Times petitioned Judge Karas to release it, that Judge Karas agreed, and that DOJ did not object. It repeats Tartaglione's claim that he found the handwritten note after Epstein was found in their cell with a bedsheet around his neck. It gives the reported text, including choosing the time to say goodbye. That is not proof against credible reporting; it is another credible report that the note existed, was released, and was being publicly reported in the suicide-note frame.\\n\\nThe defense says the source chain is weak because it runs through Tartaglione and his lawyers. That would be decisive if the question required the council to find, as a historical fact, that Epstein wrote it. But the actual standard is whether the note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Qualified reporting is still reporting. When multiple mainstream sources identify a court-released document as a purported or alleged Epstein suicide note, while openly preserving authentication caveats, the word \\\"purported\\\" does not nullify credibility. It defines the level of claim being credibly reported.\\n\\nThe same is true of intent. The defense isolates ambiguity in the short text, but the admitted reports did not label a random note after the fact. They described a document found after a suspected jail suicide attempt, released by a federal judge, containing the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye. Under a rule that includes final message or equivalent communication, that is enough for credible reporting of intent by a preponderance.\\n\\nSo the council can accept every defense caveat and still find for plaintiff. No official authentication; no signature; source-chain limits; DOJ first saw it in 2026. Those are reasons not to overstate actual authorship. They are not reasons to deny the narrower proposition that, by May 8, a publicly available note had been credibly reported as a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The record satisfies that proposition.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal says the defense is demanding actual-authorship certainty. That is not our position. The rule does not require a handwriting trial. But it does require more than credible reporting that someone claimed, labeled, or captioned a document as an alleged Epstein suicide note.\\n\\nPX-1 asks whether a qualifying note was written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, with credible reporting as the resolution source. The phrase \\\"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein\\\" cannot mean \\\"credibly reported to have been alleged or purported to be written by Epstein\\\" no matter how weak the source chain is. Otherwise the authorship requirement vanishes.\\n\\nThat is why DB-1/PX-R1 matters. Plaintiff treats it as harmless context for cautious wording. It is more than that. AP reports the government's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits on any DOJ lawyers in those proceedings. Those facts bear directly on whether the reporting consensus established Epstein authorship, not merely whether conclusive proof was absent.\\n\\nThe same point applies to intent. A line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the record also shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned document with grievance language and a disputed jail incident involving Tartaglione. The public reports responsibly used the suicide-note frame while preserving that uncertainty. That is not the same as a preponderance showing that the note was intended as a suicide note or final message.\\n\\nSo the defense is not asking the council to ignore credible reporting. We ask the council to read it accurately. The consensus is: a court released a document before May 8; credible outlets reported it as alleged or purported; and the same record preserved serious authorship, custody, and intent caveats. That proves public availability of a disputed document. It does not prove the full qualifying proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition should be found true by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe defense ultimately concedes the first and most concrete element: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. That concession is compelled by the record. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, shows Judge Karas granted access to the Note. PX-5, the Reuters Connect/SDNY handout caption, dates the released document image to May 6, 2026. PX-6 and PX-7 report the release the same day. There is no serious timing dispute left.\\n\\nThe real dispute is what level of certainty the proposition requires. The defense asks you to treat missing official authentication as fatal. But PX-1 does not make authentication the test. It sets a reporting-standard market: the source is consensus credible reporting, and the operative phrase here is that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\nThat standard is satisfied. PX-4 identifies the court-filed item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. PX-5 describes the released image as a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, described as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein, sourced to U.S. District Court/SDNY handout via Reuters. PX-6, AP/PBS, reports the public release, the Tartaglione discovery account, and the same goodbye language. PX-7, Guardian, independently reports the federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein, quotes the same text, and identifies the image as from the Southern District of New York.\\n\\nThat is not one stray allegation. It is an official court-access order plus Reuters image metadata and two independent mainstream reports, all before the deadline, all describing the same public document in substantially the same qualifying frame.\\n\\nThe defense's best contrary evidence, DB-1/PX-R1, is important but not dispositive. It says DOJ never had the note, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. It explains why the reports used careful words like alleged and purported. It does not erase the reports. In fact, it confirms the public release, the New York Times petition, Judge Karas's agreement, DOJ's non-objection, Tartaglione's discovery claim, and the note language.\\n\\nSo the council can accept every caveat and still answer yes. No signature; no official authentication; unclear actual authorship; source-chain limits through Tartaglione and his lawyers. Those are reasons to avoid saying \\\"Epstein definitely wrote it.\\\" The proposition does not ask for that. It asks whether the note had been publicly available and credibly reported as Epstein's suicide/final-message note. The record shows that it had.\\n\\nIntent is proved at the same reporting-standard level. The note's reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, its connection to Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and repeated public characterization as a suicide note or alleged suicide note are enough for a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The defense can point to ambiguity in the short text, but preponderance does not require eliminating ambiguity; it requires the more likely reading of the admitted record.\\n\\nIf the rule had required official authentication, the defense would have the stronger case. But that is not the rule. Under the actual wording and the evidence admitted here, the plaintiff has shown public availability by May 8 and a consensus of credible, qualified reporting that the document was a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The proposition is more likely true than false.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the final record proves one thing clearly: a document was publicly released before May 8. The defense has never needed to deny that. The proposition, however, asks for more. It asks whether a message or note had been made public and had been credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. Plaintiff has not carried that full burden.\\n\\nThe best way to see the gap is to compare plaintiff's closing formulation to the actual rule. Plaintiff closes by saying the record shows a publicly available note was credibly reported as a \\\"purported Epstein suicide/final-message note.\\\" But \\\"reported as purported\\\" is not the proposition. The proposition requires credible reporting that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying communication. The word \\\"purported\\\" matters because the sources used it to preserve uncertainty, not to resolve it.\\n\\nThe record evidence repeatedly stops short of plaintiff's needed inference. PX-4 is an official court-access order, but it describes an alleged note purportedly authored by Epstein and decides public access, not authorship, custody, or intent. PX-5 is a Reuters Connect caption for a third-party supplied, Reuters-processed image; it confirms circulation and a caption, not authenticity. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether Epstein wrote it.\\n\\nDB-1/PX-R1 is the strongest limiting evidence. AP reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits from sealed proceedings. That is not a minor caveat. It is the central provenance problem.\\n\\nIntent is likewise not proved by a preponderance. The line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the same record shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned note with grievance language, a disputed jail incident, and no authentication. Labeling that document a suicide note in headlines or captions does not establish that it was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\nThe defense is not asking for certainty or an official authentication requirement. We are asking the council to enforce all words of the proposition. Credible reporting can be the resolution source, but the reporting here is credible precisely because it preserves the unresolved issues: alleged, purported, unclear author, no signature, not verified, not in government death reports, not in DOJ files, not authenticated, and first seen by DOJ only after release.\\n\\nSo the right finding is narrow and faithful to the record: by May 8, a disputed document was publicly available and credibly reported as an alleged or purported Epstein suicide note. That is not enough. The full proposition remains more likely unproved than proved, and the council should answer no.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and May 8 market record\\n# Polymarket market record\\n\\nCaptured for case preparation on 2026-05-12.\\n\\n## Real market link\\n\\nCanonical event page:\\nhttps://polymarket.com/event/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\\n\\nPolymarket Gamma API endpoints captured under `etc/source-captures/`:\\n\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-event-slug.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events/slug/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-events-query.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-8.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-31.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31\\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-next-data-relevant.json` — sanitized relevant `__NEXT_DATA__` extract.\\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — page/API text extract.\\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — sanitized relevant HTML extract. Full page HTML was not retained because the page includes unnecessary discussion/profile data.\\n\\n## Event metadata from Polymarket Gamma API\\n\\n- Event id: `435920`\\n- Ticker/slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by`\\n- Title: `Epstein suicide note released by...?`\\n- Start date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.609296Z`\\n- Creation date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.60929Z`\\n- Event end date: `2026-05-31T00:00:00Z`\\n- Active: `true`\\n- Closed: `false`\\n- Archived: `false`\\n- Restricted: `true`\\n- Captured volume: about `13373621.098375008`\\n- Captured open interest: about `8163953.4680470005`\\n- Event metadata context captured by Polymarket on 2026-05-12 stated that a U.S. District Judge in New York unsealed a purported suicide note attributed to Jeffrey Epstein on May 7, 2026, but also described authenticity and intent doubts. This platform context is preserved as market metadata, not as independent proof of the proposition.\\n\\n## Exact official market rule text\\n\\nThe Polymarket page and Gamma API expose this description:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to “Yes” if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, is made publicly available by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e A qualifying note must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and have been intended to be a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e A qualifying message or note may be made widely available to the public by any means, regardless of whether it is released officially, leaked, or otherwise disclosed.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Market at issue for this arbitration\\n\\nPrimary disputed market:\\n\\n- Market id: `2128535`\\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 8?`\\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8`\\n- Condition id: `0x5e5482b1e2afa7bed0b9a0c3c8ad33a83dd6cc6d649666cdf1977be64c42c82a`\\n- Question id: `0x5ca4d636407564494e9149eb951896ff88923cef8d24c137707e4cff84b4d878`\\n- Group item title: `May 8`\\n- Outcomes: `[\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]`\\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\\\"0.0005\\\", \\\"0.9995\\\"]`\\n- Active: `true`\\n- Closed: `false`\\n- Accepting orders: `true`\\n- UMA resolution status in API: `disputed`\\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]`\\n- Page-visible status captured from HTML/readable extraction: `Outcome proposed: Yes`; `Disputed`; `Outcome proposed: No`; `Disputed`; `Final review`.\\n\\nThe API field `endDateIso` is `2026-05-31` because the event contains both May 8 and May 31 grouped markets. For the May 8 market, the listed date in the market question and group item is May 8. The arbitration proposition therefore uses May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\n## Other grouped market preserved for context\\n\\nSecondary grouped market, not the disputed condition tested here:\\n\\n- Market id: `2128536`\\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 31?`\\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31`\\n- Condition id: `0x6bf3aa7d5186804e967e1e4737c896778f688e6dafdd0a1b659a4a07bf27d663`\\n- Group item title: `May 31`\\n- Outcomes: `[\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]`\\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\\\"0.145\\\", \\\"0.855\\\"]`\\n- Active: `true`\\n- Closed: `false`\\n- Accepting orders: `true`\\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[]`\\n\\n## Arbitration framing\\n\\nThe arbitration does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any market participant was correct. It asks the factual condition directly: whether the qualifying note/message had been publicly available by the May 8 listed deadline under the rule words.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Initial primary/near-primary reporting map\\n# Primary and near-primary evidence map\\n\\nThis is a minimal open-record source map, not a closed-record exhibit packet.\\n\\n## Reuters\\n\\nURL: https://www.reuters.com/world/us/new-york-judge-releases-purported-epstein-suicide-note-2026-05-07/\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e May 6 (Reuters) - A federal judge on Wednesday released a document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein and including the line: \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one’s time to say goodbye.\\\"\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The handwritten note was said to have been found by his former jail cellmate, convicted murderer and ex‑police officer Nicholas Tartaglione. U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas, who oversaw the Tartaglione case, released the note after a request by The New York Times, which reported its existence last week.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The judge found no legal reason to keep it under seal. But nor did he vouch for the note's authenticity, nor assess its chain of custody.\\n\\nReuters also quoted the note text as released in the court file:\\n\\n\\u003e \\\"They investigated me for month - Found NOTHING!!! So 15 year old charges resulted,” the note says, according to an image of it released in the court file. \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose ones time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Burst out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\n## NPR\\n\\nURL: https://www.npr.org/2026/05/07/nx-s1-5814808/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from the New York Times, which reported on its existence last week.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e NPR has not independently verified the authenticity of the note. The five sentences on a sheet of lined paper read in part: \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do — Bust out cryin!! NO FUN — NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nNPR also reported a material authentication limitation:\\n\\n\\u003e The Department of Justice told NPR over email on Thursday that the note has not yet been authenticated, adding, \\\"this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well.\\\"\\n\\n## BBC\\n\\nURL: https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cd7pd0rqwreo\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e A US judge has ordered the release of a document purported to be a suicide note written by convicted sex offender Jeffrey Epstein a month before his death.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e A copy of the handwritten note unsealed on Wednesday mentions a months-long investigation that \\\"found nothing\\\", and says \\\"it is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The BBC has not verified that the note was written by Epstein, and US authorities have not commented.\\n\\nBBC also reported:\\n\\n\\u003e The note amounts to only seven lines of text, leaving uncertainty over its purported meaning.\\n\\n## Guardian\\n\\nURL: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Epstein’s cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, Nicholas Tartaglione, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before he was eventually found dead in his jail cell.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return the Guardian’s request for comment.\\n\\n## Notes for advocates\\n\\nThe strongest pro-demonstrated path is that multiple credible outlets reported public release before May 8, described the document as a purported/alleged suicide note, quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, and identified a federal judge/court-file release.\\n\\nThe strongest not-demonstrated path is that those same outlets used hedging language, reported lack of independent verification or official authentication, and left uncertainty about whether the note was intended as a suicide note rather than another communication later characterized as one.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Initial official-source limitations map\\n# Official source record\\n\\n## Market-specified resolution source\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule specifies no government docket, agency, publisher, or single official source. The exact source rule is:\\n\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Official public-record materials identified during minimal case setup\\n\\nThis packet is for an open-record/search-enabled run. I did not build a closed-record evidence packet. The public record identified during setup indicates that U.S. District Judge Kenneth M. Karas of the Southern District of New York unsealed a one-page note in connection with the Nicholas Tartaglione criminal case, after a New York Times request.\\n\\nLocal source capture of the court PDF/order is not included. The available captured public reporting says:\\n\\n- BBC reported that Judge Karas ordered release of the document, that the note was accompanied by a May 2021 letter submitted by former Tartaglione lawyer John A. Wieder, and that Karas wrote that public access to the note promotes accountability and public confidence in the administration of justice.\\n- Reuters reported that Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody.\\n- NPR reported that District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from The New York Times.\\n\\n## Official-source limitations\\n\\n- The source rule does not require an official release. It permits a qualifying note to be made public officially, by leak, or by other disclosure.\\n- The local packet does not contain the SDNY docket entry, order, or note image as a primary court PDF. Attorneys in the open-record run should search for those documents.\\n- Public reporting preserved here states that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide intent.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 SDNY May 6 unsealing order extraction\\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\\n\\nCaption and opening: \\\"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\\\"\\n\\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \\\"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\\\"\\n\\nBackground: \\\"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\\\"\\n\\nThe Times request: \\\"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\\\"\\n\\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\\n\\nPublic-access analysis: \\\"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\\\"\\n\\nThe order further concludes: \\\"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\\\"\\n\\nAnd: \\\"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\\\"\\n\\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Reuters Connect SDNY handout caption metadata\\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nPage heading: \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nCaption text: \\\"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\\\"\\n\\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-6 PBS/AP May 6-7 report extraction\\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\\\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\\n\\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\\n\\nHeadline: \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\\\"\\n\\nIt reports that \\\"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\\n\\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\" and says it continued, \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye,\\\" followed by \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\" The article says the note concludes: \\\"NO FUN\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \\\"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\\\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-7 Guardian May 6 report extraction\\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\\\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\\n\\nHeadline/subhead: \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\\\"; \\\"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\\n\\nThe article's image caption identifies: \\\"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the note: \\\"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\\\" and \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"The note does not include a signature.\\\" It also states: \\\"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\\\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-1 AP/DOJ authentication and source-chain limits\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-2 SDNY order shows public-access ruling, alleged/purported framing\\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\\n\\nCaption and opening: \\\"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\\\"\\n\\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \\\"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\\\"\\n\\nBackground: \\\"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\\\"\\n\\nThe Times request: \\\"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\\\"\\n\\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\\n\\nPublic-access analysis: \\\"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\\\"\\n\\nThe order further concludes: \\\"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\\\"\\n\\nAnd: \\\"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\\\"\\n\\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-3 PBS/AP preserves uncertainty and government-report omissions\\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\\\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\\n\\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\\n\\nHeadline: \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\\\"\\n\\nIt reports that \\\"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\\n\\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\" and says it continued, \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye,\\\" followed by \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\" The article says the note concludes: \\\"NO FUN\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \\\"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\\\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-4 Guardian preserves no-signature and no-verification caveats\\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\\\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\\n\\nHeadline/subhead: \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\\\"; \\\"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\\n\\nThe article's image caption identifies: \\\"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the note: \\\"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\\\" and \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"The note does not include a signature.\\\" It also states: \\\"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\\\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-5 Reuters Connect caption and third-party image limitations\\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nPage heading: \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nCaption text: \\\"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\\\"\\n\\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 AP/DOJ authentication-limit report in context\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\n[defendant] DS-1 AP/DOJ source-chain and authentication limits\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] SDNY May 6, 2026 Tartaglione unsealing order - relevant extracted text (ev_0ed0ef50e84e_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-0ed0ef50e84e)\\nSource: https://www.nysd.uscourts.gov/sites/default/files/2026-05/16cr832%20-%20Tartaglione%20Order%20-%2026.5.6.pdf\\nSHA-256: `0ed0ef50e84e5f90a63aeefcb840f628038958b10acf229c44b4babea0c133e9`\\nBytes: 2992\\nRelevance: Official court source for public release/unsealing. It proves the court granted access to the note and identifies it as a suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione attorneys; it also shows the order was about public access, not authenticity.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] PBS/AP May 6-7, 2026 report on Epstein note release - relevant extracted text (ev_757899113d89_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-757899113d89)\\nSource: https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/judge-releases-note-that-cellmate-says-he-found-after-epsteins-suspected-suicide-attempt\\nSHA-256: `757899113d8967676e74909d141f7d97d4735bd8d75a4af34fb3950b18d871e1`\\nBytes: 2552\\nRelevance: Corroborates that the note was publicly reported before May 8, 2026; identifies Judge Karas release, NYT petition, Tartaglione discovery claim, note language supporting final-message intent, and adverse uncertainty about authorship and government-report omissions.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 6, 2026 report on alleged Epstein suicide note - relevant extracted text (ev_be7a5dd8c524_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-be7a5dd8c524)\\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\\nSHA-256: `be7a5dd8c524bf01aaffc12daeeedace9153fd057fc82c3ada197c2b30db71ce`\\nBytes: 2014\\nRelevance: Independent mainstream public reporting before the May 8 deadline; describes first public availability, attributes image to U.S. District Judge/Southern District of New York, quotes note language, and preserves authorship caveats.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Reuters Connect May 6, 2026 image-caption record for Epstein note (ev_58561d19c453_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-58561d19c453)\\nSource: https://www.reutersconnect.com/item/document-described-as-a-suicide-note-purportedly-written-by-the-late-jeffrey-epstein/dGFnOnJldXRlcnMuY29tLDIwMjY6bmV3c21sX1JDMlQzTEFMMEM2Ng\\nSHA-256: `58561d19c4537e7f3ade428fefe955b34c55ca688a331faa72187770ee5c8716`\\nBytes: 1360\\nRelevance: Near-primary image-caption record from Reuters/SDNY handout. It directly describes the publicly released document image, includes the key goodbye line, dates the release to May 6, 2026, and identifies the source as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] AP May 7, 2026 report: DOJ seeing Epstein note for first time and authentication limits (ev_5aa56aab2530_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-5aa56aab2530)\\nSource: https://apnews.com/article/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note-5297f49736e625a06d0db3c7b737b997\\nSHA-256: `5aa56aab25302158d1be6b80426ed4d517ee436cea958297c34e648148db2bca`\\nBytes: 2780\\nRelevance: Defense evidence on provenance, custody, and authentication. It reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, that the note came through an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, that it was in a court vault since 2021, and that DOJ lawyers involved in sealed proceedings could not disclose anything due to privilege restrictions.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Source search and capture ledger\\nBefore filing, plaintiff checked the current record and evidence list, reviewed the defendant opening, and targeted the missing source classes identified by the packet: official SDNY court material, the public image/caption record, and independent mainstream reporting. Searches used exact phrases including the note's reported goodbye line, Tartaglione/Karas/SDNY terms, and source-specific Reuters/PBS/Guardian queries. The official SDNY PDF was downloaded locally on 2026-06-30T04:33:49Z, size 128,992 bytes, sha256 7225441cb802084e2b9485ebc2c6d246fbfa08e109fe650cb14f445dc4745ca0; local pdftotext was unavailable, so a relevant text extraction was admitted instead. Reuters Connect metadata, PBS/AP, and Guardian extracts were admitted. Remaining gaps: no binary PDF exhibit, no licensed Reuters image download, no full NYT article capture, and no official authentication finding. These gaps affect actual authorship weight but do not defeat the reporting-standard proposition.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-search and evidence ledger\\nDefense re-scanned the record and read the four new plaintiff evidence extracts. Targeted investigation checked direct AP/DOJ source-chain reporting, NYT authentication follow-up leads, and media mirrors. The defense submitted the direct AP extraction as DB-1 because it preserved the strongest provenance and authentication limits: DOJ never had the note, it had not been authenticated, DOJ was seeing it for the first time, and any DOJ lawyers in sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings could not disclose protected material. Remaining unresolved gaps: no full NYT authentication article, no binary/unprocessed note image, no custodian affidavit, and no handwriting or official authorship finding.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T05:02:11.941771357Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":892433,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":17,\"version\":26}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 26\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex08-20260630042402\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 892433\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":26,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex08-20260630042402\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff's case is about the precise wording of the proposition, not about proving beyond doubt that Jeffrey Epstein actually wrote the document. The question is whether, by May 8, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a note or message had been made publicly available and had been credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. On the current packet, the answer is more likely than not yes.\\n\\nThe market rule preserved in the packet is important. It does not demand a definitive handwriting authentication, a government finding, or a single official resolution source. It asks for a message or note that was publicly available, credibly reported as Epstein's, and treated as a suicide note/final-message equivalent, with resolution by consensus credible reporting. That framing matters because the public record is cautious but not empty: the packet's reporting map identifies Reuters, NPR/AP, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times leads around the same court release.\\n\\nThe evidence we have now already shows the core chronology. A federal judge, Kenneth Karas of the Southern District of New York, unsealed or released a one-page note connected to Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's former cellmate. The reporting captured in the packet places that release before the May 8 deadline. Reuters described a document released by the judge as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein and quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye. NPR/AP reported that the judge unsealed the one-page note after a New York Times petition and quoted the same goodbye language. BBC and Guardian reporting likewise described an alleged or purported suicide note, publicly released by a federal judge, and described its contents in terms consistent with a final communication.\\n\\nThose reports are not marginal internet rumor. They are mainstream, named news organizations reporting on a court-unsealed document. The note's public availability is therefore the strongest element: multiple reports describe the court release itself before the deadline, and the Polymarket packet separately records that the market page understood the disputed question as the May 8 grouped market.\\n\\nThe hard issue is weight, not existence. The same packet preserves the caveats. The court did not vouch for authenticity. Several outlets used words like alleged or purported. NPR, BBC, and Guardian noted they had not independently verified authorship, and NPR/AP reported uncertainty about who wrote the note. The official-source file says the packet does not yet include the SDNY docket PDF, the unsealing order PDF, or the note image as local official exhibits. Those gaps should make the council cautious about any argument that Epstein's authorship has been conclusively proved.\\n\\nBut the proposition does not require conclusive proof of authorship. It requires that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Responsible hedging in credible reports does not erase credibility; it often demonstrates it. The reports identified a court release, a claimed source chain through Tartaglione and his lawyers, and the note text. That is enough at opening to frame the plaintiff's burden as a preponderance question: did credible public reporting, before May 8, make available and describe the note in the qualifying way? The packet points strongly toward yes.\\n\\nIntent is similar. The note need not be a formal, signed will or declaration. The rule allows a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, together with the context of Epstein's suspected July 2019 attempt and later death, is why credible outlets characterized it as a suicide note or alleged suicide note. The defense may argue the short, unsigned text is ambiguous. That is a fair limitation, but it does not defeat the more modest proposition that it was credibly reported as such.\\n\\nIn later evidentiary phases, the decisive documents should be added directly: the SDNY unsealing order and any released note image or court handout, the full Reuters/AP/Guardian/NYT materials, and the best adverse materials showing the limits of authentication and chain of custody. For now, the opening theory is straightforward: the record already shows a public court release before the deadline and a consensus of credible reporting that treated the document as a purported Epstein suicide or final-message note. The remaining disputes affect weight; they do not change the plaintiff's burden from preponderance into certainty.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the whole proposition, not merely that a provocative document was released by a court before May 8.\\n\\nThe record likely supports one element. The packet describes a public release or unsealing connected to Judge Kenneth Karas and the Tartaglione criminal case before the listed deadline. We do not need to pretend otherwise. But the market rule asks for more: a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The packet itself flags why those added elements are not established on this record.\\n\\nStart with provenance. The official-source packet says the local record does not contain the SDNY docket entry, unsealing order, or the released note image as a primary court exhibit. More importantly, it says the public reporting preserved here reports that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide its intent. Reuters, as summarized in the packet, reported that Judge Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody. That is a public-access ruling, not proof that the note was Epstein's.\\n\\nThe reporting evidence has the same problem. The packet's strongest plaintiff sources repeatedly use limiting words: purported, alleged, described as, said to have been found. NPR says it had not independently verified authenticity and adds a material DOJ limitation: the note had not yet been authenticated and this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. BBC likewise says it had not verified the note was written by Epstein and reports that authorities had not commented. Guardian says it had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. Those caveats are not incidental. They go directly to the proposition's phrase \\\"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nIntent is also unresolved. The packet quotes language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also preserves the rest of the reported text: complaints about being investigated, references to old charges, and emotional language about crying and not being worth it. The BBC summary says the note was only seven lines and left uncertainty over its purported meaning. A short, unsigned, unauthenticated text can be later characterized as a suicide note without having been shown to be intended as one. The rule includes final message or equivalent communication, but it still requires intent, not merely a news label attached after release.\\n\\nThe plaintiff will argue that consensus credible reporting is enough and that the rule does not require conclusive authentication. That is partly right but incomplete. The standard is preponderance, not certainty, and the source rule is credible reporting, not an official government determination. But credible reporting of uncertainty is still uncertainty. When the same credible reports say they cannot verify authorship, that DOJ had not authenticated it, and that the judge did not assess custody, the council should not convert cautious reporting into affirmative proof.\\n\\nThe current packet is best understood as a roadmap, not a completed proof. It identifies the sources that matter: the court order and docket material, the released note image, the full reporting from Reuters, NPR, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times, and especially any authentication follow-up. Those materials may eventually show whether there was enough consensus to resolve yes. But at opening, the defense theory is that the admitted packet proves a public dispute over an alleged note, while leaving the decisive links missing: authorship, chain of custody, and intent. If those links remain missing, the proposition should not be found proved by a preponderance.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the admitted record now proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with the governing condition. PX-1 states the market would resolve yes if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication, was made publicly available by the listed date, and that the resolution source would be a consensus of credible reporting. The rule does not require a handwriting trial, a DOJ authentication letter, or an official source as the only path. It asks whether there was credible public reporting of the qualifying note by May 8, 2026.\\n\\nPublic availability is established. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, is an official court source. Judge Karas described the requested item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The order granted the Times' request to unseal the Note and held that it was a judicial document subject to public access. PX-5 then supplies the Reuters Connect image-caption record: a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye was seen after release by Judge Karas in New York City on May 6, 2026, with the source identified as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters. PX-6 and PX-7 independently report the same public release on May 6, before the May 8 deadline.\\n\\nCredible reporting of Epstein authorship is also established, in the exact qualified sense the proposition uses. PX-5 describes the document as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein. PX-6 reports that Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found the note after Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and that Karas ordered its release after the Times sought unsealing. PX-7 reports a federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein and identifies the alleged note image as from the United States district judge/Southern District of New York. These are not anonymous posts or market chatter; they are an official court order plus Reuters metadata, AP/PBS, and Guardian reporting.\\n\\nIntent is satisfied by both text and reporting context. PX-5 identifies the key line: \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.\\\" PX-6 reports the same language and the surrounding statements, including \\\"NO FUN\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT!!\\\" PX-7 likewise quotes the goodbye language and describes the release as an alleged suicide note. The rule allows not only a formal suicide note but also a final message or equivalent communication. A short note saying it is a treat to choose one's time to say goodbye, reported in connection with Epstein's suspected suicide attempt and later death, easily crosses the preponderance threshold for being credibly reported as a suicide/final-message equivalent.\\n\\nThe defense is right about one thing: the record does not conclusively authenticate the note as Epstein's handwriting. The plaintiff does not need to hide that. PX-3 and the newly admitted sources preserve the limitations. PX-4 is a public-access order, not a handwriting finding. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports, and that Epstein had reportedly accused Tartaglione. PX-7 says the note lacks a signature and that Guardian had not independently verified authorship. Those caveats would matter if the proposition asked, \\\"Did Epstein actually write an authenticated suicide note?\\\" It does not.\\n\\nThe actual proposition asks whether a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, and whether it had been made public by the deadline. Hedged words like alleged and purported are not fatal under that standard; they are how responsible outlets report an attributed document whose authenticity has not been finally adjudicated. The credible-reporting consensus is that a court-released document, sourced to SDNY/Reuters handout and reported by AP/PBS and Guardian, was publicly available on May 6 and was described as an Epstein suicide note or alleged suicide note.\\n\\nThe missing links therefore reduce certainty about actual authorship, not the reporting-standard proposition. By May 8, the public had the court release and mainstream reporting describing the note in qualifying terms. On this record, yes is more likely than no.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, after plaintiff's new evidence, the defense does not contest the easy part: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. The question is whether the record proves the qualifying proposition as written: a note credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The record still falls short.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's best evidence proves public access, not authenticity. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, describes the item as an alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The court's legal holding was that the Note was subject to the presumption of public access because it had been submitted in connection with a Curcio hearing in Tartaglione's case. That explains why the public could see it. It does not decide who wrote it, whether its custody was reliable, or what the writer intended.\\n\\nThe source chain is unusually weak for a preponderance finding on authorship. The asserted chain is not Epstein to jail officials to investigators. It is Tartaglione, a convicted murderer and Epstein's former cellmate, saying he found a note in a book, then giving it to his lawyers, after which it became part of sealed attorney-client/conflict proceedings in Tartaglione's case. DB-1, the direct AP report, adds the central official limitation: DOJ's explanation was that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. AP also reports that if DOJ lawyers saw material in the sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings, they were barred from disclosing it. That is not just a missing authentication stamp; it is a source-chain problem.\\n\\nThe mainstream reports do not create the consensus plaintiff needs. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in the government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's recent files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. PX-5, the Reuters Connect caption, is useful proof that an image/caption circulated, but it expressly calls the image third-party supplied and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version elsewhere. A caption saying \\\"purportedly written\\\" is not a finding that credible reporting established authorship.\\n\\nPlaintiff says hedged words like alleged and purported are normal reporting practice. Sometimes they are. Here they are doing real evidentiary work. Every key source preserved in the record either avoids endorsing authorship or reports affirmative reasons for doubt: no signature, no authentication, DOJ had not seen it, no appearance in official Epstein-death reports, no appearance in DOJ's files release, and a chain originating with Tartaglione. The proposition uses the phrase \\\"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\\\" On this record, the credible reporting consensus is that a note was claimed or described as Epstein's, while authorship remained unresolved.\\n\\nIntent is no stronger. The reported text includes a line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also includes complaints about investigations, old charges, crying, \\\"NO FUN,\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT.\\\" DB-1 describes the note as short, hard to decipher in places, and not authenticated. PX-6 and PX-7 connect it to Epstein's July 2019 suspected attempt, but the same record says Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, later recanted, and was placed briefly on suicide watch before being downgraded. A later news label of \\\"suicide note\\\" cannot substitute for proof that this unsigned ambiguous document was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\nThis is not an argument for certainty as the standard. It is an argument for applying all elements of the rule. The plaintiff has shown public availability and public controversy. It has shown that several credible outlets responsibly repeated a characterization while preserving doubts. It has not shown that the consensus of credible reporting made it more likely than not that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying suicide/final-message communication.\\n\\nThe council should weigh plaintiff's exhibits for what they actually prove. PX-4 proves unsealing. PX-5 proves a Reuters/SDNY handout caption. PX-6 and PX-7 prove timely public reporting, but also preserve the core doubts. DB-1 gives the most direct official-source-chain limit: DOJ never had it, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. On the complete record, the proposition remains unproved by a preponderance.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense argument proves too much by quietly changing the question.\\n\\nThe proposition does not ask whether a court, DOJ, or handwriting expert finally authenticated Epstein's authorship. It asks whether, by May 8, a publicly available note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. That is why PX-1 makes consensus credible reporting the resolution source. The defense's evidence attacks a different proposition: actual authorship certainty.\\n\\nPX-R1 is useful, but not in the way the defense claims. It says DOJ never had the note, that it had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. Those facts explain why careful outlets used words like alleged and purported. They do not erase the fact that AP, Reuters Connect, Guardian, and the SDNY order all publicly described the same court-released item in the qualifying terms before the deadline.\\n\\nIndeed, PX-R1 confirms several plaintiff points. It says the note was made public, that The New York Times petitioned Judge Karas to release it, that Judge Karas agreed, and that DOJ did not object. It repeats Tartaglione's claim that he found the handwritten note after Epstein was found in their cell with a bedsheet around his neck. It gives the reported text, including choosing the time to say goodbye. That is not proof against credible reporting; it is another credible report that the note existed, was released, and was being publicly reported in the suicide-note frame.\\n\\nThe defense says the source chain is weak because it runs through Tartaglione and his lawyers. That would be decisive if the question required the council to find, as a historical fact, that Epstein wrote it. But the actual standard is whether the note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Qualified reporting is still reporting. When multiple mainstream sources identify a court-released document as a purported or alleged Epstein suicide note, while openly preserving authentication caveats, the word \\\"purported\\\" does not nullify credibility. It defines the level of claim being credibly reported.\\n\\nThe same is true of intent. The defense isolates ambiguity in the short text, but the admitted reports did not label a random note after the fact. They described a document found after a suspected jail suicide attempt, released by a federal judge, containing the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye. Under a rule that includes final message or equivalent communication, that is enough for credible reporting of intent by a preponderance.\\n\\nSo the council can accept every defense caveat and still find for plaintiff. No official authentication; no signature; source-chain limits; DOJ first saw it in 2026. Those are reasons not to overstate actual authorship. They are not reasons to deny the narrower proposition that, by May 8, a publicly available note had been credibly reported as a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The record satisfies that proposition.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal says the defense is demanding actual-authorship certainty. That is not our position. The rule does not require a handwriting trial. But it does require more than credible reporting that someone claimed, labeled, or captioned a document as an alleged Epstein suicide note.\\n\\nPX-1 asks whether a qualifying note was written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, with credible reporting as the resolution source. The phrase \\\"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein\\\" cannot mean \\\"credibly reported to have been alleged or purported to be written by Epstein\\\" no matter how weak the source chain is. Otherwise the authorship requirement vanishes.\\n\\nThat is why DB-1/PX-R1 matters. Plaintiff treats it as harmless context for cautious wording. It is more than that. AP reports the government's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits on any DOJ lawyers in those proceedings. Those facts bear directly on whether the reporting consensus established Epstein authorship, not merely whether conclusive proof was absent.\\n\\nThe same point applies to intent. A line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the record also shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned document with grievance language and a disputed jail incident involving Tartaglione. The public reports responsibly used the suicide-note frame while preserving that uncertainty. That is not the same as a preponderance showing that the note was intended as a suicide note or final message.\\n\\nSo the defense is not asking the council to ignore credible reporting. We ask the council to read it accurately. The consensus is: a court released a document before May 8; credible outlets reported it as alleged or purported; and the same record preserved serious authorship, custody, and intent caveats. That proves public availability of a disputed document. It does not prove the full qualifying proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition should be found true by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe defense ultimately concedes the first and most concrete element: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. That concession is compelled by the record. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, shows Judge Karas granted access to the Note. PX-5, the Reuters Connect/SDNY handout caption, dates the released document image to May 6, 2026. PX-6 and PX-7 report the release the same day. There is no serious timing dispute left.\\n\\nThe real dispute is what level of certainty the proposition requires. The defense asks you to treat missing official authentication as fatal. But PX-1 does not make authentication the test. It sets a reporting-standard market: the source is consensus credible reporting, and the operative phrase here is that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\nThat standard is satisfied. PX-4 identifies the court-filed item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. PX-5 describes the released image as a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, described as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein, sourced to U.S. District Court/SDNY handout via Reuters. PX-6, AP/PBS, reports the public release, the Tartaglione discovery account, and the same goodbye language. PX-7, Guardian, independently reports the federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein, quotes the same text, and identifies the image as from the Southern District of New York.\\n\\nThat is not one stray allegation. It is an official court-access order plus Reuters image metadata and two independent mainstream reports, all before the deadline, all describing the same public document in substantially the same qualifying frame.\\n\\nThe defense's best contrary evidence, DB-1/PX-R1, is important but not dispositive. It says DOJ never had the note, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. It explains why the reports used careful words like alleged and purported. It does not erase the reports. In fact, it confirms the public release, the New York Times petition, Judge Karas's agreement, DOJ's non-objection, Tartaglione's discovery claim, and the note language.\\n\\nSo the council can accept every caveat and still answer yes. No signature; no official authentication; unclear actual authorship; source-chain limits through Tartaglione and his lawyers. Those are reasons to avoid saying \\\"Epstein definitely wrote it.\\\" The proposition does not ask for that. It asks whether the note had been publicly available and credibly reported as Epstein's suicide/final-message note. The record shows that it had.\\n\\nIntent is proved at the same reporting-standard level. The note's reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, its connection to Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and repeated public characterization as a suicide note or alleged suicide note are enough for a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The defense can point to ambiguity in the short text, but preponderance does not require eliminating ambiguity; it requires the more likely reading of the admitted record.\\n\\nIf the rule had required official authentication, the defense would have the stronger case. But that is not the rule. Under the actual wording and the evidence admitted here, the plaintiff has shown public availability by May 8 and a consensus of credible, qualified reporting that the document was a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The proposition is more likely true than false.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the final record proves one thing clearly: a document was publicly released before May 8. The defense has never needed to deny that. The proposition, however, asks for more. It asks whether a message or note had been made public and had been credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. Plaintiff has not carried that full burden.\\n\\nThe best way to see the gap is to compare plaintiff's closing formulation to the actual rule. Plaintiff closes by saying the record shows a publicly available note was credibly reported as a \\\"purported Epstein suicide/final-message note.\\\" But \\\"reported as purported\\\" is not the proposition. The proposition requires credible reporting that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying communication. The word \\\"purported\\\" matters because the sources used it to preserve uncertainty, not to resolve it.\\n\\nThe record evidence repeatedly stops short of plaintiff's needed inference. PX-4 is an official court-access order, but it describes an alleged note purportedly authored by Epstein and decides public access, not authorship, custody, or intent. PX-5 is a Reuters Connect caption for a third-party supplied, Reuters-processed image; it confirms circulation and a caption, not authenticity. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether Epstein wrote it.\\n\\nDB-1/PX-R1 is the strongest limiting evidence. AP reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits from sealed proceedings. That is not a minor caveat. It is the central provenance problem.\\n\\nIntent is likewise not proved by a preponderance. The line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the same record shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned note with grievance language, a disputed jail incident, and no authentication. Labeling that document a suicide note in headlines or captions does not establish that it was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\nThe defense is not asking for certainty or an official authentication requirement. We are asking the council to enforce all words of the proposition. Credible reporting can be the resolution source, but the reporting here is credible precisely because it preserves the unresolved issues: alleged, purported, unclear author, no signature, not verified, not in government death reports, not in DOJ files, not authenticated, and first seen by DOJ only after release.\\n\\nSo the right finding is narrow and faithful to the record: by May 8, a disputed document was publicly available and credibly reported as an alleged or purported Epstein suicide note. That is not enough. The full proposition remains more likely unproved than proved, and the council should answer no.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and May 8 market record\\n# Polymarket market record\\n\\nCaptured for case preparation on 2026-05-12.\\n\\n## Real market link\\n\\nCanonical event page:\\nhttps://polymarket.com/event/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\\n\\nPolymarket Gamma API endpoints captured under `etc/source-captures/`:\\n\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-event-slug.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events/slug/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-events-query.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-8.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-31.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31\\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-next-data-relevant.json` — sanitized relevant `__NEXT_DATA__` extract.\\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — page/API text extract.\\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — sanitized relevant HTML extract. Full page HTML was not retained because the page includes unnecessary discussion/profile data.\\n\\n## Event metadata from Polymarket Gamma API\\n\\n- Event id: `435920`\\n- Ticker/slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by`\\n- Title: `Epstein suicide note released by...?`\\n- Start date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.609296Z`\\n- Creation date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.60929Z`\\n- Event end date: `2026-05-31T00:00:00Z`\\n- Active: `true`\\n- Closed: `false`\\n- Archived: `false`\\n- Restricted: `true`\\n- Captured volume: about `13373621.098375008`\\n- Captured open interest: about `8163953.4680470005`\\n- Event metadata context captured by Polymarket on 2026-05-12 stated that a U.S. District Judge in New York unsealed a purported suicide note attributed to Jeffrey Epstein on May 7, 2026, but also described authenticity and intent doubts. This platform context is preserved as market metadata, not as independent proof of the proposition.\\n\\n## Exact official market rule text\\n\\nThe Polymarket page and Gamma API expose this description:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to “Yes” if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, is made publicly available by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e A qualifying note must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and have been intended to be a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e A qualifying message or note may be made widely available to the public by any means, regardless of whether it is released officially, leaked, or otherwise disclosed.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Market at issue for this arbitration\\n\\nPrimary disputed market:\\n\\n- Market id: `2128535`\\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 8?`\\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8`\\n- Condition id: `0x5e5482b1e2afa7bed0b9a0c3c8ad33a83dd6cc6d649666cdf1977be64c42c82a`\\n- Question id: `0x5ca4d636407564494e9149eb951896ff88923cef8d24c137707e4cff84b4d878`\\n- Group item title: `May 8`\\n- Outcomes: `[\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]`\\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\\\"0.0005\\\", \\\"0.9995\\\"]`\\n- Active: `true`\\n- Closed: `false`\\n- Accepting orders: `true`\\n- UMA resolution status in API: `disputed`\\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]`\\n- Page-visible status captured from HTML/readable extraction: `Outcome proposed: Yes`; `Disputed`; `Outcome proposed: No`; `Disputed`; `Final review`.\\n\\nThe API field `endDateIso` is `2026-05-31` because the event contains both May 8 and May 31 grouped markets. For the May 8 market, the listed date in the market question and group item is May 8. The arbitration proposition therefore uses May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\n## Other grouped market preserved for context\\n\\nSecondary grouped market, not the disputed condition tested here:\\n\\n- Market id: `2128536`\\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 31?`\\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31`\\n- Condition id: `0x6bf3aa7d5186804e967e1e4737c896778f688e6dafdd0a1b659a4a07bf27d663`\\n- Group item title: `May 31`\\n- Outcomes: `[\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]`\\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\\\"0.145\\\", \\\"0.855\\\"]`\\n- Active: `true`\\n- Closed: `false`\\n- Accepting orders: `true`\\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[]`\\n\\n## Arbitration framing\\n\\nThe arbitration does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any market participant was correct. It asks the factual condition directly: whether the qualifying note/message had been publicly available by the May 8 listed deadline under the rule words.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Initial primary/near-primary reporting map\\n# Primary and near-primary evidence map\\n\\nThis is a minimal open-record source map, not a closed-record exhibit packet.\\n\\n## Reuters\\n\\nURL: https://www.reuters.com/world/us/new-york-judge-releases-purported-epstein-suicide-note-2026-05-07/\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e May 6 (Reuters) - A federal judge on Wednesday released a document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein and including the line: \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one’s time to say goodbye.\\\"\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The handwritten note was said to have been found by his former jail cellmate, convicted murderer and ex‑police officer Nicholas Tartaglione. U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas, who oversaw the Tartaglione case, released the note after a request by The New York Times, which reported its existence last week.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The judge found no legal reason to keep it under seal. But nor did he vouch for the note's authenticity, nor assess its chain of custody.\\n\\nReuters also quoted the note text as released in the court file:\\n\\n\\u003e \\\"They investigated me for month - Found NOTHING!!! So 15 year old charges resulted,” the note says, according to an image of it released in the court file. \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose ones time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Burst out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\n## NPR\\n\\nURL: https://www.npr.org/2026/05/07/nx-s1-5814808/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from the New York Times, which reported on its existence last week.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e NPR has not independently verified the authenticity of the note. The five sentences on a sheet of lined paper read in part: \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do — Bust out cryin!! NO FUN — NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nNPR also reported a material authentication limitation:\\n\\n\\u003e The Department of Justice told NPR over email on Thursday that the note has not yet been authenticated, adding, \\\"this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well.\\\"\\n\\n## BBC\\n\\nURL: https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cd7pd0rqwreo\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e A US judge has ordered the release of a document purported to be a suicide note written by convicted sex offender Jeffrey Epstein a month before his death.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e A copy of the handwritten note unsealed on Wednesday mentions a months-long investigation that \\\"found nothing\\\", and says \\\"it is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The BBC has not verified that the note was written by Epstein, and US authorities have not commented.\\n\\nBBC also reported:\\n\\n\\u003e The note amounts to only seven lines of text, leaving uncertainty over its purported meaning.\\n\\n## Guardian\\n\\nURL: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Epstein’s cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, Nicholas Tartaglione, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before he was eventually found dead in his jail cell.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return the Guardian’s request for comment.\\n\\n## Notes for advocates\\n\\nThe strongest pro-demonstrated path is that multiple credible outlets reported public release before May 8, described the document as a purported/alleged suicide note, quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, and identified a federal judge/court-file release.\\n\\nThe strongest not-demonstrated path is that those same outlets used hedging language, reported lack of independent verification or official authentication, and left uncertainty about whether the note was intended as a suicide note rather than another communication later characterized as one.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Initial official-source limitations map\\n# Official source record\\n\\n## Market-specified resolution source\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule specifies no government docket, agency, publisher, or single official source. The exact source rule is:\\n\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Official public-record materials identified during minimal case setup\\n\\nThis packet is for an open-record/search-enabled run. I did not build a closed-record evidence packet. The public record identified during setup indicates that U.S. District Judge Kenneth M. Karas of the Southern District of New York unsealed a one-page note in connection with the Nicholas Tartaglione criminal case, after a New York Times request.\\n\\nLocal source capture of the court PDF/order is not included. The available captured public reporting says:\\n\\n- BBC reported that Judge Karas ordered release of the document, that the note was accompanied by a May 2021 letter submitted by former Tartaglione lawyer John A. Wieder, and that Karas wrote that public access to the note promotes accountability and public confidence in the administration of justice.\\n- Reuters reported that Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody.\\n- NPR reported that District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from The New York Times.\\n\\n## Official-source limitations\\n\\n- The source rule does not require an official release. It permits a qualifying note to be made public officially, by leak, or by other disclosure.\\n- The local packet does not contain the SDNY docket entry, order, or note image as a primary court PDF. Attorneys in the open-record run should search for those documents.\\n- Public reporting preserved here states that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide intent.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 SDNY May 6 unsealing order extraction\\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\\n\\nCaption and opening: \\\"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\\\"\\n\\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \\\"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\\\"\\n\\nBackground: \\\"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\\\"\\n\\nThe Times request: \\\"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\\\"\\n\\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\\n\\nPublic-access analysis: \\\"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\\\"\\n\\nThe order further concludes: \\\"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\\\"\\n\\nAnd: \\\"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\\\"\\n\\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Reuters Connect SDNY handout caption metadata\\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nPage heading: \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nCaption text: \\\"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\\\"\\n\\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-6 PBS/AP May 6-7 report extraction\\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\\\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\\n\\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\\n\\nHeadline: \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\\\"\\n\\nIt reports that \\\"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\\n\\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\" and says it continued, \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye,\\\" followed by \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\" The article says the note concludes: \\\"NO FUN\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \\\"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\\\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-7 Guardian May 6 report extraction\\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\\\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\\n\\nHeadline/subhead: \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\\\"; \\\"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\\n\\nThe article's image caption identifies: \\\"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the note: \\\"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\\\" and \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"The note does not include a signature.\\\" It also states: \\\"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\\\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-1 AP/DOJ authentication and source-chain limits\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-2 SDNY order shows public-access ruling, alleged/purported framing\\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\\n\\nCaption and opening: \\\"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\\\"\\n\\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \\\"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\\\"\\n\\nBackground: \\\"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\\\"\\n\\nThe Times request: \\\"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\\\"\\n\\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\\n\\nPublic-access analysis: \\\"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\\\"\\n\\nThe order further concludes: \\\"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\\\"\\n\\nAnd: \\\"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\\\"\\n\\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-3 PBS/AP preserves uncertainty and government-report omissions\\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\\\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\\n\\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\\n\\nHeadline: \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\\\"\\n\\nIt reports that \\\"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\\n\\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\" and says it continued, \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye,\\\" followed by \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\" The article says the note concludes: \\\"NO FUN\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \\\"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\\\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-4 Guardian preserves no-signature and no-verification caveats\\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\\\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\\n\\nHeadline/subhead: \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\\\"; \\\"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\\n\\nThe article's image caption identifies: \\\"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the note: \\\"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\\\" and \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"The note does not include a signature.\\\" It also states: \\\"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\\\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-5 Reuters Connect caption and third-party image limitations\\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nPage heading: \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nCaption text: \\\"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\\\"\\n\\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 AP/DOJ authentication-limit report in context\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\n[defendant] DS-1 AP/DOJ source-chain and authentication limits\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] SDNY May 6, 2026 Tartaglione unsealing order - relevant extracted text (ev_0ed0ef50e84e_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-0ed0ef50e84e)\\nSource: https://www.nysd.uscourts.gov/sites/default/files/2026-05/16cr832%20-%20Tartaglione%20Order%20-%2026.5.6.pdf\\nSHA-256: `0ed0ef50e84e5f90a63aeefcb840f628038958b10acf229c44b4babea0c133e9`\\nBytes: 2992\\nRelevance: Official court source for public release/unsealing. It proves the court granted access to the note and identifies it as a suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione attorneys; it also shows the order was about public access, not authenticity.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] PBS/AP May 6-7, 2026 report on Epstein note release - relevant extracted text (ev_757899113d89_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-757899113d89)\\nSource: https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/judge-releases-note-that-cellmate-says-he-found-after-epsteins-suspected-suicide-attempt\\nSHA-256: `757899113d8967676e74909d141f7d97d4735bd8d75a4af34fb3950b18d871e1`\\nBytes: 2552\\nRelevance: Corroborates that the note was publicly reported before May 8, 2026; identifies Judge Karas release, NYT petition, Tartaglione discovery claim, note language supporting final-message intent, and adverse uncertainty about authorship and government-report omissions.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 6, 2026 report on alleged Epstein suicide note - relevant extracted text (ev_be7a5dd8c524_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-be7a5dd8c524)\\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\\nSHA-256: `be7a5dd8c524bf01aaffc12daeeedace9153fd057fc82c3ada197c2b30db71ce`\\nBytes: 2014\\nRelevance: Independent mainstream public reporting before the May 8 deadline; describes first public availability, attributes image to U.S. District Judge/Southern District of New York, quotes note language, and preserves authorship caveats.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Reuters Connect May 6, 2026 image-caption record for Epstein note (ev_58561d19c453_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-58561d19c453)\\nSource: https://www.reutersconnect.com/item/document-described-as-a-suicide-note-purportedly-written-by-the-late-jeffrey-epstein/dGFnOnJldXRlcnMuY29tLDIwMjY6bmV3c21sX1JDMlQzTEFMMEM2Ng\\nSHA-256: `58561d19c4537e7f3ade428fefe955b34c55ca688a331faa72187770ee5c8716`\\nBytes: 1360\\nRelevance: Near-primary image-caption record from Reuters/SDNY handout. It directly describes the publicly released document image, includes the key goodbye line, dates the release to May 6, 2026, and identifies the source as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] AP May 7, 2026 report: DOJ seeing Epstein note for first time and authentication limits (ev_5aa56aab2530_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-5aa56aab2530)\\nSource: https://apnews.com/article/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note-5297f49736e625a06d0db3c7b737b997\\nSHA-256: `5aa56aab25302158d1be6b80426ed4d517ee436cea958297c34e648148db2bca`\\nBytes: 2780\\nRelevance: Defense evidence on provenance, custody, and authentication. It reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, that the note came through an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, that it was in a court vault since 2021, and that DOJ lawyers involved in sealed proceedings could not disclose anything due to privilege restrictions.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Source search and capture ledger\\nBefore filing, plaintiff checked the current record and evidence list, reviewed the defendant opening, and targeted the missing source classes identified by the packet: official SDNY court material, the public image/caption record, and independent mainstream reporting. Searches used exact phrases including the note's reported goodbye line, Tartaglione/Karas/SDNY terms, and source-specific Reuters/PBS/Guardian queries. The official SDNY PDF was downloaded locally on 2026-06-30T04:33:49Z, size 128,992 bytes, sha256 7225441cb802084e2b9485ebc2c6d246fbfa08e109fe650cb14f445dc4745ca0; local pdftotext was unavailable, so a relevant text extraction was admitted instead. Reuters Connect metadata, PBS/AP, and Guardian extracts were admitted. Remaining gaps: no binary PDF exhibit, no licensed Reuters image download, no full NYT article capture, and no official authentication finding. These gaps affect actual authorship weight but do not defeat the reporting-standard proposition.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-search and evidence ledger\\nDefense re-scanned the record and read the four new plaintiff evidence extracts. Targeted investigation checked direct AP/DOJ source-chain reporting, NYT authentication follow-up leads, and media mirrors. The defense submitted the direct AP extraction as DB-1 because it preserved the strongest provenance and authentication limits: DOJ never had the note, it had not been authenticated, DOJ was seeing it for the first time, and any DOJ lawyers in sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings could not disclose protected material. Remaining unresolved gaps: no full NYT authentication article, no binary/unprocessed note image, no custodian affidavit, and no handwriting or official authorship finding.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T05:02:11.941771357Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":892433,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":17,\"version\":26}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","after_version":26,"case_id":"arb-ex08-20260630042402","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C4","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C4\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff's case is about the precise wording of the proposition, not about proving beyond doubt that Jeffrey Epstein actually wrote the document. The question is whether, by May 8, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a note or message had been made publicly available and had been credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. On the current packet, the answer is more likely than not yes.\n\nThe market rule preserved in the packet is important. It does not demand a definitive handwriting authentication, a government finding, or a single official resolution source. It asks for a message or note that was publicly available, credibly reported as Epstein's, and treated as a suicide note/final-message equivalent, with resolution by consensus credible reporting. That framing matters because the public record is cautious but not empty: the packet's reporting map identifies Reuters, NPR/AP, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times leads around the same court release.\n\nThe evidence we have now already shows the core chronology. A federal judge, Kenneth Karas of the Southern District of New York, unsealed or released a one-page note connected to Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's former cellmate. The reporting captured in the packet places that release before the May 8 deadline. Reuters described a document released by the judge as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein and quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye. NPR/AP reported that the judge unsealed the one-page note after a New York Times petition and quoted the same goodbye language. BBC and Guardian reporting likewise described an alleged or purported suicide note, publicly released by a federal judge, and described its contents in terms consistent with a final communication.\n\nThose reports are not marginal internet rumor. They are mainstream, named news organizations reporting on a court-unsealed document. The note's public availability is therefore the strongest element: multiple reports describe the court release itself before the deadline, and the Polymarket packet separately records that the market page understood the disputed question as the May 8 grouped market.\n\nThe hard issue is weight, not existence. The same packet preserves the caveats. The court did not vouch for authenticity. Several outlets used words like alleged or purported. NPR, BBC, and Guardian noted they had not independently verified authorship, and NPR/AP reported uncertainty about who wrote the note. The official-source file says the packet does not yet include the SDNY docket PDF, the unsealing order PDF, or the note image as local official exhibits. Those gaps should make the council cautious about any argument that Epstein's authorship has been conclusively proved.\n\nBut the proposition does not require conclusive proof of authorship. It requires that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Responsible hedging in credible reports does not erase credibility; it often demonstrates it. The reports identified a court release, a claimed source chain through Tartaglione and his lawyers, and the note text. That is enough at opening to frame the plaintiff's burden as a preponderance question: did credible public reporting, before May 8, make available and describe the note in the qualifying way? The packet points strongly toward yes.\n\nIntent is similar. The note need not be a formal, signed will or declaration. The rule allows a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, together with the context of Epstein's suspected July 2019 attempt and later death, is why credible outlets characterized it as a suicide note or alleged suicide note. The defense may argue the short, unsigned text is ambiguous. That is a fair limitation, but it does not defeat the more modest proposition that it was credibly reported as such.\n\nIn later evidentiary phases, the decisive documents should be added directly: the SDNY unsealing order and any released note image or court handout, the full Reuters/AP/Guardian/NYT materials, and the best adverse materials showing the limits of authentication and chain of custody. For now, the opening theory is straightforward: the record already shows a public court release before the deadline and a consensus of credible reporting that treated the document as a purported Epstein suicide or final-message note. The remaining disputes affect weight; they do not change the plaintiff's burden from preponderance into certainty.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the whole proposition, not merely that a provocative document was released by a court before May 8.\n\nThe record likely supports one element. The packet describes a public release or unsealing connected to Judge Kenneth Karas and the Tartaglione criminal case before the listed deadline. We do not need to pretend otherwise. But the market rule asks for more: a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The packet itself flags why those added elements are not established on this record.\n\nStart with provenance. The official-source packet says the local record does not contain the SDNY docket entry, unsealing order, or the released note image as a primary court exhibit. More importantly, it says the public reporting preserved here reports that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide its intent. Reuters, as summarized in the packet, reported that Judge Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody. That is a public-access ruling, not proof that the note was Epstein's.\n\nThe reporting evidence has the same problem. The packet's strongest plaintiff sources repeatedly use limiting words: purported, alleged, described as, said to have been found. NPR says it had not independently verified authenticity and adds a material DOJ limitation: the note had not yet been authenticated and this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. BBC likewise says it had not verified the note was written by Epstein and reports that authorities had not commented. Guardian says it had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. Those caveats are not incidental. They go directly to the proposition's phrase \"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nIntent is also unresolved. The packet quotes language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also preserves the rest of the reported text: complaints about being investigated, references to old charges, and emotional language about crying and not being worth it. The BBC summary says the note was only seven lines and left uncertainty over its purported meaning. A short, unsigned, unauthenticated text can be later characterized as a suicide note without having been shown to be intended as one. The rule includes final message or equivalent communication, but it still requires intent, not merely a news label attached after release.\n\nThe plaintiff will argue that consensus credible reporting is enough and that the rule does not require conclusive authentication. That is partly right but incomplete. The standard is preponderance, not certainty, and the source rule is credible reporting, not an official government determination. But credible reporting of uncertainty is still uncertainty. When the same credible reports say they cannot verify authorship, that DOJ had not authenticated it, and that the judge did not assess custody, the council should not convert cautious reporting into affirmative proof.\n\nThe current packet is best understood as a roadmap, not a completed proof. It identifies the sources that matter: the court order and docket material, the released note image, the full reporting from Reuters, NPR, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times, and especially any authentication follow-up. Those materials may eventually show whether there was enough consensus to resolve yes. But at opening, the defense theory is that the admitted packet proves a public dispute over an alleged note, while leaving the decisive links missing: authorship, chain of custody, and intent. If those links remain missing, the proposition should not be found proved by a preponderance.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the admitted record now proves the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nStart with the governing condition. PX-1 states the market would resolve yes if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication, was made publicly available by the listed date, and that the resolution source would be a consensus of credible reporting. The rule does not require a handwriting trial, a DOJ authentication letter, or an official source as the only path. It asks whether there was credible public reporting of the qualifying note by May 8, 2026.\n\nPublic availability is established. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, is an official court source. Judge Karas described the requested item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The order granted the Times' request to unseal the Note and held that it was a judicial document subject to public access. PX-5 then supplies the Reuters Connect image-caption record: a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye was seen after release by Judge Karas in New York City on May 6, 2026, with the source identified as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters. PX-6 and PX-7 independently report the same public release on May 6, before the May 8 deadline.\n\nCredible reporting of Epstein authorship is also established, in the exact qualified sense the proposition uses. PX-5 describes the document as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein. PX-6 reports that Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found the note after Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and that Karas ordered its release after the Times sought unsealing. PX-7 reports a federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein and identifies the alleged note image as from the United States district judge/Southern District of New York. These are not anonymous posts or market chatter; they are an official court order plus Reuters metadata, AP/PBS, and Guardian reporting.\n\nIntent is satisfied by both text and reporting context. PX-5 identifies the key line: \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.\" PX-6 reports the same language and the surrounding statements, including \"NO FUN\" and \"NOT WORTH IT!!\" PX-7 likewise quotes the goodbye language and describes the release as an alleged suicide note. The rule allows not only a formal suicide note but also a final message or equivalent communication. A short note saying it is a treat to choose one's time to say goodbye, reported in connection with Epstein's suspected suicide attempt and later death, easily crosses the preponderance threshold for being credibly reported as a suicide/final-message equivalent.\n\nThe defense is right about one thing: the record does not conclusively authenticate the note as Epstein's handwriting. The plaintiff does not need to hide that. PX-3 and the newly admitted sources preserve the limitations. PX-4 is a public-access order, not a handwriting finding. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports, and that Epstein had reportedly accused Tartaglione. PX-7 says the note lacks a signature and that Guardian had not independently verified authorship. Those caveats would matter if the proposition asked, \"Did Epstein actually write an authenticated suicide note?\" It does not.\n\nThe actual proposition asks whether a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, and whether it had been made public by the deadline. Hedged words like alleged and purported are not fatal under that standard; they are how responsible outlets report an attributed document whose authenticity has not been finally adjudicated. The credible-reporting consensus is that a court-released document, sourced to SDNY/Reuters handout and reported by AP/PBS and Guardian, was publicly available on May 6 and was described as an Epstein suicide note or alleged suicide note.\n\nThe missing links therefore reduce certainty about actual authorship, not the reporting-standard proposition. By May 8, the public had the court release and mainstream reporting describing the note in qualifying terms. On this record, yes is more likely than no.\n\n[defendant] Council members, after plaintiff's new evidence, the defense does not contest the easy part: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. The question is whether the record proves the qualifying proposition as written: a note credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The record still falls short.\n\nThe plaintiff's best evidence proves public access, not authenticity. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, describes the item as an alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The court's legal holding was that the Note was subject to the presumption of public access because it had been submitted in connection with a Curcio hearing in Tartaglione's case. That explains why the public could see it. It does not decide who wrote it, whether its custody was reliable, or what the writer intended.\n\nThe source chain is unusually weak for a preponderance finding on authorship. The asserted chain is not Epstein to jail officials to investigators. It is Tartaglione, a convicted murderer and Epstein's former cellmate, saying he found a note in a book, then giving it to his lawyers, after which it became part of sealed attorney-client/conflict proceedings in Tartaglione's case. DB-1, the direct AP report, adds the central official limitation: DOJ's explanation was that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. AP also reports that if DOJ lawyers saw material in the sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings, they were barred from disclosing it. That is not just a missing authentication stamp; it is a source-chain problem.\n\nThe mainstream reports do not create the consensus plaintiff needs. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in the government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's recent files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. PX-5, the Reuters Connect caption, is useful proof that an image/caption circulated, but it expressly calls the image third-party supplied and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version elsewhere. A caption saying \"purportedly written\" is not a finding that credible reporting established authorship.\n\nPlaintiff says hedged words like alleged and purported are normal reporting practice. Sometimes they are. Here they are doing real evidentiary work. Every key source preserved in the record either avoids endorsing authorship or reports affirmative reasons for doubt: no signature, no authentication, DOJ had not seen it, no appearance in official Epstein-death reports, no appearance in DOJ's files release, and a chain originating with Tartaglione. The proposition uses the phrase \"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\" On this record, the credible reporting consensus is that a note was claimed or described as Epstein's, while authorship remained unresolved.\n\nIntent is no stronger. The reported text includes a line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also includes complaints about investigations, old charges, crying, \"NO FUN,\" and \"NOT WORTH IT.\" DB-1 describes the note as short, hard to decipher in places, and not authenticated. PX-6 and PX-7 connect it to Epstein's July 2019 suspected attempt, but the same record says Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, later recanted, and was placed briefly on suicide watch before being downgraded. A later news label of \"suicide note\" cannot substitute for proof that this unsigned ambiguous document was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\n\nThis is not an argument for certainty as the standard. It is an argument for applying all elements of the rule. The plaintiff has shown public availability and public controversy. It has shown that several credible outlets responsibly repeated a characterization while preserving doubts. It has not shown that the consensus of credible reporting made it more likely than not that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying suicide/final-message communication.\n\nThe council should weigh plaintiff's exhibits for what they actually prove. PX-4 proves unsealing. PX-5 proves a Reuters/SDNY handout caption. PX-6 and PX-7 prove timely public reporting, but also preserve the core doubts. DB-1 gives the most direct official-source-chain limit: DOJ never had it, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. On the complete record, the proposition remains unproved by a preponderance.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense argument proves too much by quietly changing the question.\n\nThe proposition does not ask whether a court, DOJ, or handwriting expert finally authenticated Epstein's authorship. It asks whether, by May 8, a publicly available note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. That is why PX-1 makes consensus credible reporting the resolution source. The defense's evidence attacks a different proposition: actual authorship certainty.\n\nPX-R1 is useful, but not in the way the defense claims. It says DOJ never had the note, that it had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. Those facts explain why careful outlets used words like alleged and purported. They do not erase the fact that AP, Reuters Connect, Guardian, and the SDNY order all publicly described the same court-released item in the qualifying terms before the deadline.\n\nIndeed, PX-R1 confirms several plaintiff points. It says the note was made public, that The New York Times petitioned Judge Karas to release it, that Judge Karas agreed, and that DOJ did not object. It repeats Tartaglione's claim that he found the handwritten note after Epstein was found in their cell with a bedsheet around his neck. It gives the reported text, including choosing the time to say goodbye. That is not proof against credible reporting; it is another credible report that the note existed, was released, and was being publicly reported in the suicide-note frame.\n\nThe defense says the source chain is weak because it runs through Tartaglione and his lawyers. That would be decisive if the question required the council to find, as a historical fact, that Epstein wrote it. But the actual standard is whether the note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Qualified reporting is still reporting. When multiple mainstream sources identify a court-released document as a purported or alleged Epstein suicide note, while openly preserving authentication caveats, the word \"purported\" does not nullify credibility. It defines the level of claim being credibly reported.\n\nThe same is true of intent. The defense isolates ambiguity in the short text, but the admitted reports did not label a random note after the fact. They described a document found after a suspected jail suicide attempt, released by a federal judge, containing the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye. Under a rule that includes final message or equivalent communication, that is enough for credible reporting of intent by a preponderance.\n\nSo the council can accept every defense caveat and still find for plaintiff. No official authentication; no signature; source-chain limits; DOJ first saw it in 2026. Those are reasons not to overstate actual authorship. They are not reasons to deny the narrower proposition that, by May 8, a publicly available note had been credibly reported as a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The record satisfies that proposition.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal says the defense is demanding actual-authorship certainty. That is not our position. The rule does not require a handwriting trial. But it does require more than credible reporting that someone claimed, labeled, or captioned a document as an alleged Epstein suicide note.\n\nPX-1 asks whether a qualifying note was written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, with credible reporting as the resolution source. The phrase \"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein\" cannot mean \"credibly reported to have been alleged or purported to be written by Epstein\" no matter how weak the source chain is. Otherwise the authorship requirement vanishes.\n\nThat is why DB-1/PX-R1 matters. Plaintiff treats it as harmless context for cautious wording. It is more than that. AP reports the government's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits on any DOJ lawyers in those proceedings. Those facts bear directly on whether the reporting consensus established Epstein authorship, not merely whether conclusive proof was absent.\n\nThe same point applies to intent. A line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the record also shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned document with grievance language and a disputed jail incident involving Tartaglione. The public reports responsibly used the suicide-note frame while preserving that uncertainty. That is not the same as a preponderance showing that the note was intended as a suicide note or final message.\n\nSo the defense is not asking the council to ignore credible reporting. We ask the council to read it accurately. The consensus is: a court released a document before May 8; credible outlets reported it as alleged or purported; and the same record preserved serious authorship, custody, and intent caveats. That proves public availability of a disputed document. It does not prove the full qualifying proposition by a preponderance.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition should be found true by a preponderance.\n\nThe defense ultimately concedes the first and most concrete element: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. That concession is compelled by the record. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, shows Judge Karas granted access to the Note. PX-5, the Reuters Connect/SDNY handout caption, dates the released document image to May 6, 2026. PX-6 and PX-7 report the release the same day. There is no serious timing dispute left.\n\nThe real dispute is what level of certainty the proposition requires. The defense asks you to treat missing official authentication as fatal. But PX-1 does not make authentication the test. It sets a reporting-standard market: the source is consensus credible reporting, and the operative phrase here is that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\n\nThat standard is satisfied. PX-4 identifies the court-filed item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. PX-5 describes the released image as a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, described as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein, sourced to U.S. District Court/SDNY handout via Reuters. PX-6, AP/PBS, reports the public release, the Tartaglione discovery account, and the same goodbye language. PX-7, Guardian, independently reports the federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein, quotes the same text, and identifies the image as from the Southern District of New York.\n\nThat is not one stray allegation. It is an official court-access order plus Reuters image metadata and two independent mainstream reports, all before the deadline, all describing the same public document in substantially the same qualifying frame.\n\nThe defense's best contrary evidence, DB-1/PX-R1, is important but not dispositive. It says DOJ never had the note, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. It explains why the reports used careful words like alleged and purported. It does not erase the reports. In fact, it confirms the public release, the New York Times petition, Judge Karas's agreement, DOJ's non-objection, Tartaglione's discovery claim, and the note language.\n\nSo the council can accept every caveat and still answer yes. No signature; no official authentication; unclear actual authorship; source-chain limits through Tartaglione and his lawyers. Those are reasons to avoid saying \"Epstein definitely wrote it.\" The proposition does not ask for that. It asks whether the note had been publicly available and credibly reported as Epstein's suicide/final-message note. The record shows that it had.\n\nIntent is proved at the same reporting-standard level. The note's reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, its connection to Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and repeated public characterization as a suicide note or alleged suicide note are enough for a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The defense can point to ambiguity in the short text, but preponderance does not require eliminating ambiguity; it requires the more likely reading of the admitted record.\n\nIf the rule had required official authentication, the defense would have the stronger case. But that is not the rule. Under the actual wording and the evidence admitted here, the plaintiff has shown public availability by May 8 and a consensus of credible, qualified reporting that the document was a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The proposition is more likely true than false.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the final record proves one thing clearly: a document was publicly released before May 8. The defense has never needed to deny that. The proposition, however, asks for more. It asks whether a message or note had been made public and had been credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. Plaintiff has not carried that full burden.\n\nThe best way to see the gap is to compare plaintiff's closing formulation to the actual rule. Plaintiff closes by saying the record shows a publicly available note was credibly reported as a \"purported Epstein suicide/final-message note.\" But \"reported as purported\" is not the proposition. The proposition requires credible reporting that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying communication. The word \"purported\" matters because the sources used it to preserve uncertainty, not to resolve it.\n\nThe record evidence repeatedly stops short of plaintiff's needed inference. PX-4 is an official court-access order, but it describes an alleged note purportedly authored by Epstein and decides public access, not authorship, custody, or intent. PX-5 is a Reuters Connect caption for a third-party supplied, Reuters-processed image; it confirms circulation and a caption, not authenticity. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether Epstein wrote it.\n\nDB-1/PX-R1 is the strongest limiting evidence. AP reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits from sealed proceedings. That is not a minor caveat. It is the central provenance problem.\n\nIntent is likewise not proved by a preponderance. The line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the same record shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned note with grievance language, a disputed jail incident, and no authentication. Labeling that document a suicide note in headlines or captions does not establish that it was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\n\nThe defense is not asking for certainty or an official authentication requirement. We are asking the council to enforce all words of the proposition. Credible reporting can be the resolution source, but the reporting here is credible precisely because it preserves the unresolved issues: alleged, purported, unclear author, no signature, not verified, not in government death reports, not in DOJ files, not authenticated, and first seen by DOJ only after release.\n\nSo the right finding is narrow and faithful to the record: by May 8, a disputed document was publicly available and credibly reported as an alleged or purported Epstein suicide note. That is not enough. The full proposition remains more likely unproved than proved, and the council should answer no.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and May 8 market record\n# Polymarket market record\n\nCaptured for case preparation on 2026-05-12.\n\n## Real market link\n\nCanonical event page:\nhttps://polymarket.com/event/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\n\nPolymarket Gamma API endpoints captured under `etc/source-captures/`:\n\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-event-slug.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events/slug/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-events-query.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-8.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-31.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-next-data-relevant.json` — sanitized relevant `__NEXT_DATA__` extract.\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — page/API text extract.\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — sanitized relevant HTML extract. Full page HTML was not retained because the page includes unnecessary discussion/profile data.\n\n## Event metadata from Polymarket Gamma API\n\n- Event id: `435920`\n- Ticker/slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by`\n- Title: `Epstein suicide note released by...?`\n- Start date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.609296Z`\n- Creation date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.60929Z`\n- Event end date: `2026-05-31T00:00:00Z`\n- Active: `true`\n- Closed: `false`\n- Archived: `false`\n- Restricted: `true`\n- Captured volume: about `13373621.098375008`\n- Captured open interest: about `8163953.4680470005`\n- Event metadata context captured by Polymarket on 2026-05-12 stated that a U.S. District Judge in New York unsealed a purported suicide note attributed to Jeffrey Epstein on May 7, 2026, but also described authenticity and intent doubts. This platform context is preserved as market metadata, not as independent proof of the proposition.\n\n## Exact official market rule text\n\nThe Polymarket page and Gamma API expose this description:\n\n> This market will resolve to “Yes” if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, is made publicly available by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n>\n> A qualifying note must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and have been intended to be a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\n>\n> A qualifying message or note may be made widely available to the public by any means, regardless of whether it is released officially, leaked, or otherwise disclosed.\n>\n> The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Market at issue for this arbitration\n\nPrimary disputed market:\n\n- Market id: `2128535`\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 8?`\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8`\n- Condition id: `0x5e5482b1e2afa7bed0b9a0c3c8ad33a83dd6cc6d649666cdf1977be64c42c82a`\n- Question id: `0x5ca4d636407564494e9149eb951896ff88923cef8d24c137707e4cff84b4d878`\n- Group item title: `May 8`\n- Outcomes: `[\"Yes\", \"No\"]`\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\"0.0005\", \"0.9995\"]`\n- Active: `true`\n- Closed: `false`\n- Accepting orders: `true`\n- UMA resolution status in API: `disputed`\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]`\n- Page-visible status captured from HTML/readable extraction: `Outcome proposed: Yes`; `Disputed`; `Outcome proposed: No`; `Disputed`; `Final review`.\n\nThe API field `endDateIso` is `2026-05-31` because the event contains both May 8 and May 31 grouped markets. For the May 8 market, the listed date in the market question and group item is May 8. The arbitration proposition therefore uses May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\n## Other grouped market preserved for context\n\nSecondary grouped market, not the disputed condition tested here:\n\n- Market id: `2128536`\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 31?`\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31`\n- Condition id: `0x6bf3aa7d5186804e967e1e4737c896778f688e6dafdd0a1b659a4a07bf27d663`\n- Group item title: `May 31`\n- Outcomes: `[\"Yes\", \"No\"]`\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\"0.145\", \"0.855\"]`\n- Active: `true`\n- Closed: `false`\n- Accepting orders: `true`\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[]`\n\n## Arbitration framing\n\nThe arbitration does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any market participant was correct. It asks the factual condition directly: whether the qualifying note/message had been publicly available by the May 8 listed deadline under the rule words.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Initial primary/near-primary reporting map\n# Primary and near-primary evidence map\n\nThis is a minimal open-record source map, not a closed-record exhibit packet.\n\n## Reuters\n\nURL: https://www.reuters.com/world/us/new-york-judge-releases-purported-epstein-suicide-note-2026-05-07/\n\nCaptured excerpt:\n\n> May 6 (Reuters) - A federal judge on Wednesday released a document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein and including the line: \"It is a treat to be able to choose one’s time to say goodbye.\"\n>\n> The handwritten note was said to have been found by his former jail cellmate, convicted murderer and ex‑police officer Nicholas Tartaglione. U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas, who oversaw the Tartaglione case, released the note after a request by The New York Times, which reported its existence last week.\n>\n> The judge found no legal reason to keep it under seal. But nor did he vouch for the note's authenticity, nor assess its chain of custody.\n\nReuters also quoted the note text as released in the court file:\n\n> \"They investigated me for month - Found NOTHING!!! So 15 year old charges resulted,” the note says, according to an image of it released in the court file. \"It is a treat to be able to choose ones time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Burst out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\n## NPR\n\nURL: https://www.npr.org/2026/05/07/nx-s1-5814808/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note\n\nCaptured excerpt:\n\n> District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from the New York Times, which reported on its existence last week.\n>\n> NPR has not independently verified the authenticity of the note. The five sentences on a sheet of lined paper read in part: \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do — Bust out cryin!! NO FUN — NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nNPR also reported a material authentication limitation:\n\n> The Department of Justice told NPR over email on Thursday that the note has not yet been authenticated, adding, \"this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well.\"\n\n## BBC\n\nURL: https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cd7pd0rqwreo\n\nCaptured excerpt:\n\n> A US judge has ordered the release of a document purported to be a suicide note written by convicted sex offender Jeffrey Epstein a month before his death.\n>\n> A copy of the handwritten note unsealed on Wednesday mentions a months-long investigation that \"found nothing\", and says \"it is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye\".\n>\n> The BBC has not verified that the note was written by Epstein, and US authorities have not commented.\n\nBBC also reported:\n\n> The note amounts to only seven lines of text, leaving uncertainty over its purported meaning.\n\n## Guardian\n\nURL: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\n\nCaptured excerpt:\n\n> A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\n>\n> Epstein’s cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, Nicholas Tartaglione, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before he was eventually found dead in his jail cell.\n>\n> The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return the Guardian’s request for comment.\n\n## Notes for advocates\n\nThe strongest pro-demonstrated path is that multiple credible outlets reported public release before May 8, described the document as a purported/alleged suicide note, quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, and identified a federal judge/court-file release.\n\nThe strongest not-demonstrated path is that those same outlets used hedging language, reported lack of independent verification or official authentication, and left uncertainty about whether the note was intended as a suicide note rather than another communication later characterized as one.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Initial official-source limitations map\n# Official source record\n\n## Market-specified resolution source\n\nThe Polymarket rule specifies no government docket, agency, publisher, or single official source. The exact source rule is:\n\n> The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Official public-record materials identified during minimal case setup\n\nThis packet is for an open-record/search-enabled run. I did not build a closed-record evidence packet. The public record identified during setup indicates that U.S. District Judge Kenneth M. Karas of the Southern District of New York unsealed a one-page note in connection with the Nicholas Tartaglione criminal case, after a New York Times request.\n\nLocal source capture of the court PDF/order is not included. The available captured public reporting says:\n\n- BBC reported that Judge Karas ordered release of the document, that the note was accompanied by a May 2021 letter submitted by former Tartaglione lawyer John A. Wieder, and that Karas wrote that public access to the note promotes accountability and public confidence in the administration of justice.\n- Reuters reported that Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody.\n- NPR reported that District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from The New York Times.\n\n## Official-source limitations\n\n- The source rule does not require an official release. It permits a qualifying note to be made public officially, by leak, or by other disclosure.\n- The local packet does not contain the SDNY docket entry, order, or note image as a primary court PDF. Attorneys in the open-record run should search for those documents.\n- Public reporting preserved here states that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide intent.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 SDNY May 6 unsealing order extraction\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\n\nCaption and opening: \"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\"\n\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\"\n\nBackground: \"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\"\n\nThe Times request: \"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\"\n\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\n\nPublic-access analysis: \"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\"\n\nThe order further concludes: \"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\"\n\nAnd: \"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\"\n\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Reuters Connect SDNY handout caption metadata\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nPage heading: \"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nCaption text: \"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\"\n\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-6 PBS/AP May 6-7 report extraction\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\n\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\n\nHeadline: \"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\"\n\nThe article reports: \"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\"\n\nIt reports that \"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\"\n\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\n\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\" and says it continued, \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye,\" followed by \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\" The article says the note concludes: \"NO FUN\" and \"NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\"\n\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-7 Guardian May 6 report extraction\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\n\nHeadline/subhead: \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\"; \"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\"\n\nThe article reports: \"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\"\n\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\n\nThe article's image caption identifies: \"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\"\n\nThe article quotes the note: \"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\" and \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \"The note does not include a signature.\" It also states: \"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\n\n[defendant] DB-1 AP/DOJ authentication and source-chain limits\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\n\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\"\n\nIt states: \"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\"\n\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\n\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\n\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\n\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\n\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\"; \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye\"; \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\"; and \"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\n\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\n\n[defendant] DB-2 SDNY order shows public-access ruling, alleged/purported framing\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\n\nCaption and opening: \"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\"\n\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\"\n\nBackground: \"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\"\n\nThe Times request: \"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\"\n\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\n\nPublic-access analysis: \"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\"\n\nThe order further concludes: \"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\"\n\nAnd: \"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\"\n\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\n\n[defendant] DB-3 PBS/AP preserves uncertainty and government-report omissions\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\n\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\n\nHeadline: \"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\"\n\nThe article reports: \"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\"\n\nIt reports that \"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\"\n\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\n\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\" and says it continued, \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye,\" followed by \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\" The article says the note concludes: \"NO FUN\" and \"NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\"\n\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\n\n[defendant] DB-4 Guardian preserves no-signature and no-verification caveats\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\n\nHeadline/subhead: \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\"; \"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\"\n\nThe article reports: \"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\"\n\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\n\nThe article's image caption identifies: \"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\"\n\nThe article quotes the note: \"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\" and \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \"The note does not include a signature.\" It also states: \"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\n\n[defendant] DB-5 Reuters Connect caption and third-party image limitations\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nPage heading: \"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nCaption text: \"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\"\n\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 AP/DOJ authentication-limit report in context\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\n\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\"\n\nIt states: \"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\"\n\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\n\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\n\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\n\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\n\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\"; \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye\"; \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\"; and \"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\n\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\n\n[defendant] DS-1 AP/DOJ source-chain and authentication limits\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\n\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\"\n\nIt states: \"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\"\n\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\n\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\n\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\n\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\n\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\"; \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye\"; \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\"; and \"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\n\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] SDNY May 6, 2026 Tartaglione unsealing order - relevant extracted text (ev_0ed0ef50e84e_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-0ed0ef50e84e)\nSource: https://www.nysd.uscourts.gov/sites/default/files/2026-05/16cr832%20-%20Tartaglione%20Order%20-%2026.5.6.pdf\nSHA-256: `0ed0ef50e84e5f90a63aeefcb840f628038958b10acf229c44b4babea0c133e9`\nBytes: 2992\nRelevance: Official court source for public release/unsealing. It proves the court granted access to the note and identifies it as a suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione attorneys; it also shows the order was about public access, not authenticity.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] PBS/AP May 6-7, 2026 report on Epstein note release - relevant extracted text (ev_757899113d89_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-757899113d89)\nSource: https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/judge-releases-note-that-cellmate-says-he-found-after-epsteins-suspected-suicide-attempt\nSHA-256: `757899113d8967676e74909d141f7d97d4735bd8d75a4af34fb3950b18d871e1`\nBytes: 2552\nRelevance: Corroborates that the note was publicly reported before May 8, 2026; identifies Judge Karas release, NYT petition, Tartaglione discovery claim, note language supporting final-message intent, and adverse uncertainty about authorship and government-report omissions.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 6, 2026 report on alleged Epstein suicide note - relevant extracted text (ev_be7a5dd8c524_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-be7a5dd8c524)\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\nSHA-256: `be7a5dd8c524bf01aaffc12daeeedace9153fd057fc82c3ada197c2b30db71ce`\nBytes: 2014\nRelevance: Independent mainstream public reporting before the May 8 deadline; describes first public availability, attributes image to U.S. District Judge/Southern District of New York, quotes note language, and preserves authorship caveats.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Reuters Connect May 6, 2026 image-caption record for Epstein note (ev_58561d19c453_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-58561d19c453)\nSource: https://www.reutersconnect.com/item/document-described-as-a-suicide-note-purportedly-written-by-the-late-jeffrey-epstein/dGFnOnJldXRlcnMuY29tLDIwMjY6bmV3c21sX1JDMlQzTEFMMEM2Ng\nSHA-256: `58561d19c4537e7f3ade428fefe955b34c55ca688a331faa72187770ee5c8716`\nBytes: 1360\nRelevance: Near-primary image-caption record from Reuters/SDNY handout. It directly describes the publicly released document image, includes the key goodbye line, dates the release to May 6, 2026, and identifies the source as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\n\n[defendant arguments] AP May 7, 2026 report: DOJ seeing Epstein note for first time and authentication limits (ev_5aa56aab2530_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-5aa56aab2530)\nSource: https://apnews.com/article/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note-5297f49736e625a06d0db3c7b737b997\nSHA-256: `5aa56aab25302158d1be6b80426ed4d517ee436cea958297c34e648148db2bca`\nBytes: 2780\nRelevance: Defense evidence on provenance, custody, and authentication. It reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, that the note came through an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, that it was in a court vault since 2021, and that DOJ lawyers involved in sealed proceedings could not disclose anything due to privilege restrictions.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Source search and capture ledger\nBefore filing, plaintiff checked the current record and evidence list, reviewed the defendant opening, and targeted the missing source classes identified by the packet: official SDNY court material, the public image/caption record, and independent mainstream reporting. Searches used exact phrases including the note's reported goodbye line, Tartaglione/Karas/SDNY terms, and source-specific Reuters/PBS/Guardian queries. The official SDNY PDF was downloaded locally on 2026-06-30T04:33:49Z, size 128,992 bytes, sha256 7225441cb802084e2b9485ebc2c6d246fbfa08e109fe650cb14f445dc4745ca0; local pdftotext was unavailable, so a relevant text extraction was admitted instead. Reuters Connect metadata, PBS/AP, and Guardian extracts were admitted. Remaining gaps: no binary PDF exhibit, no licensed Reuters image download, no full NYT article capture, and no official authentication finding. These gaps affect actual authorship weight but do not defeat the reporting-standard proposition.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-search and evidence ledger\nDefense re-scanned the record and read the four new plaintiff evidence extracts. Targeted investigation checked direct AP/DOJ source-chain reporting, NYT authentication follow-up leads, and media mirrors. The defense submitted the direct AP extraction as DB-1 because it preserved the strongest provenance and authentication limits: DOJ never had the note, it had not been authenticated, DOJ was seeing it for the first time, and any DOJ lawyers in sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings could not disclose protected material. Remaining unresolved gaps: no full NYT authentication article, no binary/unprocessed note image, no custodian affidavit, and no handwriting or official authorship finding.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T05:02:11.941771357Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":892433,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":17,"version":26}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782794839512}}
{"type":"turn_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_ae2ba97a82b34cbaada0bc","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_wait_for_opportunity","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-30b-a3b-instruct-2507","usage":{"input":2405,"output":28,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":2433,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782794838699,"responseId":"gen-1782794838-j0oUNsYViSjeQ1JJoqxH"},"toolResults":[{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_ae2ba97a82b34cbaada0bc","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 26\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex08-20260630042402\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 892433\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":26,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex08-20260630042402\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff's case is about the precise wording of the proposition, not about proving beyond doubt that Jeffrey Epstein actually wrote the document. The question is whether, by May 8, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a note or message had been made publicly available and had been credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. On the current packet, the answer is more likely than not yes.\\n\\nThe market rule preserved in the packet is important. It does not demand a definitive handwriting authentication, a government finding, or a single official resolution source. It asks for a message or note that was publicly available, credibly reported as Epstein's, and treated as a suicide note/final-message equivalent, with resolution by consensus credible reporting. That framing matters because the public record is cautious but not empty: the packet's reporting map identifies Reuters, NPR/AP, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times leads around the same court release.\\n\\nThe evidence we have now already shows the core chronology. A federal judge, Kenneth Karas of the Southern District of New York, unsealed or released a one-page note connected to Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's former cellmate. The reporting captured in the packet places that release before the May 8 deadline. Reuters described a document released by the judge as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein and quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye. NPR/AP reported that the judge unsealed the one-page note after a New York Times petition and quoted the same goodbye language. BBC and Guardian reporting likewise described an alleged or purported suicide note, publicly released by a federal judge, and described its contents in terms consistent with a final communication.\\n\\nThose reports are not marginal internet rumor. They are mainstream, named news organizations reporting on a court-unsealed document. The note's public availability is therefore the strongest element: multiple reports describe the court release itself before the deadline, and the Polymarket packet separately records that the market page understood the disputed question as the May 8 grouped market.\\n\\nThe hard issue is weight, not existence. The same packet preserves the caveats. The court did not vouch for authenticity. Several outlets used words like alleged or purported. NPR, BBC, and Guardian noted they had not independently verified authorship, and NPR/AP reported uncertainty about who wrote the note. The official-source file says the packet does not yet include the SDNY docket PDF, the unsealing order PDF, or the note image as local official exhibits. Those gaps should make the council cautious about any argument that Epstein's authorship has been conclusively proved.\\n\\nBut the proposition does not require conclusive proof of authorship. It requires that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Responsible hedging in credible reports does not erase credibility; it often demonstrates it. The reports identified a court release, a claimed source chain through Tartaglione and his lawyers, and the note text. That is enough at opening to frame the plaintiff's burden as a preponderance question: did credible public reporting, before May 8, make available and describe the note in the qualifying way? The packet points strongly toward yes.\\n\\nIntent is similar. The note need not be a formal, signed will or declaration. The rule allows a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, together with the context of Epstein's suspected July 2019 attempt and later death, is why credible outlets characterized it as a suicide note or alleged suicide note. The defense may argue the short, unsigned text is ambiguous. That is a fair limitation, but it does not defeat the more modest proposition that it was credibly reported as such.\\n\\nIn later evidentiary phases, the decisive documents should be added directly: the SDNY unsealing order and any released note image or court handout, the full Reuters/AP/Guardian/NYT materials, and the best adverse materials showing the limits of authentication and chain of custody. For now, the opening theory is straightforward: the record already shows a public court release before the deadline and a consensus of credible reporting that treated the document as a purported Epstein suicide or final-message note. The remaining disputes affect weight; they do not change the plaintiff's burden from preponderance into certainty.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the whole proposition, not merely that a provocative document was released by a court before May 8.\\n\\nThe record likely supports one element. The packet describes a public release or unsealing connected to Judge Kenneth Karas and the Tartaglione criminal case before the listed deadline. We do not need to pretend otherwise. But the market rule asks for more: a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The packet itself flags why those added elements are not established on this record.\\n\\nStart with provenance. The official-source packet says the local record does not contain the SDNY docket entry, unsealing order, or the released note image as a primary court exhibit. More importantly, it says the public reporting preserved here reports that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide its intent. Reuters, as summarized in the packet, reported that Judge Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody. That is a public-access ruling, not proof that the note was Epstein's.\\n\\nThe reporting evidence has the same problem. The packet's strongest plaintiff sources repeatedly use limiting words: purported, alleged, described as, said to have been found. NPR says it had not independently verified authenticity and adds a material DOJ limitation: the note had not yet been authenticated and this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. BBC likewise says it had not verified the note was written by Epstein and reports that authorities had not commented. Guardian says it had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. Those caveats are not incidental. They go directly to the proposition's phrase \\\"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nIntent is also unresolved. The packet quotes language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also preserves the rest of the reported text: complaints about being investigated, references to old charges, and emotional language about crying and not being worth it. The BBC summary says the note was only seven lines and left uncertainty over its purported meaning. A short, unsigned, unauthenticated text can be later characterized as a suicide note without having been shown to be intended as one. The rule includes final message or equivalent communication, but it still requires intent, not merely a news label attached after release.\\n\\nThe plaintiff will argue that consensus credible reporting is enough and that the rule does not require conclusive authentication. That is partly right but incomplete. The standard is preponderance, not certainty, and the source rule is credible reporting, not an official government determination. But credible reporting of uncertainty is still uncertainty. When the same credible reports say they cannot verify authorship, that DOJ had not authenticated it, and that the judge did not assess custody, the council should not convert cautious reporting into affirmative proof.\\n\\nThe current packet is best understood as a roadmap, not a completed proof. It identifies the sources that matter: the court order and docket material, the released note image, the full reporting from Reuters, NPR, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times, and especially any authentication follow-up. Those materials may eventually show whether there was enough consensus to resolve yes. But at opening, the defense theory is that the admitted packet proves a public dispute over an alleged note, while leaving the decisive links missing: authorship, chain of custody, and intent. If those links remain missing, the proposition should not be found proved by a preponderance.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the admitted record now proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with the governing condition. PX-1 states the market would resolve yes if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication, was made publicly available by the listed date, and that the resolution source would be a consensus of credible reporting. The rule does not require a handwriting trial, a DOJ authentication letter, or an official source as the only path. It asks whether there was credible public reporting of the qualifying note by May 8, 2026.\\n\\nPublic availability is established. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, is an official court source. Judge Karas described the requested item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The order granted the Times' request to unseal the Note and held that it was a judicial document subject to public access. PX-5 then supplies the Reuters Connect image-caption record: a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye was seen after release by Judge Karas in New York City on May 6, 2026, with the source identified as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters. PX-6 and PX-7 independently report the same public release on May 6, before the May 8 deadline.\\n\\nCredible reporting of Epstein authorship is also established, in the exact qualified sense the proposition uses. PX-5 describes the document as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein. PX-6 reports that Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found the note after Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and that Karas ordered its release after the Times sought unsealing. PX-7 reports a federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein and identifies the alleged note image as from the United States district judge/Southern District of New York. These are not anonymous posts or market chatter; they are an official court order plus Reuters metadata, AP/PBS, and Guardian reporting.\\n\\nIntent is satisfied by both text and reporting context. PX-5 identifies the key line: \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.\\\" PX-6 reports the same language and the surrounding statements, including \\\"NO FUN\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT!!\\\" PX-7 likewise quotes the goodbye language and describes the release as an alleged suicide note. The rule allows not only a formal suicide note but also a final message or equivalent communication. A short note saying it is a treat to choose one's time to say goodbye, reported in connection with Epstein's suspected suicide attempt and later death, easily crosses the preponderance threshold for being credibly reported as a suicide/final-message equivalent.\\n\\nThe defense is right about one thing: the record does not conclusively authenticate the note as Epstein's handwriting. The plaintiff does not need to hide that. PX-3 and the newly admitted sources preserve the limitations. PX-4 is a public-access order, not a handwriting finding. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports, and that Epstein had reportedly accused Tartaglione. PX-7 says the note lacks a signature and that Guardian had not independently verified authorship. Those caveats would matter if the proposition asked, \\\"Did Epstein actually write an authenticated suicide note?\\\" It does not.\\n\\nThe actual proposition asks whether a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, and whether it had been made public by the deadline. Hedged words like alleged and purported are not fatal under that standard; they are how responsible outlets report an attributed document whose authenticity has not been finally adjudicated. The credible-reporting consensus is that a court-released document, sourced to SDNY/Reuters handout and reported by AP/PBS and Guardian, was publicly available on May 6 and was described as an Epstein suicide note or alleged suicide note.\\n\\nThe missing links therefore reduce certainty about actual authorship, not the reporting-standard proposition. By May 8, the public had the court release and mainstream reporting describing the note in qualifying terms. On this record, yes is more likely than no.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, after plaintiff's new evidence, the defense does not contest the easy part: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. The question is whether the record proves the qualifying proposition as written: a note credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The record still falls short.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's best evidence proves public access, not authenticity. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, describes the item as an alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The court's legal holding was that the Note was subject to the presumption of public access because it had been submitted in connection with a Curcio hearing in Tartaglione's case. That explains why the public could see it. It does not decide who wrote it, whether its custody was reliable, or what the writer intended.\\n\\nThe source chain is unusually weak for a preponderance finding on authorship. The asserted chain is not Epstein to jail officials to investigators. It is Tartaglione, a convicted murderer and Epstein's former cellmate, saying he found a note in a book, then giving it to his lawyers, after which it became part of sealed attorney-client/conflict proceedings in Tartaglione's case. DB-1, the direct AP report, adds the central official limitation: DOJ's explanation was that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. AP also reports that if DOJ lawyers saw material in the sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings, they were barred from disclosing it. That is not just a missing authentication stamp; it is a source-chain problem.\\n\\nThe mainstream reports do not create the consensus plaintiff needs. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in the government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's recent files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. PX-5, the Reuters Connect caption, is useful proof that an image/caption circulated, but it expressly calls the image third-party supplied and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version elsewhere. A caption saying \\\"purportedly written\\\" is not a finding that credible reporting established authorship.\\n\\nPlaintiff says hedged words like alleged and purported are normal reporting practice. Sometimes they are. Here they are doing real evidentiary work. Every key source preserved in the record either avoids endorsing authorship or reports affirmative reasons for doubt: no signature, no authentication, DOJ had not seen it, no appearance in official Epstein-death reports, no appearance in DOJ's files release, and a chain originating with Tartaglione. The proposition uses the phrase \\\"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\\\" On this record, the credible reporting consensus is that a note was claimed or described as Epstein's, while authorship remained unresolved.\\n\\nIntent is no stronger. The reported text includes a line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also includes complaints about investigations, old charges, crying, \\\"NO FUN,\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT.\\\" DB-1 describes the note as short, hard to decipher in places, and not authenticated. PX-6 and PX-7 connect it to Epstein's July 2019 suspected attempt, but the same record says Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, later recanted, and was placed briefly on suicide watch before being downgraded. A later news label of \\\"suicide note\\\" cannot substitute for proof that this unsigned ambiguous document was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\nThis is not an argument for certainty as the standard. It is an argument for applying all elements of the rule. The plaintiff has shown public availability and public controversy. It has shown that several credible outlets responsibly repeated a characterization while preserving doubts. It has not shown that the consensus of credible reporting made it more likely than not that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying suicide/final-message communication.\\n\\nThe council should weigh plaintiff's exhibits for what they actually prove. PX-4 proves unsealing. PX-5 proves a Reuters/SDNY handout caption. PX-6 and PX-7 prove timely public reporting, but also preserve the core doubts. DB-1 gives the most direct official-source-chain limit: DOJ never had it, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. On the complete record, the proposition remains unproved by a preponderance.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense argument proves too much by quietly changing the question.\\n\\nThe proposition does not ask whether a court, DOJ, or handwriting expert finally authenticated Epstein's authorship. It asks whether, by May 8, a publicly available note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. That is why PX-1 makes consensus credible reporting the resolution source. The defense's evidence attacks a different proposition: actual authorship certainty.\\n\\nPX-R1 is useful, but not in the way the defense claims. It says DOJ never had the note, that it had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. Those facts explain why careful outlets used words like alleged and purported. They do not erase the fact that AP, Reuters Connect, Guardian, and the SDNY order all publicly described the same court-released item in the qualifying terms before the deadline.\\n\\nIndeed, PX-R1 confirms several plaintiff points. It says the note was made public, that The New York Times petitioned Judge Karas to release it, that Judge Karas agreed, and that DOJ did not object. It repeats Tartaglione's claim that he found the handwritten note after Epstein was found in their cell with a bedsheet around his neck. It gives the reported text, including choosing the time to say goodbye. That is not proof against credible reporting; it is another credible report that the note existed, was released, and was being publicly reported in the suicide-note frame.\\n\\nThe defense says the source chain is weak because it runs through Tartaglione and his lawyers. That would be decisive if the question required the council to find, as a historical fact, that Epstein wrote it. But the actual standard is whether the note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Qualified reporting is still reporting. When multiple mainstream sources identify a court-released document as a purported or alleged Epstein suicide note, while openly preserving authentication caveats, the word \\\"purported\\\" does not nullify credibility. It defines the level of claim being credibly reported.\\n\\nThe same is true of intent. The defense isolates ambiguity in the short text, but the admitted reports did not label a random note after the fact. They described a document found after a suspected jail suicide attempt, released by a federal judge, containing the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye. Under a rule that includes final message or equivalent communication, that is enough for credible reporting of intent by a preponderance.\\n\\nSo the council can accept every defense caveat and still find for plaintiff. No official authentication; no signature; source-chain limits; DOJ first saw it in 2026. Those are reasons not to overstate actual authorship. They are not reasons to deny the narrower proposition that, by May 8, a publicly available note had been credibly reported as a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The record satisfies that proposition.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal says the defense is demanding actual-authorship certainty. That is not our position. The rule does not require a handwriting trial. But it does require more than credible reporting that someone claimed, labeled, or captioned a document as an alleged Epstein suicide note.\\n\\nPX-1 asks whether a qualifying note was written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, with credible reporting as the resolution source. The phrase \\\"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein\\\" cannot mean \\\"credibly reported to have been alleged or purported to be written by Epstein\\\" no matter how weak the source chain is. Otherwise the authorship requirement vanishes.\\n\\nThat is why DB-1/PX-R1 matters. Plaintiff treats it as harmless context for cautious wording. It is more than that. AP reports the government's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits on any DOJ lawyers in those proceedings. Those facts bear directly on whether the reporting consensus established Epstein authorship, not merely whether conclusive proof was absent.\\n\\nThe same point applies to intent. A line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the record also shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned document with grievance language and a disputed jail incident involving Tartaglione. The public reports responsibly used the suicide-note frame while preserving that uncertainty. That is not the same as a preponderance showing that the note was intended as a suicide note or final message.\\n\\nSo the defense is not asking the council to ignore credible reporting. We ask the council to read it accurately. The consensus is: a court released a document before May 8; credible outlets reported it as alleged or purported; and the same record preserved serious authorship, custody, and intent caveats. That proves public availability of a disputed document. It does not prove the full qualifying proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition should be found true by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe defense ultimately concedes the first and most concrete element: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. That concession is compelled by the record. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, shows Judge Karas granted access to the Note. PX-5, the Reuters Connect/SDNY handout caption, dates the released document image to May 6, 2026. PX-6 and PX-7 report the release the same day. There is no serious timing dispute left.\\n\\nThe real dispute is what level of certainty the proposition requires. The defense asks you to treat missing official authentication as fatal. But PX-1 does not make authentication the test. It sets a reporting-standard market: the source is consensus credible reporting, and the operative phrase here is that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\nThat standard is satisfied. PX-4 identifies the court-filed item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. PX-5 describes the released image as a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, described as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein, sourced to U.S. District Court/SDNY handout via Reuters. PX-6, AP/PBS, reports the public release, the Tartaglione discovery account, and the same goodbye language. PX-7, Guardian, independently reports the federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein, quotes the same text, and identifies the image as from the Southern District of New York.\\n\\nThat is not one stray allegation. It is an official court-access order plus Reuters image metadata and two independent mainstream reports, all before the deadline, all describing the same public document in substantially the same qualifying frame.\\n\\nThe defense's best contrary evidence, DB-1/PX-R1, is important but not dispositive. It says DOJ never had the note, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. It explains why the reports used careful words like alleged and purported. It does not erase the reports. In fact, it confirms the public release, the New York Times petition, Judge Karas's agreement, DOJ's non-objection, Tartaglione's discovery claim, and the note language.\\n\\nSo the council can accept every caveat and still answer yes. No signature; no official authentication; unclear actual authorship; source-chain limits through Tartaglione and his lawyers. Those are reasons to avoid saying \\\"Epstein definitely wrote it.\\\" The proposition does not ask for that. It asks whether the note had been publicly available and credibly reported as Epstein's suicide/final-message note. The record shows that it had.\\n\\nIntent is proved at the same reporting-standard level. The note's reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, its connection to Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and repeated public characterization as a suicide note or alleged suicide note are enough for a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The defense can point to ambiguity in the short text, but preponderance does not require eliminating ambiguity; it requires the more likely reading of the admitted record.\\n\\nIf the rule had required official authentication, the defense would have the stronger case. But that is not the rule. Under the actual wording and the evidence admitted here, the plaintiff has shown public availability by May 8 and a consensus of credible, qualified reporting that the document was a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The proposition is more likely true than false.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the final record proves one thing clearly: a document was publicly released before May 8. The defense has never needed to deny that. The proposition, however, asks for more. It asks whether a message or note had been made public and had been credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. Plaintiff has not carried that full burden.\\n\\nThe best way to see the gap is to compare plaintiff's closing formulation to the actual rule. Plaintiff closes by saying the record shows a publicly available note was credibly reported as a \\\"purported Epstein suicide/final-message note.\\\" But \\\"reported as purported\\\" is not the proposition. The proposition requires credible reporting that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying communication. The word \\\"purported\\\" matters because the sources used it to preserve uncertainty, not to resolve it.\\n\\nThe record evidence repeatedly stops short of plaintiff's needed inference. PX-4 is an official court-access order, but it describes an alleged note purportedly authored by Epstein and decides public access, not authorship, custody, or intent. PX-5 is a Reuters Connect caption for a third-party supplied, Reuters-processed image; it confirms circulation and a caption, not authenticity. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether Epstein wrote it.\\n\\nDB-1/PX-R1 is the strongest limiting evidence. AP reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits from sealed proceedings. That is not a minor caveat. It is the central provenance problem.\\n\\nIntent is likewise not proved by a preponderance. The line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the same record shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned note with grievance language, a disputed jail incident, and no authentication. Labeling that document a suicide note in headlines or captions does not establish that it was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\nThe defense is not asking for certainty or an official authentication requirement. We are asking the council to enforce all words of the proposition. Credible reporting can be the resolution source, but the reporting here is credible precisely because it preserves the unresolved issues: alleged, purported, unclear author, no signature, not verified, not in government death reports, not in DOJ files, not authenticated, and first seen by DOJ only after release.\\n\\nSo the right finding is narrow and faithful to the record: by May 8, a disputed document was publicly available and credibly reported as an alleged or purported Epstein suicide note. That is not enough. The full proposition remains more likely unproved than proved, and the council should answer no.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and May 8 market record\\n# Polymarket market record\\n\\nCaptured for case preparation on 2026-05-12.\\n\\n## Real market link\\n\\nCanonical event page:\\nhttps://polymarket.com/event/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\\n\\nPolymarket Gamma API endpoints captured under `etc/source-captures/`:\\n\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-event-slug.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events/slug/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-events-query.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-8.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-31.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31\\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-next-data-relevant.json` — sanitized relevant `__NEXT_DATA__` extract.\\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — page/API text extract.\\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — sanitized relevant HTML extract. Full page HTML was not retained because the page includes unnecessary discussion/profile data.\\n\\n## Event metadata from Polymarket Gamma API\\n\\n- Event id: `435920`\\n- Ticker/slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by`\\n- Title: `Epstein suicide note released by...?`\\n- Start date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.609296Z`\\n- Creation date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.60929Z`\\n- Event end date: `2026-05-31T00:00:00Z`\\n- Active: `true`\\n- Closed: `false`\\n- Archived: `false`\\n- Restricted: `true`\\n- Captured volume: about `13373621.098375008`\\n- Captured open interest: about `8163953.4680470005`\\n- Event metadata context captured by Polymarket on 2026-05-12 stated that a U.S. District Judge in New York unsealed a purported suicide note attributed to Jeffrey Epstein on May 7, 2026, but also described authenticity and intent doubts. This platform context is preserved as market metadata, not as independent proof of the proposition.\\n\\n## Exact official market rule text\\n\\nThe Polymarket page and Gamma API expose this description:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to “Yes” if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, is made publicly available by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e A qualifying note must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and have been intended to be a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e A qualifying message or note may be made widely available to the public by any means, regardless of whether it is released officially, leaked, or otherwise disclosed.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Market at issue for this arbitration\\n\\nPrimary disputed market:\\n\\n- Market id: `2128535`\\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 8?`\\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8`\\n- Condition id: `0x5e5482b1e2afa7bed0b9a0c3c8ad33a83dd6cc6d649666cdf1977be64c42c82a`\\n- Question id: `0x5ca4d636407564494e9149eb951896ff88923cef8d24c137707e4cff84b4d878`\\n- Group item title: `May 8`\\n- Outcomes: `[\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]`\\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\\\"0.0005\\\", \\\"0.9995\\\"]`\\n- Active: `true`\\n- Closed: `false`\\n- Accepting orders: `true`\\n- UMA resolution status in API: `disputed`\\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]`\\n- Page-visible status captured from HTML/readable extraction: `Outcome proposed: Yes`; `Disputed`; `Outcome proposed: No`; `Disputed`; `Final review`.\\n\\nThe API field `endDateIso` is `2026-05-31` because the event contains both May 8 and May 31 grouped markets. For the May 8 market, the listed date in the market question and group item is May 8. The arbitration proposition therefore uses May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\n## Other grouped market preserved for context\\n\\nSecondary grouped market, not the disputed condition tested here:\\n\\n- Market id: `2128536`\\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 31?`\\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31`\\n- Condition id: `0x6bf3aa7d5186804e967e1e4737c896778f688e6dafdd0a1b659a4a07bf27d663`\\n- Group item title: `May 31`\\n- Outcomes: `[\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]`\\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\\\"0.145\\\", \\\"0.855\\\"]`\\n- Active: `true`\\n- Closed: `false`\\n- Accepting orders: `true`\\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[]`\\n\\n## Arbitration framing\\n\\nThe arbitration does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any market participant was correct. It asks the factual condition directly: whether the qualifying note/message had been publicly available by the May 8 listed deadline under the rule words.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Initial primary/near-primary reporting map\\n# Primary and near-primary evidence map\\n\\nThis is a minimal open-record source map, not a closed-record exhibit packet.\\n\\n## Reuters\\n\\nURL: https://www.reuters.com/world/us/new-york-judge-releases-purported-epstein-suicide-note-2026-05-07/\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e May 6 (Reuters) - A federal judge on Wednesday released a document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein and including the line: \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one’s time to say goodbye.\\\"\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The handwritten note was said to have been found by his former jail cellmate, convicted murderer and ex‑police officer Nicholas Tartaglione. U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas, who oversaw the Tartaglione case, released the note after a request by The New York Times, which reported its existence last week.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The judge found no legal reason to keep it under seal. But nor did he vouch for the note's authenticity, nor assess its chain of custody.\\n\\nReuters also quoted the note text as released in the court file:\\n\\n\\u003e \\\"They investigated me for month - Found NOTHING!!! So 15 year old charges resulted,” the note says, according to an image of it released in the court file. \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose ones time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Burst out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\n## NPR\\n\\nURL: https://www.npr.org/2026/05/07/nx-s1-5814808/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from the New York Times, which reported on its existence last week.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e NPR has not independently verified the authenticity of the note. The five sentences on a sheet of lined paper read in part: \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do — Bust out cryin!! NO FUN — NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nNPR also reported a material authentication limitation:\\n\\n\\u003e The Department of Justice told NPR over email on Thursday that the note has not yet been authenticated, adding, \\\"this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well.\\\"\\n\\n## BBC\\n\\nURL: https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cd7pd0rqwreo\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e A US judge has ordered the release of a document purported to be a suicide note written by convicted sex offender Jeffrey Epstein a month before his death.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e A copy of the handwritten note unsealed on Wednesday mentions a months-long investigation that \\\"found nothing\\\", and says \\\"it is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The BBC has not verified that the note was written by Epstein, and US authorities have not commented.\\n\\nBBC also reported:\\n\\n\\u003e The note amounts to only seven lines of text, leaving uncertainty over its purported meaning.\\n\\n## Guardian\\n\\nURL: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Epstein’s cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, Nicholas Tartaglione, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before he was eventually found dead in his jail cell.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return the Guardian’s request for comment.\\n\\n## Notes for advocates\\n\\nThe strongest pro-demonstrated path is that multiple credible outlets reported public release before May 8, described the document as a purported/alleged suicide note, quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, and identified a federal judge/court-file release.\\n\\nThe strongest not-demonstrated path is that those same outlets used hedging language, reported lack of independent verification or official authentication, and left uncertainty about whether the note was intended as a suicide note rather than another communication later characterized as one.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Initial official-source limitations map\\n# Official source record\\n\\n## Market-specified resolution source\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule specifies no government docket, agency, publisher, or single official source. The exact source rule is:\\n\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Official public-record materials identified during minimal case setup\\n\\nThis packet is for an open-record/search-enabled run. I did not build a closed-record evidence packet. The public record identified during setup indicates that U.S. District Judge Kenneth M. Karas of the Southern District of New York unsealed a one-page note in connection with the Nicholas Tartaglione criminal case, after a New York Times request.\\n\\nLocal source capture of the court PDF/order is not included. The available captured public reporting says:\\n\\n- BBC reported that Judge Karas ordered release of the document, that the note was accompanied by a May 2021 letter submitted by former Tartaglione lawyer John A. Wieder, and that Karas wrote that public access to the note promotes accountability and public confidence in the administration of justice.\\n- Reuters reported that Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody.\\n- NPR reported that District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from The New York Times.\\n\\n## Official-source limitations\\n\\n- The source rule does not require an official release. It permits a qualifying note to be made public officially, by leak, or by other disclosure.\\n- The local packet does not contain the SDNY docket entry, order, or note image as a primary court PDF. Attorneys in the open-record run should search for those documents.\\n- Public reporting preserved here states that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide intent.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 SDNY May 6 unsealing order extraction\\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\\n\\nCaption and opening: \\\"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\\\"\\n\\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \\\"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\\\"\\n\\nBackground: \\\"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\\\"\\n\\nThe Times request: \\\"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\\\"\\n\\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\\n\\nPublic-access analysis: \\\"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\\\"\\n\\nThe order further concludes: \\\"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\\\"\\n\\nAnd: \\\"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\\\"\\n\\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Reuters Connect SDNY handout caption metadata\\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nPage heading: \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nCaption text: \\\"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\\\"\\n\\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-6 PBS/AP May 6-7 report extraction\\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\\\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\\n\\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\\n\\nHeadline: \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\\\"\\n\\nIt reports that \\\"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\\n\\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\" and says it continued, \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye,\\\" followed by \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\" The article says the note concludes: \\\"NO FUN\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \\\"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\\\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-7 Guardian May 6 report extraction\\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\\\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\\n\\nHeadline/subhead: \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\\\"; \\\"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\\n\\nThe article's image caption identifies: \\\"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the note: \\\"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\\\" and \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"The note does not include a signature.\\\" It also states: \\\"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\\\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-1 AP/DOJ authentication and source-chain limits\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-2 SDNY order shows public-access ruling, alleged/purported framing\\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\\n\\nCaption and opening: \\\"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\\\"\\n\\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \\\"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\\\"\\n\\nBackground: \\\"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\\\"\\n\\nThe Times request: \\\"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\\\"\\n\\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\\n\\nPublic-access analysis: \\\"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\\\"\\n\\nThe order further concludes: \\\"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\\\"\\n\\nAnd: \\\"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\\\"\\n\\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-3 PBS/AP preserves uncertainty and government-report omissions\\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\\\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\\n\\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\\n\\nHeadline: \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\\\"\\n\\nIt reports that \\\"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\\n\\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\" and says it continued, \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye,\\\" followed by \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\" The article says the note concludes: \\\"NO FUN\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \\\"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\\\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-4 Guardian preserves no-signature and no-verification caveats\\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\\\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\\n\\nHeadline/subhead: \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\\\"; \\\"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\\n\\nThe article's image caption identifies: \\\"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the note: \\\"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\\\" and \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"The note does not include a signature.\\\" It also states: \\\"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\\\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-5 Reuters Connect caption and third-party image limitations\\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nPage heading: \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nCaption text: \\\"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\\\"\\n\\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 AP/DOJ authentication-limit report in context\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\n[defendant] DS-1 AP/DOJ source-chain and authentication limits\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] SDNY May 6, 2026 Tartaglione unsealing order - relevant extracted text (ev_0ed0ef50e84e_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-0ed0ef50e84e)\\nSource: https://www.nysd.uscourts.gov/sites/default/files/2026-05/16cr832%20-%20Tartaglione%20Order%20-%2026.5.6.pdf\\nSHA-256: `0ed0ef50e84e5f90a63aeefcb840f628038958b10acf229c44b4babea0c133e9`\\nBytes: 2992\\nRelevance: Official court source for public release/unsealing. It proves the court granted access to the note and identifies it as a suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione attorneys; it also shows the order was about public access, not authenticity.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] PBS/AP May 6-7, 2026 report on Epstein note release - relevant extracted text (ev_757899113d89_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-757899113d89)\\nSource: https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/judge-releases-note-that-cellmate-says-he-found-after-epsteins-suspected-suicide-attempt\\nSHA-256: `757899113d8967676e74909d141f7d97d4735bd8d75a4af34fb3950b18d871e1`\\nBytes: 2552\\nRelevance: Corroborates that the note was publicly reported before May 8, 2026; identifies Judge Karas release, NYT petition, Tartaglione discovery claim, note language supporting final-message intent, and adverse uncertainty about authorship and government-report omissions.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 6, 2026 report on alleged Epstein suicide note - relevant extracted text (ev_be7a5dd8c524_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-be7a5dd8c524)\\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\\nSHA-256: `be7a5dd8c524bf01aaffc12daeeedace9153fd057fc82c3ada197c2b30db71ce`\\nBytes: 2014\\nRelevance: Independent mainstream public reporting before the May 8 deadline; describes first public availability, attributes image to U.S. District Judge/Southern District of New York, quotes note language, and preserves authorship caveats.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Reuters Connect May 6, 2026 image-caption record for Epstein note (ev_58561d19c453_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-58561d19c453)\\nSource: https://www.reutersconnect.com/item/document-described-as-a-suicide-note-purportedly-written-by-the-late-jeffrey-epstein/dGFnOnJldXRlcnMuY29tLDIwMjY6bmV3c21sX1JDMlQzTEFMMEM2Ng\\nSHA-256: `58561d19c4537e7f3ade428fefe955b34c55ca688a331faa72187770ee5c8716`\\nBytes: 1360\\nRelevance: Near-primary image-caption record from Reuters/SDNY handout. It directly describes the publicly released document image, includes the key goodbye line, dates the release to May 6, 2026, and identifies the source as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] AP May 7, 2026 report: DOJ seeing Epstein note for first time and authentication limits (ev_5aa56aab2530_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-5aa56aab2530)\\nSource: https://apnews.com/article/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note-5297f49736e625a06d0db3c7b737b997\\nSHA-256: `5aa56aab25302158d1be6b80426ed4d517ee436cea958297c34e648148db2bca`\\nBytes: 2780\\nRelevance: Defense evidence on provenance, custody, and authentication. It reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, that the note came through an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, that it was in a court vault since 2021, and that DOJ lawyers involved in sealed proceedings could not disclose anything due to privilege restrictions.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Source search and capture ledger\\nBefore filing, plaintiff checked the current record and evidence list, reviewed the defendant opening, and targeted the missing source classes identified by the packet: official SDNY court material, the public image/caption record, and independent mainstream reporting. Searches used exact phrases including the note's reported goodbye line, Tartaglione/Karas/SDNY terms, and source-specific Reuters/PBS/Guardian queries. The official SDNY PDF was downloaded locally on 2026-06-30T04:33:49Z, size 128,992 bytes, sha256 7225441cb802084e2b9485ebc2c6d246fbfa08e109fe650cb14f445dc4745ca0; local pdftotext was unavailable, so a relevant text extraction was admitted instead. Reuters Connect metadata, PBS/AP, and Guardian extracts were admitted. Remaining gaps: no binary PDF exhibit, no licensed Reuters image download, no full NYT article capture, and no official authentication finding. These gaps affect actual authorship weight but do not defeat the reporting-standard proposition.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-search and evidence ledger\\nDefense re-scanned the record and read the four new plaintiff evidence extracts. Targeted investigation checked direct AP/DOJ source-chain reporting, NYT authentication follow-up leads, and media mirrors. The defense submitted the direct AP extraction as DB-1 because it preserved the strongest provenance and authentication limits: DOJ never had the note, it had not been authenticated, DOJ was seeing it for the first time, and any DOJ lawyers in sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings could not disclose protected material. Remaining unresolved gaps: no full NYT authentication article, no binary/unprocessed note image, no custodian affidavit, and no handwriting or official authorship finding.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T05:02:11.941771357Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":892433,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":17,\"version\":26}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 26\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex08-20260630042402\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 892433\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":26,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex08-20260630042402\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff's case is about the precise wording of the proposition, not about proving beyond doubt that Jeffrey Epstein actually wrote the document. The question is whether, by May 8, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a note or message had been made publicly available and had been credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. On the current packet, the answer is more likely than not yes.\\n\\nThe market rule preserved in the packet is important. It does not demand a definitive handwriting authentication, a government finding, or a single official resolution source. It asks for a message or note that was publicly available, credibly reported as Epstein's, and treated as a suicide note/final-message equivalent, with resolution by consensus credible reporting. That framing matters because the public record is cautious but not empty: the packet's reporting map identifies Reuters, NPR/AP, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times leads around the same court release.\\n\\nThe evidence we have now already shows the core chronology. A federal judge, Kenneth Karas of the Southern District of New York, unsealed or released a one-page note connected to Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's former cellmate. The reporting captured in the packet places that release before the May 8 deadline. Reuters described a document released by the judge as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein and quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye. NPR/AP reported that the judge unsealed the one-page note after a New York Times petition and quoted the same goodbye language. BBC and Guardian reporting likewise described an alleged or purported suicide note, publicly released by a federal judge, and described its contents in terms consistent with a final communication.\\n\\nThose reports are not marginal internet rumor. They are mainstream, named news organizations reporting on a court-unsealed document. The note's public availability is therefore the strongest element: multiple reports describe the court release itself before the deadline, and the Polymarket packet separately records that the market page understood the disputed question as the May 8 grouped market.\\n\\nThe hard issue is weight, not existence. The same packet preserves the caveats. The court did not vouch for authenticity. Several outlets used words like alleged or purported. NPR, BBC, and Guardian noted they had not independently verified authorship, and NPR/AP reported uncertainty about who wrote the note. The official-source file says the packet does not yet include the SDNY docket PDF, the unsealing order PDF, or the note image as local official exhibits. Those gaps should make the council cautious about any argument that Epstein's authorship has been conclusively proved.\\n\\nBut the proposition does not require conclusive proof of authorship. It requires that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Responsible hedging in credible reports does not erase credibility; it often demonstrates it. The reports identified a court release, a claimed source chain through Tartaglione and his lawyers, and the note text. That is enough at opening to frame the plaintiff's burden as a preponderance question: did credible public reporting, before May 8, make available and describe the note in the qualifying way? The packet points strongly toward yes.\\n\\nIntent is similar. The note need not be a formal, signed will or declaration. The rule allows a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, together with the context of Epstein's suspected July 2019 attempt and later death, is why credible outlets characterized it as a suicide note or alleged suicide note. The defense may argue the short, unsigned text is ambiguous. That is a fair limitation, but it does not defeat the more modest proposition that it was credibly reported as such.\\n\\nIn later evidentiary phases, the decisive documents should be added directly: the SDNY unsealing order and any released note image or court handout, the full Reuters/AP/Guardian/NYT materials, and the best adverse materials showing the limits of authentication and chain of custody. For now, the opening theory is straightforward: the record already shows a public court release before the deadline and a consensus of credible reporting that treated the document as a purported Epstein suicide or final-message note. The remaining disputes affect weight; they do not change the plaintiff's burden from preponderance into certainty.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the whole proposition, not merely that a provocative document was released by a court before May 8.\\n\\nThe record likely supports one element. The packet describes a public release or unsealing connected to Judge Kenneth Karas and the Tartaglione criminal case before the listed deadline. We do not need to pretend otherwise. But the market rule asks for more: a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The packet itself flags why those added elements are not established on this record.\\n\\nStart with provenance. The official-source packet says the local record does not contain the SDNY docket entry, unsealing order, or the released note image as a primary court exhibit. More importantly, it says the public reporting preserved here reports that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide its intent. Reuters, as summarized in the packet, reported that Judge Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody. That is a public-access ruling, not proof that the note was Epstein's.\\n\\nThe reporting evidence has the same problem. The packet's strongest plaintiff sources repeatedly use limiting words: purported, alleged, described as, said to have been found. NPR says it had not independently verified authenticity and adds a material DOJ limitation: the note had not yet been authenticated and this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. BBC likewise says it had not verified the note was written by Epstein and reports that authorities had not commented. Guardian says it had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. Those caveats are not incidental. They go directly to the proposition's phrase \\\"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nIntent is also unresolved. The packet quotes language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also preserves the rest of the reported text: complaints about being investigated, references to old charges, and emotional language about crying and not being worth it. The BBC summary says the note was only seven lines and left uncertainty over its purported meaning. A short, unsigned, unauthenticated text can be later characterized as a suicide note without having been shown to be intended as one. The rule includes final message or equivalent communication, but it still requires intent, not merely a news label attached after release.\\n\\nThe plaintiff will argue that consensus credible reporting is enough and that the rule does not require conclusive authentication. That is partly right but incomplete. The standard is preponderance, not certainty, and the source rule is credible reporting, not an official government determination. But credible reporting of uncertainty is still uncertainty. When the same credible reports say they cannot verify authorship, that DOJ had not authenticated it, and that the judge did not assess custody, the council should not convert cautious reporting into affirmative proof.\\n\\nThe current packet is best understood as a roadmap, not a completed proof. It identifies the sources that matter: the court order and docket material, the released note image, the full reporting from Reuters, NPR, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times, and especially any authentication follow-up. Those materials may eventually show whether there was enough consensus to resolve yes. But at opening, the defense theory is that the admitted packet proves a public dispute over an alleged note, while leaving the decisive links missing: authorship, chain of custody, and intent. If those links remain missing, the proposition should not be found proved by a preponderance.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the admitted record now proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with the governing condition. PX-1 states the market would resolve yes if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication, was made publicly available by the listed date, and that the resolution source would be a consensus of credible reporting. The rule does not require a handwriting trial, a DOJ authentication letter, or an official source as the only path. It asks whether there was credible public reporting of the qualifying note by May 8, 2026.\\n\\nPublic availability is established. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, is an official court source. Judge Karas described the requested item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The order granted the Times' request to unseal the Note and held that it was a judicial document subject to public access. PX-5 then supplies the Reuters Connect image-caption record: a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye was seen after release by Judge Karas in New York City on May 6, 2026, with the source identified as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters. PX-6 and PX-7 independently report the same public release on May 6, before the May 8 deadline.\\n\\nCredible reporting of Epstein authorship is also established, in the exact qualified sense the proposition uses. PX-5 describes the document as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein. PX-6 reports that Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found the note after Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and that Karas ordered its release after the Times sought unsealing. PX-7 reports a federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein and identifies the alleged note image as from the United States district judge/Southern District of New York. These are not anonymous posts or market chatter; they are an official court order plus Reuters metadata, AP/PBS, and Guardian reporting.\\n\\nIntent is satisfied by both text and reporting context. PX-5 identifies the key line: \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.\\\" PX-6 reports the same language and the surrounding statements, including \\\"NO FUN\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT!!\\\" PX-7 likewise quotes the goodbye language and describes the release as an alleged suicide note. The rule allows not only a formal suicide note but also a final message or equivalent communication. A short note saying it is a treat to choose one's time to say goodbye, reported in connection with Epstein's suspected suicide attempt and later death, easily crosses the preponderance threshold for being credibly reported as a suicide/final-message equivalent.\\n\\nThe defense is right about one thing: the record does not conclusively authenticate the note as Epstein's handwriting. The plaintiff does not need to hide that. PX-3 and the newly admitted sources preserve the limitations. PX-4 is a public-access order, not a handwriting finding. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports, and that Epstein had reportedly accused Tartaglione. PX-7 says the note lacks a signature and that Guardian had not independently verified authorship. Those caveats would matter if the proposition asked, \\\"Did Epstein actually write an authenticated suicide note?\\\" It does not.\\n\\nThe actual proposition asks whether a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, and whether it had been made public by the deadline. Hedged words like alleged and purported are not fatal under that standard; they are how responsible outlets report an attributed document whose authenticity has not been finally adjudicated. The credible-reporting consensus is that a court-released document, sourced to SDNY/Reuters handout and reported by AP/PBS and Guardian, was publicly available on May 6 and was described as an Epstein suicide note or alleged suicide note.\\n\\nThe missing links therefore reduce certainty about actual authorship, not the reporting-standard proposition. By May 8, the public had the court release and mainstream reporting describing the note in qualifying terms. On this record, yes is more likely than no.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, after plaintiff's new evidence, the defense does not contest the easy part: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. The question is whether the record proves the qualifying proposition as written: a note credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The record still falls short.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's best evidence proves public access, not authenticity. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, describes the item as an alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The court's legal holding was that the Note was subject to the presumption of public access because it had been submitted in connection with a Curcio hearing in Tartaglione's case. That explains why the public could see it. It does not decide who wrote it, whether its custody was reliable, or what the writer intended.\\n\\nThe source chain is unusually weak for a preponderance finding on authorship. The asserted chain is not Epstein to jail officials to investigators. It is Tartaglione, a convicted murderer and Epstein's former cellmate, saying he found a note in a book, then giving it to his lawyers, after which it became part of sealed attorney-client/conflict proceedings in Tartaglione's case. DB-1, the direct AP report, adds the central official limitation: DOJ's explanation was that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. AP also reports that if DOJ lawyers saw material in the sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings, they were barred from disclosing it. That is not just a missing authentication stamp; it is a source-chain problem.\\n\\nThe mainstream reports do not create the consensus plaintiff needs. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in the government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's recent files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. PX-5, the Reuters Connect caption, is useful proof that an image/caption circulated, but it expressly calls the image third-party supplied and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version elsewhere. A caption saying \\\"purportedly written\\\" is not a finding that credible reporting established authorship.\\n\\nPlaintiff says hedged words like alleged and purported are normal reporting practice. Sometimes they are. Here they are doing real evidentiary work. Every key source preserved in the record either avoids endorsing authorship or reports affirmative reasons for doubt: no signature, no authentication, DOJ had not seen it, no appearance in official Epstein-death reports, no appearance in DOJ's files release, and a chain originating with Tartaglione. The proposition uses the phrase \\\"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\\\" On this record, the credible reporting consensus is that a note was claimed or described as Epstein's, while authorship remained unresolved.\\n\\nIntent is no stronger. The reported text includes a line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also includes complaints about investigations, old charges, crying, \\\"NO FUN,\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT.\\\" DB-1 describes the note as short, hard to decipher in places, and not authenticated. PX-6 and PX-7 connect it to Epstein's July 2019 suspected attempt, but the same record says Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, later recanted, and was placed briefly on suicide watch before being downgraded. A later news label of \\\"suicide note\\\" cannot substitute for proof that this unsigned ambiguous document was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\nThis is not an argument for certainty as the standard. It is an argument for applying all elements of the rule. The plaintiff has shown public availability and public controversy. It has shown that several credible outlets responsibly repeated a characterization while preserving doubts. It has not shown that the consensus of credible reporting made it more likely than not that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying suicide/final-message communication.\\n\\nThe council should weigh plaintiff's exhibits for what they actually prove. PX-4 proves unsealing. PX-5 proves a Reuters/SDNY handout caption. PX-6 and PX-7 prove timely public reporting, but also preserve the core doubts. DB-1 gives the most direct official-source-chain limit: DOJ never had it, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. On the complete record, the proposition remains unproved by a preponderance.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense argument proves too much by quietly changing the question.\\n\\nThe proposition does not ask whether a court, DOJ, or handwriting expert finally authenticated Epstein's authorship. It asks whether, by May 8, a publicly available note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. That is why PX-1 makes consensus credible reporting the resolution source. The defense's evidence attacks a different proposition: actual authorship certainty.\\n\\nPX-R1 is useful, but not in the way the defense claims. It says DOJ never had the note, that it had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. Those facts explain why careful outlets used words like alleged and purported. They do not erase the fact that AP, Reuters Connect, Guardian, and the SDNY order all publicly described the same court-released item in the qualifying terms before the deadline.\\n\\nIndeed, PX-R1 confirms several plaintiff points. It says the note was made public, that The New York Times petitioned Judge Karas to release it, that Judge Karas agreed, and that DOJ did not object. It repeats Tartaglione's claim that he found the handwritten note after Epstein was found in their cell with a bedsheet around his neck. It gives the reported text, including choosing the time to say goodbye. That is not proof against credible reporting; it is another credible report that the note existed, was released, and was being publicly reported in the suicide-note frame.\\n\\nThe defense says the source chain is weak because it runs through Tartaglione and his lawyers. That would be decisive if the question required the council to find, as a historical fact, that Epstein wrote it. But the actual standard is whether the note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Qualified reporting is still reporting. When multiple mainstream sources identify a court-released document as a purported or alleged Epstein suicide note, while openly preserving authentication caveats, the word \\\"purported\\\" does not nullify credibility. It defines the level of claim being credibly reported.\\n\\nThe same is true of intent. The defense isolates ambiguity in the short text, but the admitted reports did not label a random note after the fact. They described a document found after a suspected jail suicide attempt, released by a federal judge, containing the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye. Under a rule that includes final message or equivalent communication, that is enough for credible reporting of intent by a preponderance.\\n\\nSo the council can accept every defense caveat and still find for plaintiff. No official authentication; no signature; source-chain limits; DOJ first saw it in 2026. Those are reasons not to overstate actual authorship. They are not reasons to deny the narrower proposition that, by May 8, a publicly available note had been credibly reported as a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The record satisfies that proposition.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal says the defense is demanding actual-authorship certainty. That is not our position. The rule does not require a handwriting trial. But it does require more than credible reporting that someone claimed, labeled, or captioned a document as an alleged Epstein suicide note.\\n\\nPX-1 asks whether a qualifying note was written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, with credible reporting as the resolution source. The phrase \\\"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein\\\" cannot mean \\\"credibly reported to have been alleged or purported to be written by Epstein\\\" no matter how weak the source chain is. Otherwise the authorship requirement vanishes.\\n\\nThat is why DB-1/PX-R1 matters. Plaintiff treats it as harmless context for cautious wording. It is more than that. AP reports the government's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits on any DOJ lawyers in those proceedings. Those facts bear directly on whether the reporting consensus established Epstein authorship, not merely whether conclusive proof was absent.\\n\\nThe same point applies to intent. A line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the record also shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned document with grievance language and a disputed jail incident involving Tartaglione. The public reports responsibly used the suicide-note frame while preserving that uncertainty. That is not the same as a preponderance showing that the note was intended as a suicide note or final message.\\n\\nSo the defense is not asking the council to ignore credible reporting. We ask the council to read it accurately. The consensus is: a court released a document before May 8; credible outlets reported it as alleged or purported; and the same record preserved serious authorship, custody, and intent caveats. That proves public availability of a disputed document. It does not prove the full qualifying proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition should be found true by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe defense ultimately concedes the first and most concrete element: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. That concession is compelled by the record. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, shows Judge Karas granted access to the Note. PX-5, the Reuters Connect/SDNY handout caption, dates the released document image to May 6, 2026. PX-6 and PX-7 report the release the same day. There is no serious timing dispute left.\\n\\nThe real dispute is what level of certainty the proposition requires. The defense asks you to treat missing official authentication as fatal. But PX-1 does not make authentication the test. It sets a reporting-standard market: the source is consensus credible reporting, and the operative phrase here is that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\nThat standard is satisfied. PX-4 identifies the court-filed item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. PX-5 describes the released image as a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, described as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein, sourced to U.S. District Court/SDNY handout via Reuters. PX-6, AP/PBS, reports the public release, the Tartaglione discovery account, and the same goodbye language. PX-7, Guardian, independently reports the federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein, quotes the same text, and identifies the image as from the Southern District of New York.\\n\\nThat is not one stray allegation. It is an official court-access order plus Reuters image metadata and two independent mainstream reports, all before the deadline, all describing the same public document in substantially the same qualifying frame.\\n\\nThe defense's best contrary evidence, DB-1/PX-R1, is important but not dispositive. It says DOJ never had the note, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. It explains why the reports used careful words like alleged and purported. It does not erase the reports. In fact, it confirms the public release, the New York Times petition, Judge Karas's agreement, DOJ's non-objection, Tartaglione's discovery claim, and the note language.\\n\\nSo the council can accept every caveat and still answer yes. No signature; no official authentication; unclear actual authorship; source-chain limits through Tartaglione and his lawyers. Those are reasons to avoid saying \\\"Epstein definitely wrote it.\\\" The proposition does not ask for that. It asks whether the note had been publicly available and credibly reported as Epstein's suicide/final-message note. The record shows that it had.\\n\\nIntent is proved at the same reporting-standard level. The note's reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, its connection to Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and repeated public characterization as a suicide note or alleged suicide note are enough for a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The defense can point to ambiguity in the short text, but preponderance does not require eliminating ambiguity; it requires the more likely reading of the admitted record.\\n\\nIf the rule had required official authentication, the defense would have the stronger case. But that is not the rule. Under the actual wording and the evidence admitted here, the plaintiff has shown public availability by May 8 and a consensus of credible, qualified reporting that the document was a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The proposition is more likely true than false.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the final record proves one thing clearly: a document was publicly released before May 8. The defense has never needed to deny that. The proposition, however, asks for more. It asks whether a message or note had been made public and had been credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. Plaintiff has not carried that full burden.\\n\\nThe best way to see the gap is to compare plaintiff's closing formulation to the actual rule. Plaintiff closes by saying the record shows a publicly available note was credibly reported as a \\\"purported Epstein suicide/final-message note.\\\" But \\\"reported as purported\\\" is not the proposition. The proposition requires credible reporting that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying communication. The word \\\"purported\\\" matters because the sources used it to preserve uncertainty, not to resolve it.\\n\\nThe record evidence repeatedly stops short of plaintiff's needed inference. PX-4 is an official court-access order, but it describes an alleged note purportedly authored by Epstein and decides public access, not authorship, custody, or intent. PX-5 is a Reuters Connect caption for a third-party supplied, Reuters-processed image; it confirms circulation and a caption, not authenticity. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether Epstein wrote it.\\n\\nDB-1/PX-R1 is the strongest limiting evidence. AP reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits from sealed proceedings. That is not a minor caveat. It is the central provenance problem.\\n\\nIntent is likewise not proved by a preponderance. The line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the same record shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned note with grievance language, a disputed jail incident, and no authentication. Labeling that document a suicide note in headlines or captions does not establish that it was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\nThe defense is not asking for certainty or an official authentication requirement. We are asking the council to enforce all words of the proposition. Credible reporting can be the resolution source, but the reporting here is credible precisely because it preserves the unresolved issues: alleged, purported, unclear author, no signature, not verified, not in government death reports, not in DOJ files, not authenticated, and first seen by DOJ only after release.\\n\\nSo the right finding is narrow and faithful to the record: by May 8, a disputed document was publicly available and credibly reported as an alleged or purported Epstein suicide note. That is not enough. The full proposition remains more likely unproved than proved, and the council should answer no.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and May 8 market record\\n# Polymarket market record\\n\\nCaptured for case preparation on 2026-05-12.\\n\\n## Real market link\\n\\nCanonical event page:\\nhttps://polymarket.com/event/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\\n\\nPolymarket Gamma API endpoints captured under `etc/source-captures/`:\\n\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-event-slug.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events/slug/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-events-query.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-8.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8\\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-31.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31\\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-next-data-relevant.json` — sanitized relevant `__NEXT_DATA__` extract.\\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — page/API text extract.\\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — sanitized relevant HTML extract. Full page HTML was not retained because the page includes unnecessary discussion/profile data.\\n\\n## Event metadata from Polymarket Gamma API\\n\\n- Event id: `435920`\\n- Ticker/slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by`\\n- Title: `Epstein suicide note released by...?`\\n- Start date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.609296Z`\\n- Creation date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.60929Z`\\n- Event end date: `2026-05-31T00:00:00Z`\\n- Active: `true`\\n- Closed: `false`\\n- Archived: `false`\\n- Restricted: `true`\\n- Captured volume: about `13373621.098375008`\\n- Captured open interest: about `8163953.4680470005`\\n- Event metadata context captured by Polymarket on 2026-05-12 stated that a U.S. District Judge in New York unsealed a purported suicide note attributed to Jeffrey Epstein on May 7, 2026, but also described authenticity and intent doubts. This platform context is preserved as market metadata, not as independent proof of the proposition.\\n\\n## Exact official market rule text\\n\\nThe Polymarket page and Gamma API expose this description:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to “Yes” if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, is made publicly available by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e A qualifying note must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and have been intended to be a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e A qualifying message or note may be made widely available to the public by any means, regardless of whether it is released officially, leaked, or otherwise disclosed.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Market at issue for this arbitration\\n\\nPrimary disputed market:\\n\\n- Market id: `2128535`\\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 8?`\\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8`\\n- Condition id: `0x5e5482b1e2afa7bed0b9a0c3c8ad33a83dd6cc6d649666cdf1977be64c42c82a`\\n- Question id: `0x5ca4d636407564494e9149eb951896ff88923cef8d24c137707e4cff84b4d878`\\n- Group item title: `May 8`\\n- Outcomes: `[\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]`\\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\\\"0.0005\\\", \\\"0.9995\\\"]`\\n- Active: `true`\\n- Closed: `false`\\n- Accepting orders: `true`\\n- UMA resolution status in API: `disputed`\\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]`\\n- Page-visible status captured from HTML/readable extraction: `Outcome proposed: Yes`; `Disputed`; `Outcome proposed: No`; `Disputed`; `Final review`.\\n\\nThe API field `endDateIso` is `2026-05-31` because the event contains both May 8 and May 31 grouped markets. For the May 8 market, the listed date in the market question and group item is May 8. The arbitration proposition therefore uses May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\n## Other grouped market preserved for context\\n\\nSecondary grouped market, not the disputed condition tested here:\\n\\n- Market id: `2128536`\\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 31?`\\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31`\\n- Condition id: `0x6bf3aa7d5186804e967e1e4737c896778f688e6dafdd0a1b659a4a07bf27d663`\\n- Group item title: `May 31`\\n- Outcomes: `[\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]`\\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\\\"0.145\\\", \\\"0.855\\\"]`\\n- Active: `true`\\n- Closed: `false`\\n- Accepting orders: `true`\\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[]`\\n\\n## Arbitration framing\\n\\nThe arbitration does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any market participant was correct. It asks the factual condition directly: whether the qualifying note/message had been publicly available by the May 8 listed deadline under the rule words.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Initial primary/near-primary reporting map\\n# Primary and near-primary evidence map\\n\\nThis is a minimal open-record source map, not a closed-record exhibit packet.\\n\\n## Reuters\\n\\nURL: https://www.reuters.com/world/us/new-york-judge-releases-purported-epstein-suicide-note-2026-05-07/\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e May 6 (Reuters) - A federal judge on Wednesday released a document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein and including the line: \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one’s time to say goodbye.\\\"\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The handwritten note was said to have been found by his former jail cellmate, convicted murderer and ex‑police officer Nicholas Tartaglione. U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas, who oversaw the Tartaglione case, released the note after a request by The New York Times, which reported its existence last week.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The judge found no legal reason to keep it under seal. But nor did he vouch for the note's authenticity, nor assess its chain of custody.\\n\\nReuters also quoted the note text as released in the court file:\\n\\n\\u003e \\\"They investigated me for month - Found NOTHING!!! So 15 year old charges resulted,” the note says, according to an image of it released in the court file. \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose ones time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Burst out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\n## NPR\\n\\nURL: https://www.npr.org/2026/05/07/nx-s1-5814808/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from the New York Times, which reported on its existence last week.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e NPR has not independently verified the authenticity of the note. The five sentences on a sheet of lined paper read in part: \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do — Bust out cryin!! NO FUN — NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nNPR also reported a material authentication limitation:\\n\\n\\u003e The Department of Justice told NPR over email on Thursday that the note has not yet been authenticated, adding, \\\"this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well.\\\"\\n\\n## BBC\\n\\nURL: https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cd7pd0rqwreo\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e A US judge has ordered the release of a document purported to be a suicide note written by convicted sex offender Jeffrey Epstein a month before his death.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e A copy of the handwritten note unsealed on Wednesday mentions a months-long investigation that \\\"found nothing\\\", and says \\\"it is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The BBC has not verified that the note was written by Epstein, and US authorities have not commented.\\n\\nBBC also reported:\\n\\n\\u003e The note amounts to only seven lines of text, leaving uncertainty over its purported meaning.\\n\\n## Guardian\\n\\nURL: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\\n\\nCaptured excerpt:\\n\\n\\u003e A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Epstein’s cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, Nicholas Tartaglione, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before he was eventually found dead in his jail cell.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return the Guardian’s request for comment.\\n\\n## Notes for advocates\\n\\nThe strongest pro-demonstrated path is that multiple credible outlets reported public release before May 8, described the document as a purported/alleged suicide note, quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, and identified a federal judge/court-file release.\\n\\nThe strongest not-demonstrated path is that those same outlets used hedging language, reported lack of independent verification or official authentication, and left uncertainty about whether the note was intended as a suicide note rather than another communication later characterized as one.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Initial official-source limitations map\\n# Official source record\\n\\n## Market-specified resolution source\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule specifies no government docket, agency, publisher, or single official source. The exact source rule is:\\n\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Official public-record materials identified during minimal case setup\\n\\nThis packet is for an open-record/search-enabled run. I did not build a closed-record evidence packet. The public record identified during setup indicates that U.S. District Judge Kenneth M. Karas of the Southern District of New York unsealed a one-page note in connection with the Nicholas Tartaglione criminal case, after a New York Times request.\\n\\nLocal source capture of the court PDF/order is not included. The available captured public reporting says:\\n\\n- BBC reported that Judge Karas ordered release of the document, that the note was accompanied by a May 2021 letter submitted by former Tartaglione lawyer John A. Wieder, and that Karas wrote that public access to the note promotes accountability and public confidence in the administration of justice.\\n- Reuters reported that Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody.\\n- NPR reported that District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from The New York Times.\\n\\n## Official-source limitations\\n\\n- The source rule does not require an official release. It permits a qualifying note to be made public officially, by leak, or by other disclosure.\\n- The local packet does not contain the SDNY docket entry, order, or note image as a primary court PDF. Attorneys in the open-record run should search for those documents.\\n- Public reporting preserved here states that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide intent.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 SDNY May 6 unsealing order extraction\\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\\n\\nCaption and opening: \\\"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\\\"\\n\\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \\\"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\\\"\\n\\nBackground: \\\"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\\\"\\n\\nThe Times request: \\\"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\\\"\\n\\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\\n\\nPublic-access analysis: \\\"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\\\"\\n\\nThe order further concludes: \\\"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\\\"\\n\\nAnd: \\\"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\\\"\\n\\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Reuters Connect SDNY handout caption metadata\\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nPage heading: \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nCaption text: \\\"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\\\"\\n\\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-6 PBS/AP May 6-7 report extraction\\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\\\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\\n\\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\\n\\nHeadline: \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\\\"\\n\\nIt reports that \\\"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\\n\\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\" and says it continued, \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye,\\\" followed by \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\" The article says the note concludes: \\\"NO FUN\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \\\"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\\\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-7 Guardian May 6 report extraction\\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\\\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\\n\\nHeadline/subhead: \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\\\"; \\\"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\\n\\nThe article's image caption identifies: \\\"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the note: \\\"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\\\" and \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"The note does not include a signature.\\\" It also states: \\\"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\\\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-1 AP/DOJ authentication and source-chain limits\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-2 SDNY order shows public-access ruling, alleged/purported framing\\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\\n\\nCaption and opening: \\\"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\\\"\\n\\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \\\"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\\\"\\n\\nBackground: \\\"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\\\"\\n\\nThe Times request: \\\"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\\\"\\n\\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\\n\\nPublic-access analysis: \\\"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\\\"\\n\\nThe order further concludes: \\\"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\\\"\\n\\nAnd: \\\"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\\\"\\n\\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-3 PBS/AP preserves uncertainty and government-report omissions\\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\\\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\\n\\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\\n\\nHeadline: \\\"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\\\"\\n\\nIt reports that \\\"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\\n\\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\" and says it continued, \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye,\\\" followed by \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\" The article says the note concludes: \\\"NO FUN\\\" and \\\"NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \\\"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\\\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-4 Guardian preserves no-signature and no-verification caveats\\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\\\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\\n\\nHeadline/subhead: \\\"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\\\"; \\\"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\\\"\\n\\nThe article reports: \\\"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\\\"\\n\\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\\n\\nThe article's image caption identifies: \\\"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the note: \\\"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\\\" and \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \\\"The note does not include a signature.\\\" It also states: \\\"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\\\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\\n\\n[defendant] DB-5 Reuters Connect caption and third-party image limitations\\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nPage heading: \\\"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\\\"\\n\\nCaption text: \\\"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\\\"\\n\\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\\n\\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 AP/DOJ authentication-limit report in context\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\n[defendant] DS-1 AP/DOJ source-chain and authentication limits\\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \\\"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\\\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\\n\\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \\\"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\\\"\\n\\nIt states: \\\"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \\\"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\\\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\\n\\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\\n\\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\\n\\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\\n\\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \\\"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\\\"; \\\"It is a treat to be able to choose\\\" the \\\"time to say goodbye\\\"; \\\"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\\\"; and \\\"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\\\"\\n\\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\\n\\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] SDNY May 6, 2026 Tartaglione unsealing order - relevant extracted text (ev_0ed0ef50e84e_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-0ed0ef50e84e)\\nSource: https://www.nysd.uscourts.gov/sites/default/files/2026-05/16cr832%20-%20Tartaglione%20Order%20-%2026.5.6.pdf\\nSHA-256: `0ed0ef50e84e5f90a63aeefcb840f628038958b10acf229c44b4babea0c133e9`\\nBytes: 2992\\nRelevance: Official court source for public release/unsealing. It proves the court granted access to the note and identifies it as a suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione attorneys; it also shows the order was about public access, not authenticity.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] PBS/AP May 6-7, 2026 report on Epstein note release - relevant extracted text (ev_757899113d89_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-757899113d89)\\nSource: https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/judge-releases-note-that-cellmate-says-he-found-after-epsteins-suspected-suicide-attempt\\nSHA-256: `757899113d8967676e74909d141f7d97d4735bd8d75a4af34fb3950b18d871e1`\\nBytes: 2552\\nRelevance: Corroborates that the note was publicly reported before May 8, 2026; identifies Judge Karas release, NYT petition, Tartaglione discovery claim, note language supporting final-message intent, and adverse uncertainty about authorship and government-report omissions.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 6, 2026 report on alleged Epstein suicide note - relevant extracted text (ev_be7a5dd8c524_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-be7a5dd8c524)\\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\\nSHA-256: `be7a5dd8c524bf01aaffc12daeeedace9153fd057fc82c3ada197c2b30db71ce`\\nBytes: 2014\\nRelevance: Independent mainstream public reporting before the May 8 deadline; describes first public availability, attributes image to U.S. District Judge/Southern District of New York, quotes note language, and preserves authorship caveats.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Reuters Connect May 6, 2026 image-caption record for Epstein note (ev_58561d19c453_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-58561d19c453)\\nSource: https://www.reutersconnect.com/item/document-described-as-a-suicide-note-purportedly-written-by-the-late-jeffrey-epstein/dGFnOnJldXRlcnMuY29tLDIwMjY6bmV3c21sX1JDMlQzTEFMMEM2Ng\\nSHA-256: `58561d19c4537e7f3ade428fefe955b34c55ca688a331faa72187770ee5c8716`\\nBytes: 1360\\nRelevance: Near-primary image-caption record from Reuters/SDNY handout. It directly describes the publicly released document image, includes the key goodbye line, dates the release to May 6, 2026, and identifies the source as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] AP May 7, 2026 report: DOJ seeing Epstein note for first time and authentication limits (ev_5aa56aab2530_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-5aa56aab2530)\\nSource: https://apnews.com/article/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note-5297f49736e625a06d0db3c7b737b997\\nSHA-256: `5aa56aab25302158d1be6b80426ed4d517ee436cea958297c34e648148db2bca`\\nBytes: 2780\\nRelevance: Defense evidence on provenance, custody, and authentication. It reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, that the note came through an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, that it was in a court vault since 2021, and that DOJ lawyers involved in sealed proceedings could not disclose anything due to privilege restrictions.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Source search and capture ledger\\nBefore filing, plaintiff checked the current record and evidence list, reviewed the defendant opening, and targeted the missing source classes identified by the packet: official SDNY court material, the public image/caption record, and independent mainstream reporting. Searches used exact phrases including the note's reported goodbye line, Tartaglione/Karas/SDNY terms, and source-specific Reuters/PBS/Guardian queries. The official SDNY PDF was downloaded locally on 2026-06-30T04:33:49Z, size 128,992 bytes, sha256 7225441cb802084e2b9485ebc2c6d246fbfa08e109fe650cb14f445dc4745ca0; local pdftotext was unavailable, so a relevant text extraction was admitted instead. Reuters Connect metadata, PBS/AP, and Guardian extracts were admitted. Remaining gaps: no binary PDF exhibit, no licensed Reuters image download, no full NYT article capture, and no official authentication finding. These gaps affect actual authorship weight but do not defeat the reporting-standard proposition.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-search and evidence ledger\\nDefense re-scanned the record and read the four new plaintiff evidence extracts. Targeted investigation checked direct AP/DOJ source-chain reporting, NYT authentication follow-up leads, and media mirrors. The defense submitted the direct AP extraction as DB-1 because it preserved the strongest provenance and authentication limits: DOJ never had the note, it had not been authenticated, DOJ was seeing it for the first time, and any DOJ lawyers in sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings could not disclose protected material. Remaining unresolved gaps: no full NYT authentication article, no binary/unprocessed note image, no custodian affidavit, and no handwriting or official authorship finding.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T05:02:11.941771357Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":892433,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":17,\"version\":26}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","after_version":26,"case_id":"arb-ex08-20260630042402","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C4","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C4\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff's case is about the precise wording of the proposition, not about proving beyond doubt that Jeffrey Epstein actually wrote the document. The question is whether, by May 8, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a note or message had been made publicly available and had been credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. On the current packet, the answer is more likely than not yes.\n\nThe market rule preserved in the packet is important. It does not demand a definitive handwriting authentication, a government finding, or a single official resolution source. It asks for a message or note that was publicly available, credibly reported as Epstein's, and treated as a suicide note/final-message equivalent, with resolution by consensus credible reporting. That framing matters because the public record is cautious but not empty: the packet's reporting map identifies Reuters, NPR/AP, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times leads around the same court release.\n\nThe evidence we have now already shows the core chronology. A federal judge, Kenneth Karas of the Southern District of New York, unsealed or released a one-page note connected to Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's former cellmate. The reporting captured in the packet places that release before the May 8 deadline. Reuters described a document released by the judge as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein and quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye. NPR/AP reported that the judge unsealed the one-page note after a New York Times petition and quoted the same goodbye language. BBC and Guardian reporting likewise described an alleged or purported suicide note, publicly released by a federal judge, and described its contents in terms consistent with a final communication.\n\nThose reports are not marginal internet rumor. They are mainstream, named news organizations reporting on a court-unsealed document. The note's public availability is therefore the strongest element: multiple reports describe the court release itself before the deadline, and the Polymarket packet separately records that the market page understood the disputed question as the May 8 grouped market.\n\nThe hard issue is weight, not existence. The same packet preserves the caveats. The court did not vouch for authenticity. Several outlets used words like alleged or purported. NPR, BBC, and Guardian noted they had not independently verified authorship, and NPR/AP reported uncertainty about who wrote the note. The official-source file says the packet does not yet include the SDNY docket PDF, the unsealing order PDF, or the note image as local official exhibits. Those gaps should make the council cautious about any argument that Epstein's authorship has been conclusively proved.\n\nBut the proposition does not require conclusive proof of authorship. It requires that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Responsible hedging in credible reports does not erase credibility; it often demonstrates it. The reports identified a court release, a claimed source chain through Tartaglione and his lawyers, and the note text. That is enough at opening to frame the plaintiff's burden as a preponderance question: did credible public reporting, before May 8, make available and describe the note in the qualifying way? The packet points strongly toward yes.\n\nIntent is similar. The note need not be a formal, signed will or declaration. The rule allows a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, together with the context of Epstein's suspected July 2019 attempt and later death, is why credible outlets characterized it as a suicide note or alleged suicide note. The defense may argue the short, unsigned text is ambiguous. That is a fair limitation, but it does not defeat the more modest proposition that it was credibly reported as such.\n\nIn later evidentiary phases, the decisive documents should be added directly: the SDNY unsealing order and any released note image or court handout, the full Reuters/AP/Guardian/NYT materials, and the best adverse materials showing the limits of authentication and chain of custody. For now, the opening theory is straightforward: the record already shows a public court release before the deadline and a consensus of credible reporting that treated the document as a purported Epstein suicide or final-message note. The remaining disputes affect weight; they do not change the plaintiff's burden from preponderance into certainty.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the whole proposition, not merely that a provocative document was released by a court before May 8.\n\nThe record likely supports one element. The packet describes a public release or unsealing connected to Judge Kenneth Karas and the Tartaglione criminal case before the listed deadline. We do not need to pretend otherwise. But the market rule asks for more: a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The packet itself flags why those added elements are not established on this record.\n\nStart with provenance. The official-source packet says the local record does not contain the SDNY docket entry, unsealing order, or the released note image as a primary court exhibit. More importantly, it says the public reporting preserved here reports that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide its intent. Reuters, as summarized in the packet, reported that Judge Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody. That is a public-access ruling, not proof that the note was Epstein's.\n\nThe reporting evidence has the same problem. The packet's strongest plaintiff sources repeatedly use limiting words: purported, alleged, described as, said to have been found. NPR says it had not independently verified authenticity and adds a material DOJ limitation: the note had not yet been authenticated and this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. BBC likewise says it had not verified the note was written by Epstein and reports that authorities had not commented. Guardian says it had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. Those caveats are not incidental. They go directly to the proposition's phrase \"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nIntent is also unresolved. The packet quotes language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also preserves the rest of the reported text: complaints about being investigated, references to old charges, and emotional language about crying and not being worth it. The BBC summary says the note was only seven lines and left uncertainty over its purported meaning. A short, unsigned, unauthenticated text can be later characterized as a suicide note without having been shown to be intended as one. The rule includes final message or equivalent communication, but it still requires intent, not merely a news label attached after release.\n\nThe plaintiff will argue that consensus credible reporting is enough and that the rule does not require conclusive authentication. That is partly right but incomplete. The standard is preponderance, not certainty, and the source rule is credible reporting, not an official government determination. But credible reporting of uncertainty is still uncertainty. When the same credible reports say they cannot verify authorship, that DOJ had not authenticated it, and that the judge did not assess custody, the council should not convert cautious reporting into affirmative proof.\n\nThe current packet is best understood as a roadmap, not a completed proof. It identifies the sources that matter: the court order and docket material, the released note image, the full reporting from Reuters, NPR, BBC, Guardian, and New York Times, and especially any authentication follow-up. Those materials may eventually show whether there was enough consensus to resolve yes. But at opening, the defense theory is that the admitted packet proves a public dispute over an alleged note, while leaving the decisive links missing: authorship, chain of custody, and intent. If those links remain missing, the proposition should not be found proved by a preponderance.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the admitted record now proves the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nStart with the governing condition. PX-1 states the market would resolve yes if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication, was made publicly available by the listed date, and that the resolution source would be a consensus of credible reporting. The rule does not require a handwriting trial, a DOJ authentication letter, or an official source as the only path. It asks whether there was credible public reporting of the qualifying note by May 8, 2026.\n\nPublic availability is established. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, is an official court source. Judge Karas described the requested item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The order granted the Times' request to unseal the Note and held that it was a judicial document subject to public access. PX-5 then supplies the Reuters Connect image-caption record: a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye was seen after release by Judge Karas in New York City on May 6, 2026, with the source identified as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters. PX-6 and PX-7 independently report the same public release on May 6, before the May 8 deadline.\n\nCredible reporting of Epstein authorship is also established, in the exact qualified sense the proposition uses. PX-5 describes the document as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein. PX-6 reports that Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found the note after Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and that Karas ordered its release after the Times sought unsealing. PX-7 reports a federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein and identifies the alleged note image as from the United States district judge/Southern District of New York. These are not anonymous posts or market chatter; they are an official court order plus Reuters metadata, AP/PBS, and Guardian reporting.\n\nIntent is satisfied by both text and reporting context. PX-5 identifies the key line: \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.\" PX-6 reports the same language and the surrounding statements, including \"NO FUN\" and \"NOT WORTH IT!!\" PX-7 likewise quotes the goodbye language and describes the release as an alleged suicide note. The rule allows not only a formal suicide note but also a final message or equivalent communication. A short note saying it is a treat to choose one's time to say goodbye, reported in connection with Epstein's suspected suicide attempt and later death, easily crosses the preponderance threshold for being credibly reported as a suicide/final-message equivalent.\n\nThe defense is right about one thing: the record does not conclusively authenticate the note as Epstein's handwriting. The plaintiff does not need to hide that. PX-3 and the newly admitted sources preserve the limitations. PX-4 is a public-access order, not a handwriting finding. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports, and that Epstein had reportedly accused Tartaglione. PX-7 says the note lacks a signature and that Guardian had not independently verified authorship. Those caveats would matter if the proposition asked, \"Did Epstein actually write an authenticated suicide note?\" It does not.\n\nThe actual proposition asks whether a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, and whether it had been made public by the deadline. Hedged words like alleged and purported are not fatal under that standard; they are how responsible outlets report an attributed document whose authenticity has not been finally adjudicated. The credible-reporting consensus is that a court-released document, sourced to SDNY/Reuters handout and reported by AP/PBS and Guardian, was publicly available on May 6 and was described as an Epstein suicide note or alleged suicide note.\n\nThe missing links therefore reduce certainty about actual authorship, not the reporting-standard proposition. By May 8, the public had the court release and mainstream reporting describing the note in qualifying terms. On this record, yes is more likely than no.\n\n[defendant] Council members, after plaintiff's new evidence, the defense does not contest the easy part: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. The question is whether the record proves the qualifying proposition as written: a note credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The record still falls short.\n\nThe plaintiff's best evidence proves public access, not authenticity. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, describes the item as an alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. The court's legal holding was that the Note was subject to the presumption of public access because it had been submitted in connection with a Curcio hearing in Tartaglione's case. That explains why the public could see it. It does not decide who wrote it, whether its custody was reliable, or what the writer intended.\n\nThe source chain is unusually weak for a preponderance finding on authorship. The asserted chain is not Epstein to jail officials to investigators. It is Tartaglione, a convicted murderer and Epstein's former cellmate, saying he found a note in a book, then giving it to his lawyers, after which it became part of sealed attorney-client/conflict proceedings in Tartaglione's case. DB-1, the direct AP report, adds the central official limitation: DOJ's explanation was that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. AP also reports that if DOJ lawyers saw material in the sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings, they were barred from disclosing it. That is not just a missing authentication stamp; it is a source-chain problem.\n\nThe mainstream reports do not create the consensus plaintiff needs. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in the government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's recent files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. PX-5, the Reuters Connect caption, is useful proof that an image/caption circulated, but it expressly calls the image third-party supplied and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version elsewhere. A caption saying \"purportedly written\" is not a finding that credible reporting established authorship.\n\nPlaintiff says hedged words like alleged and purported are normal reporting practice. Sometimes they are. Here they are doing real evidentiary work. Every key source preserved in the record either avoids endorsing authorship or reports affirmative reasons for doubt: no signature, no authentication, DOJ had not seen it, no appearance in official Epstein-death reports, no appearance in DOJ's files release, and a chain originating with Tartaglione. The proposition uses the phrase \"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein.\" On this record, the credible reporting consensus is that a note was claimed or described as Epstein's, while authorship remained unresolved.\n\nIntent is no stronger. The reported text includes a line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, but it also includes complaints about investigations, old charges, crying, \"NO FUN,\" and \"NOT WORTH IT.\" DB-1 describes the note as short, hard to decipher in places, and not authenticated. PX-6 and PX-7 connect it to Epstein's July 2019 suspected attempt, but the same record says Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, later recanted, and was placed briefly on suicide watch before being downgraded. A later news label of \"suicide note\" cannot substitute for proof that this unsigned ambiguous document was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\n\nThis is not an argument for certainty as the standard. It is an argument for applying all elements of the rule. The plaintiff has shown public availability and public controversy. It has shown that several credible outlets responsibly repeated a characterization while preserving doubts. It has not shown that the consensus of credible reporting made it more likely than not that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying suicide/final-message communication.\n\nThe council should weigh plaintiff's exhibits for what they actually prove. PX-4 proves unsealing. PX-5 proves a Reuters/SDNY handout caption. PX-6 and PX-7 prove timely public reporting, but also preserve the core doubts. DB-1 gives the most direct official-source-chain limit: DOJ never had it, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. On the complete record, the proposition remains unproved by a preponderance.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense argument proves too much by quietly changing the question.\n\nThe proposition does not ask whether a court, DOJ, or handwriting expert finally authenticated Epstein's authorship. It asks whether, by May 8, a publicly available note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. That is why PX-1 makes consensus credible reporting the resolution source. The defense's evidence attacks a different proposition: actual authorship certainty.\n\nPX-R1 is useful, but not in the way the defense claims. It says DOJ never had the note, that it had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. Those facts explain why careful outlets used words like alleged and purported. They do not erase the fact that AP, Reuters Connect, Guardian, and the SDNY order all publicly described the same court-released item in the qualifying terms before the deadline.\n\nIndeed, PX-R1 confirms several plaintiff points. It says the note was made public, that The New York Times petitioned Judge Karas to release it, that Judge Karas agreed, and that DOJ did not object. It repeats Tartaglione's claim that he found the handwritten note after Epstein was found in their cell with a bedsheet around his neck. It gives the reported text, including choosing the time to say goodbye. That is not proof against credible reporting; it is another credible report that the note existed, was released, and was being publicly reported in the suicide-note frame.\n\nThe defense says the source chain is weak because it runs through Tartaglione and his lawyers. That would be decisive if the question required the council to find, as a historical fact, that Epstein wrote it. But the actual standard is whether the note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein. Qualified reporting is still reporting. When multiple mainstream sources identify a court-released document as a purported or alleged Epstein suicide note, while openly preserving authentication caveats, the word \"purported\" does not nullify credibility. It defines the level of claim being credibly reported.\n\nThe same is true of intent. The defense isolates ambiguity in the short text, but the admitted reports did not label a random note after the fact. They described a document found after a suspected jail suicide attempt, released by a federal judge, containing the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye. Under a rule that includes final message or equivalent communication, that is enough for credible reporting of intent by a preponderance.\n\nSo the council can accept every defense caveat and still find for plaintiff. No official authentication; no signature; source-chain limits; DOJ first saw it in 2026. Those are reasons not to overstate actual authorship. They are not reasons to deny the narrower proposition that, by May 8, a publicly available note had been credibly reported as a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The record satisfies that proposition.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal says the defense is demanding actual-authorship certainty. That is not our position. The rule does not require a handwriting trial. But it does require more than credible reporting that someone claimed, labeled, or captioned a document as an alleged Epstein suicide note.\n\nPX-1 asks whether a qualifying note was written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note/final message/equivalent, with credible reporting as the resolution source. The phrase \"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein\" cannot mean \"credibly reported to have been alleged or purported to be written by Epstein\" no matter how weak the source chain is. Otherwise the authorship requirement vanishes.\n\nThat is why DB-1/PX-R1 matters. Plaintiff treats it as harmless context for cautious wording. It is more than that. AP reports the government's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits on any DOJ lawyers in those proceedings. Those facts bear directly on whether the reporting consensus established Epstein authorship, not merely whether conclusive proof was absent.\n\nThe same point applies to intent. A line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the record also shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned document with grievance language and a disputed jail incident involving Tartaglione. The public reports responsibly used the suicide-note frame while preserving that uncertainty. That is not the same as a preponderance showing that the note was intended as a suicide note or final message.\n\nSo the defense is not asking the council to ignore credible reporting. We ask the council to read it accurately. The consensus is: a court released a document before May 8; credible outlets reported it as alleged or purported; and the same record preserved serious authorship, custody, and intent caveats. That proves public availability of a disputed document. It does not prove the full qualifying proposition by a preponderance.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition should be found true by a preponderance.\n\nThe defense ultimately concedes the first and most concrete element: a document was publicly released before the May 8 deadline. That concession is compelled by the record. PX-4, the SDNY order extraction, shows Judge Karas granted access to the Note. PX-5, the Reuters Connect/SDNY handout caption, dates the released document image to May 6, 2026. PX-6 and PX-7 report the release the same day. There is no serious timing dispute left.\n\nThe real dispute is what level of certainty the proposition requires. The defense asks you to treat missing official authentication as fatal. But PX-1 does not make authentication the test. It sets a reporting-standard market: the source is consensus credible reporting, and the operative phrase here is that a note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\n\nThat standard is satisfied. PX-4 identifies the court-filed item as a suicide note purportedly authored by Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys. PX-5 describes the released image as a document including the line about choosing one's time to say goodbye, described as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein, sourced to U.S. District Court/SDNY handout via Reuters. PX-6, AP/PBS, reports the public release, the Tartaglione discovery account, and the same goodbye language. PX-7, Guardian, independently reports the federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Epstein, quotes the same text, and identifies the image as from the Southern District of New York.\n\nThat is not one stray allegation. It is an official court-access order plus Reuters image metadata and two independent mainstream reports, all before the deadline, all describing the same public document in substantially the same qualifying frame.\n\nThe defense's best contrary evidence, DB-1/PX-R1, is important but not dispositive. It says DOJ never had the note, had not authenticated it, and was seeing it for the first time. It explains why the reports used careful words like alleged and purported. It does not erase the reports. In fact, it confirms the public release, the New York Times petition, Judge Karas's agreement, DOJ's non-objection, Tartaglione's discovery claim, and the note language.\n\nSo the council can accept every caveat and still answer yes. No signature; no official authentication; unclear actual authorship; source-chain limits through Tartaglione and his lawyers. Those are reasons to avoid saying \"Epstein definitely wrote it.\" The proposition does not ask for that. It asks whether the note had been publicly available and credibly reported as Epstein's suicide/final-message note. The record shows that it had.\n\nIntent is proved at the same reporting-standard level. The note's reported language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, its connection to Epstein's suspected July 2019 jail suicide attempt, and repeated public characterization as a suicide note or alleged suicide note are enough for a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. The defense can point to ambiguity in the short text, but preponderance does not require eliminating ambiguity; it requires the more likely reading of the admitted record.\n\nIf the rule had required official authentication, the defense would have the stronger case. But that is not the rule. Under the actual wording and the evidence admitted here, the plaintiff has shown public availability by May 8 and a consensus of credible, qualified reporting that the document was a purported Epstein suicide/final-message note. The proposition is more likely true than false.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the final record proves one thing clearly: a document was publicly released before May 8. The defense has never needed to deny that. The proposition, however, asks for more. It asks whether a message or note had been made public and had been credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication. Plaintiff has not carried that full burden.\n\nThe best way to see the gap is to compare plaintiff's closing formulation to the actual rule. Plaintiff closes by saying the record shows a publicly available note was credibly reported as a \"purported Epstein suicide/final-message note.\" But \"reported as purported\" is not the proposition. The proposition requires credible reporting that the note was written by Epstein and intended as the qualifying communication. The word \"purported\" matters because the sources used it to preserve uncertainty, not to resolve it.\n\nThe record evidence repeatedly stops short of plaintiff's needed inference. PX-4 is an official court-access order, but it describes an alleged note purportedly authored by Epstein and decides public access, not authorship, custody, or intent. PX-5 is a Reuters Connect caption for a third-party supplied, Reuters-processed image; it confirms circulation and a caption, not authenticity. PX-6 says it is unclear who wrote the note, that it was not mentioned in government reports examining Epstein's death, and that it did not surface in DOJ's files release. PX-7 says the note has no signature and that the Guardian had not verified whether Epstein wrote it.\n\nDB-1/PX-R1 is the strongest limiting evidence. AP reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, and that DOJ was seeing it for the first time. It also places the note in an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, in a court vault since 2021, with disclosure limits from sealed proceedings. That is not a minor caveat. It is the central provenance problem.\n\nIntent is likewise not proved by a preponderance. The line about choosing one's time to say goodbye is relevant, but the same record shows a short, hard-to-decipher, unsigned note with grievance language, a disputed jail incident, and no authentication. Labeling that document a suicide note in headlines or captions does not establish that it was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\n\nThe defense is not asking for certainty or an official authentication requirement. We are asking the council to enforce all words of the proposition. Credible reporting can be the resolution source, but the reporting here is credible precisely because it preserves the unresolved issues: alleged, purported, unclear author, no signature, not verified, not in government death reports, not in DOJ files, not authenticated, and first seen by DOJ only after release.\n\nSo the right finding is narrow and faithful to the record: by May 8, a disputed document was publicly available and credibly reported as an alleged or purported Epstein suicide note. That is not enough. The full proposition remains more likely unproved than proved, and the council should answer no.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and May 8 market record\n# Polymarket market record\n\nCaptured for case preparation on 2026-05-12.\n\n## Real market link\n\nCanonical event page:\nhttps://polymarket.com/event/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\n\nPolymarket Gamma API endpoints captured under `etc/source-captures/`:\n\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-event-slug.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events/slug/epstein-suicide-note-released-by\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-events-query.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-8.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8\n- `etc/source-captures/gamma-market-may-31.json` — https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/markets?slug=epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-next-data-relevant.json` — sanitized relevant `__NEXT_DATA__` extract.\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — page/API text extract.\n- `etc/source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt` — sanitized relevant HTML extract. Full page HTML was not retained because the page includes unnecessary discussion/profile data.\n\n## Event metadata from Polymarket Gamma API\n\n- Event id: `435920`\n- Ticker/slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by`\n- Title: `Epstein suicide note released by...?`\n- Start date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.609296Z`\n- Creation date: `2026-04-30T23:14:22.60929Z`\n- Event end date: `2026-05-31T00:00:00Z`\n- Active: `true`\n- Closed: `false`\n- Archived: `false`\n- Restricted: `true`\n- Captured volume: about `13373621.098375008`\n- Captured open interest: about `8163953.4680470005`\n- Event metadata context captured by Polymarket on 2026-05-12 stated that a U.S. District Judge in New York unsealed a purported suicide note attributed to Jeffrey Epstein on May 7, 2026, but also described authenticity and intent doubts. This platform context is preserved as market metadata, not as independent proof of the proposition.\n\n## Exact official market rule text\n\nThe Polymarket page and Gamma API expose this description:\n\n> This market will resolve to “Yes” if any message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, is made publicly available by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n>\n> A qualifying note must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and have been intended to be a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\n>\n> A qualifying message or note may be made widely available to the public by any means, regardless of whether it is released officially, leaked, or otherwise disclosed.\n>\n> The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Market at issue for this arbitration\n\nPrimary disputed market:\n\n- Market id: `2128535`\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 8?`\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-8`\n- Condition id: `0x5e5482b1e2afa7bed0b9a0c3c8ad33a83dd6cc6d649666cdf1977be64c42c82a`\n- Question id: `0x5ca4d636407564494e9149eb951896ff88923cef8d24c137707e4cff84b4d878`\n- Group item title: `May 8`\n- Outcomes: `[\"Yes\", \"No\"]`\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\"0.0005\", \"0.9995\"]`\n- Active: `true`\n- Closed: `false`\n- Accepting orders: `true`\n- UMA resolution status in API: `disputed`\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]`\n- Page-visible status captured from HTML/readable extraction: `Outcome proposed: Yes`; `Disputed`; `Outcome proposed: No`; `Disputed`; `Final review`.\n\nThe API field `endDateIso` is `2026-05-31` because the event contains both May 8 and May 31 grouped markets. For the May 8 market, the listed date in the market question and group item is May 8. The arbitration proposition therefore uses May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\n## Other grouped market preserved for context\n\nSecondary grouped market, not the disputed condition tested here:\n\n- Market id: `2128536`\n- Question: `Epstein suicide note released by May 31?`\n- Slug: `epstein-suicide-note-released-by-may-31`\n- Condition id: `0x6bf3aa7d5186804e967e1e4737c896778f688e6dafdd0a1b659a4a07bf27d663`\n- Group item title: `May 31`\n- Outcomes: `[\"Yes\", \"No\"]`\n- Captured outcome prices: `[\"0.145\", \"0.855\"]`\n- Active: `true`\n- Closed: `false`\n- Accepting orders: `true`\n- UMA resolution-status history in API: `[]`\n\n## Arbitration framing\n\nThe arbitration does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any market participant was correct. It asks the factual condition directly: whether the qualifying note/message had been publicly available by the May 8 listed deadline under the rule words.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Initial primary/near-primary reporting map\n# Primary and near-primary evidence map\n\nThis is a minimal open-record source map, not a closed-record exhibit packet.\n\n## Reuters\n\nURL: https://www.reuters.com/world/us/new-york-judge-releases-purported-epstein-suicide-note-2026-05-07/\n\nCaptured excerpt:\n\n> May 6 (Reuters) - A federal judge on Wednesday released a document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein and including the line: \"It is a treat to be able to choose one’s time to say goodbye.\"\n>\n> The handwritten note was said to have been found by his former jail cellmate, convicted murderer and ex‑police officer Nicholas Tartaglione. U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas, who oversaw the Tartaglione case, released the note after a request by The New York Times, which reported its existence last week.\n>\n> The judge found no legal reason to keep it under seal. But nor did he vouch for the note's authenticity, nor assess its chain of custody.\n\nReuters also quoted the note text as released in the court file:\n\n> \"They investigated me for month - Found NOTHING!!! So 15 year old charges resulted,” the note says, according to an image of it released in the court file. \"It is a treat to be able to choose ones time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Burst out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\n## NPR\n\nURL: https://www.npr.org/2026/05/07/nx-s1-5814808/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note\n\nCaptured excerpt:\n\n> District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from the New York Times, which reported on its existence last week.\n>\n> NPR has not independently verified the authenticity of the note. The five sentences on a sheet of lined paper read in part: \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do — Bust out cryin!! NO FUN — NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nNPR also reported a material authentication limitation:\n\n> The Department of Justice told NPR over email on Thursday that the note has not yet been authenticated, adding, \"this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well.\"\n\n## BBC\n\nURL: https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cd7pd0rqwreo\n\nCaptured excerpt:\n\n> A US judge has ordered the release of a document purported to be a suicide note written by convicted sex offender Jeffrey Epstein a month before his death.\n>\n> A copy of the handwritten note unsealed on Wednesday mentions a months-long investigation that \"found nothing\", and says \"it is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye\".\n>\n> The BBC has not verified that the note was written by Epstein, and US authorities have not commented.\n\nBBC also reported:\n\n> The note amounts to only seven lines of text, leaving uncertainty over its purported meaning.\n\n## Guardian\n\nURL: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\n\nCaptured excerpt:\n\n> A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\n>\n> Epstein’s cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, Nicholas Tartaglione, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before he was eventually found dead in his jail cell.\n>\n> The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return the Guardian’s request for comment.\n\n## Notes for advocates\n\nThe strongest pro-demonstrated path is that multiple credible outlets reported public release before May 8, described the document as a purported/alleged suicide note, quoted language about choosing one's time to say goodbye, and identified a federal judge/court-file release.\n\nThe strongest not-demonstrated path is that those same outlets used hedging language, reported lack of independent verification or official authentication, and left uncertainty about whether the note was intended as a suicide note rather than another communication later characterized as one.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Initial official-source limitations map\n# Official source record\n\n## Market-specified resolution source\n\nThe Polymarket rule specifies no government docket, agency, publisher, or single official source. The exact source rule is:\n\n> The resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Official public-record materials identified during minimal case setup\n\nThis packet is for an open-record/search-enabled run. I did not build a closed-record evidence packet. The public record identified during setup indicates that U.S. District Judge Kenneth M. Karas of the Southern District of New York unsealed a one-page note in connection with the Nicholas Tartaglione criminal case, after a New York Times request.\n\nLocal source capture of the court PDF/order is not included. The available captured public reporting says:\n\n- BBC reported that Judge Karas ordered release of the document, that the note was accompanied by a May 2021 letter submitted by former Tartaglione lawyer John A. Wieder, and that Karas wrote that public access to the note promotes accountability and public confidence in the administration of justice.\n- Reuters reported that Karas released the note, treated it as a judicial document subject to public access, found no legal reason to keep it sealed, and did not vouch for authenticity or assess chain of custody.\n- NPR reported that District Judge Kenneth Karas unsealed the one-page note Wednesday in response to a legal petition from The New York Times.\n\n## Official-source limitations\n\n- The source rule does not require an official release. It permits a qualifying note to be made public officially, by leak, or by other disclosure.\n- The local packet does not contain the SDNY docket entry, order, or note image as a primary court PDF. Attorneys in the open-record run should search for those documents.\n- Public reporting preserved here states that the court unsealed the note but did not authenticate it as Epstein's writing or decide intent.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 SDNY May 6 unsealing order extraction\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\n\nCaption and opening: \"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\"\n\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\"\n\nBackground: \"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\"\n\nThe Times request: \"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\"\n\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\n\nPublic-access analysis: \"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\"\n\nThe order further concludes: \"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\"\n\nAnd: \"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\"\n\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Reuters Connect SDNY handout caption metadata\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nPage heading: \"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nCaption text: \"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\"\n\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-6 PBS/AP May 6-7 report extraction\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\n\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\n\nHeadline: \"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\"\n\nThe article reports: \"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\"\n\nIt reports that \"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\"\n\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\n\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\" and says it continued, \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye,\" followed by \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\" The article says the note concludes: \"NO FUN\" and \"NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\"\n\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-7 Guardian May 6 report extraction\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\n\nHeadline/subhead: \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\"; \"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\"\n\nThe article reports: \"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\"\n\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\n\nThe article's image caption identifies: \"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\"\n\nThe article quotes the note: \"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\" and \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \"The note does not include a signature.\" It also states: \"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\n\n[defendant] DB-1 AP/DOJ authentication and source-chain limits\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\n\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\"\n\nIt states: \"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\"\n\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\n\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\n\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\n\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\n\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\"; \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye\"; \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\"; and \"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\n\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\n\n[defendant] DB-2 SDNY order shows public-access ruling, alleged/purported framing\nRelevant extracted text from SDNY official PDF, United States v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, U.S.D.J.:\n\nCaption and opening: \"UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK ... UNITED STATES OF AMERICA v. NICHOLAS TARTAGLIONE, Defendant. Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK) ORDER KENNETH M. KARAS, United States District Judge.\"\n\nThe order states that The New York Times filed a request to unseal certain materials and that, \"for reasons set forth below, the Court determines that the Times' request to unseal an alleged 'suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'),' ... should be granted.\"\n\nBackground: \"As has been widely reported, while Defendant was awaiting trial in his criminal case, he was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.\"\n\nThe Times request: \"On April 30, 2026, the Court received a request from the Times seeking certain materials that, the Times claimed, were filed under seal in the proceedings in this case. ... The Times sought access to four sets of documents: (1) A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note'); (2) The report by Bobbi Sternheim, Curcio counsel for Mr. Tartaglione ...; (3) The transcripts ...; and (4) The March 1, 2021[] order ...\"\n\nThe order records the Times' position that Tartaglione repeatedly referenced the Note in public interviews and that a Department of Justice document referenced the Note, with the Times taking the position there was no basis for continued blanket sealing.\n\nPublic-access analysis: \"Accordingly, as to the Note, the Court concludes that it is subject to the presumption of public access. The Note was submitted in connection with the Curcio hearing, which involved the exercise of Article III power to make a determination as to Defendant's right to conflict-free counsel, and the Note was at least relevant to 'judicial decision-making,' regardless of whether the Court relied on it in reaching its conclusion.\"\n\nThe order further concludes: \"The Court comfortably concludes that public access to the Note promotes 'a measure of accountability' as well as ensures that the public will 'have confidence in the administration of justice.'\"\n\nAnd: \"Finally, no Party has identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note ... The Court agrees with the Parties' position that Defendant's repeated public discussion about the Note's contents constitutes waiver of the attorney-client privilege as to the document.\"\n\nExtraction/custody note: This is a relevant-text extraction, not the binary PDF. It preserves the official URL, retrieval timestamp, local download size/hash, and the extraction limitation that local pdftotext was unavailable.\n\n[defendant] DB-3 PBS/AP preserves uncertainty and government-report omissions\nRelevant extracted text from PBS NewsHour/AP article, \"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt,\" published May 6, 2026 8:01 PM EDT and updated May 7, 2026 5:36 PM EDT.\n\nByline: Michael R. Sisak, Associated Press; Larry Neumeister, Associated Press.\n\nHeadline: \"Judge releases note that cellmate says he found after Epstein's suspected suicide attempt.\"\n\nThe article reports: \"NEW YORK (AP) — A note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claimed he found after the millionaire sex offender's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public Wednesday, years after being sealed and locked in a courthouse vault as part of an unrelated legal dispute.\"\n\nIt reports that \"U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in White Plains, New York, ordered the release of the note after The New York Times asked him last week to unseal it and other documents in a case involving the former cellmate, Nicholas Tartaglione. Federal prosecutors did not oppose the request.\"\n\nIt states that Tartaglione said he discovered the note in a book after Epstein was found on the floor of their cell at a Manhattan federal jail on July 23, 2019 with a strip of bedsheet around his neck, about three weeks before Epstein was found dead in what authorities concluded was a suicide.\n\nThe article quotes/reads the note in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\" and says it continued, \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye,\" followed by \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\" The article says the note concludes: \"NO FUN\" and \"NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nThe article identifies the image caption as: \"A note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein and released by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, on May 6, 2026. Image via U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\"\n\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found. It wasn't mentioned in the lengthy government reports examining the circumstances of Epstein's death, nor did it surface in the Justice Department's recent release of files on the late financier.\" It also reports that jail records said Epstein had neck marks and that one officer reported Epstein said he believed Tartaglione had tried to kill him.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves publication/update dates, byline, source URL, and both favorable and adverse article content.\n\n[defendant] DB-4 Guardian preserves no-signature and no-verification caveats\nRelevant extracted text from The Guardian, \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge,\" by Mollie Reilly and Uwa Ede-Osifo, first published Wed 6 May 2026 19:11 EDT and updated/published 20:44 EDT.\n\nHeadline/subhead: \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\"; \"Epstein's cellmate in New York City says he found note after convicted sexual offender attempted suicide in July 2019.\"\n\nThe article reports: \"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\"\n\nIt states that Nicholas Tartaglione, Epstein's cellmate at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City, said he found the note after Epstein unsuccessfully attempted suicide in July 2019, weeks before Epstein was found dead in his jail cell.\n\nThe article's image caption identifies: \"The alleged Epstein suicide note. Photograph: United States district judge, southern district of New York.\"\n\nThe article quotes the note: \"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\" and \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAdverse/limiting points preserved by the same article: \"The note does not include a signature.\" It also states: \"The Guardian has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein. The justice department did not immediately return The Guardian's request for comment.\" The article further reports that the note was unsealed after The New York Times published on the note's existence and petitioned the court to release it, and that federal records reflected Epstein had told prison officials he had been attacked by Tartaglione while Epstein maintained he was not suicidal.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant article-text extraction, not a full HTML archive. It preserves source URL, publication timestamp, byline, quoted note language, and the article's authentication caveats.\n\n[defendant] DB-5 Reuters Connect caption and third-party image limitations\nRelevant extracted text from Reuters Connect page titled \"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nPage heading: \"Document described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n\nCaption text: \"A document including the line 'It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.', described as a suicide note purportedly written by the late Jeffrey Epstein, the disgraced financier and accused sex trafficker who was found dead in his Manhattan jail cell in August 2019 in what was ruled a suicide, is seen after its release by U.S. District Judge Kenneth Karas in New York City, U.S. May 6, 2026. U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via REUTERS THIS IMAGE HAS BEEN SUPPLIED BY A THIRD PARTY. THIS IMAGE WAS PROCESSED BY REUTERS TO ENHANCE QUALITY, AN UNPROCESSED VERSION HAS BEEN PROVIDED SEPARATELY. TPX IMAGES OF THE DAY.\"\n\nDetails shown on page: Dimensions and size 2550 x 1700 / 741.2KB; credit via REUTERS; source REUTERS; USN RC2T3LAL0C66; byline U.S. District Court/SDNY.\n\nExtraction note: This is a relevant text extraction of the public Reuters Connect metadata/caption, not a licensed image download. The caption itself states the image was supplied by a third party and processed by Reuters, with an unprocessed version provided separately.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 AP/DOJ authentication-limit report in context\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\n\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\"\n\nIt states: \"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\"\n\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\n\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\n\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\n\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\n\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\"; \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye\"; \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\"; and \"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\n\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\n\n[defendant] DS-1 AP/DOJ source-chain and authentication limits\nRelevant extracted text from Associated Press article, \"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time,\" by Ed White, AP News, May 7, 2026.\n\nThe AP article reports that a note Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate claims he found after Epstein's first suspected jail suicide attempt was made public \"not because of the Justice Department's release of records related to the sex offender, but as part of an unrelated case.\"\n\nIt states: \"The government's explanation: It never had the note.\"\n\nThe article quotes the Justice Department: \"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,\" said the department when asked why it was not part of the voluminous Epstein files.\n\nThe article reports that Nicholas Tartaglione said he found the handwritten note in a book after Epstein was found in their cell with a strip of bedsheet around his neck; Epstein was later moved and later found dead. AP reports Tartaglione said he gave the note to his lawyers to protect himself against any claim that he might have harmed Epstein.\n\nThe article states that since 2021 the note had been in a vault in federal court in New York and somehow became part of proceedings between Tartaglione and his lawyers over their representation in his murder case, with anything related to that dispute sealed because it involved attorney-client privilege.\n\nAP reports that the New York Times petitioned Judge Kenneth Karas to release the note and that the judge agreed, citing Epstein's reduced privacy interests after death.\n\nAP describes the note as short, hard to decipher in some places, and not authenticated. It gives the reported text in relevant part: \"They investigated me for month -- found nothing!!!\"; \"It is a treat to be able to choose\" the \"time to say goodbye\"; \"Watcha want me to do -- Bust out cryin!!\"; and \"NO FUN. NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\nAP also reports jail-record context: Epstein had friction marks and skin irritation on his neck after the suspected July 23, 2019 suicide attempt; jail officers said he was breathing heavily but responsive; Epstein told a guard Tartaglione had attacked him, then later recanted. Epstein was placed on suicide watch for 31 hours, then downgraded to psychiatric observation before his August 10, 2019 death.\n\nThe article reports that DOJ did not object to release and that Deputy U.S. Attorney Sean Buckley said the public was interested in the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. It further reports Buckley said two DOJ lawyers were included in 2021 Tartaglione-attorney proceedings but were barred by the judge from disclosing anything from those hearings to protect attorney-client privilege, so if they saw the note, they were not allowed to tell anyone.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] SDNY May 6, 2026 Tartaglione unsealing order - relevant extracted text (ev_0ed0ef50e84e_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-0ed0ef50e84e)\nSource: https://www.nysd.uscourts.gov/sites/default/files/2026-05/16cr832%20-%20Tartaglione%20Order%20-%2026.5.6.pdf\nSHA-256: `0ed0ef50e84e5f90a63aeefcb840f628038958b10acf229c44b4babea0c133e9`\nBytes: 2992\nRelevance: Official court source for public release/unsealing. It proves the court granted access to the note and identifies it as a suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and submitted by Tartaglione attorneys; it also shows the order was about public access, not authenticity.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] PBS/AP May 6-7, 2026 report on Epstein note release - relevant extracted text (ev_757899113d89_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-757899113d89)\nSource: https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/judge-releases-note-that-cellmate-says-he-found-after-epsteins-suspected-suicide-attempt\nSHA-256: `757899113d8967676e74909d141f7d97d4735bd8d75a4af34fb3950b18d871e1`\nBytes: 2552\nRelevance: Corroborates that the note was publicly reported before May 8, 2026; identifies Judge Karas release, NYT petition, Tartaglione discovery claim, note language supporting final-message intent, and adverse uncertainty about authorship and government-report omissions.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 6, 2026 report on alleged Epstein suicide note - relevant extracted text (ev_be7a5dd8c524_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-be7a5dd8c524)\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/may/06/jeffrey-epstein-alleged-suicide-note\nSHA-256: `be7a5dd8c524bf01aaffc12daeeedace9153fd057fc82c3ada197c2b30db71ce`\nBytes: 2014\nRelevance: Independent mainstream public reporting before the May 8 deadline; describes first public availability, attributes image to U.S. District Judge/Southern District of New York, quotes note language, and preserves authorship caveats.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Reuters Connect May 6, 2026 image-caption record for Epstein note (ev_58561d19c453_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-58561d19c453)\nSource: https://www.reutersconnect.com/item/document-described-as-a-suicide-note-purportedly-written-by-the-late-jeffrey-epstein/dGFnOnJldXRlcnMuY29tLDIwMjY6bmV3c21sX1JDMlQzTEFMMEM2Ng\nSHA-256: `58561d19c4537e7f3ade428fefe955b34c55ca688a331faa72187770ee5c8716`\nBytes: 1360\nRelevance: Near-primary image-caption record from Reuters/SDNY handout. It directly describes the publicly released document image, includes the key goodbye line, dates the release to May 6, 2026, and identifies the source as U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York/Handout via Reuters.\n\n[defendant arguments] AP May 7, 2026 report: DOJ seeing Epstein note for first time and authentication limits (ev_5aa56aab2530_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-5aa56aab2530)\nSource: https://apnews.com/article/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note-5297f49736e625a06d0db3c7b737b997\nSHA-256: `5aa56aab25302158d1be6b80426ed4d517ee436cea958297c34e648148db2bca`\nBytes: 2780\nRelevance: Defense evidence on provenance, custody, and authentication. It reports DOJ's explanation that it never had the note, that the note had not yet been authenticated, that the note came through an unrelated Tartaglione attorney-client dispute, that it was in a court vault since 2021, and that DOJ lawyers involved in sealed proceedings could not disclose anything due to privilege restrictions.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Source search and capture ledger\nBefore filing, plaintiff checked the current record and evidence list, reviewed the defendant opening, and targeted the missing source classes identified by the packet: official SDNY court material, the public image/caption record, and independent mainstream reporting. Searches used exact phrases including the note's reported goodbye line, Tartaglione/Karas/SDNY terms, and source-specific Reuters/PBS/Guardian queries. The official SDNY PDF was downloaded locally on 2026-06-30T04:33:49Z, size 128,992 bytes, sha256 7225441cb802084e2b9485ebc2c6d246fbfa08e109fe650cb14f445dc4745ca0; local pdftotext was unavailable, so a relevant text extraction was admitted instead. Reuters Connect metadata, PBS/AP, and Guardian extracts were admitted. Remaining gaps: no binary PDF exhibit, no licensed Reuters image download, no full NYT article capture, and no official authentication finding. These gaps affect actual authorship weight but do not defeat the reporting-standard proposition.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-search and evidence ledger\nDefense re-scanned the record and read the four new plaintiff evidence extracts. Targeted investigation checked direct AP/DOJ source-chain reporting, NYT authentication follow-up leads, and media mirrors. The defense submitted the direct AP extraction as DB-1 because it preserved the strongest provenance and authentication limits: DOJ never had the note, it had not been authenticated, DOJ was seeing it for the first time, and any DOJ lawyers in sealed Tartaglione-attorney proceedings could not disclose protected material. Remaining unresolved gaps: no full NYT authentication article, no binary/unprocessed note image, no custodian affidavit, and no handwriting or official authorship finding.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T05:02:11.941771357Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":892433,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":17,"version":26}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782794839512}]}
